[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello, and welcome to this course! My name is Daniel King. I’m a Grandmaster. I have represented England on numerous occasions, but in the last few years you might know me better as a commentator on many of the chess world’s top events and through the videos I have created for my YouTube channel – Power Play Chess.I have proudly played the Sicilian with Black for most of my chess career – The Najdorf, The Sveshnikov and the Kalashnikov. I love the dynamism of the opening! My most notable scalp with the Sicilian was Vishy Anand, and this victory helped me to win the prestigious Goodricke Open in Calcutta 1992.Previously I have written three courses for Chessable: How Good Is Your Chess 1 and 2; and King’s Kalashnikov Sicilian. I decided to offer a repertoire with the Kalashnikov as there is considerably less theory to take in compared to other Sicilians, and because the pawn structure is relatively fixed, it is quite strategic in nature.Feedback has been very positive, but there has been a near constant cry from the beginning: what happens if my opponent avoids the open Sicilian? What about the Rossolimo? The Grand Prix Attack? The Morra Gambit?   It was quite clear that a course for Black on the Anti-Sicilians was necessary if everyone was to feel comfortable when going for the Kalashnikov. This course is designed for those who want to play the Kalashnikov, as well as for other Sicilian devotees. But be advised, I will only be covering @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  – not  2...d6  .This course provides a repertoire for Black against the Anti-Sicilian systems. I have played the Sicilian since I was around 12 years old, so these lines are very familiar to me and based on years of experience. Some people are disappointed when an Anti-Sicilian appears on the board: My attitude is always, ‘They are too chicken to go into an open Sicilian!’. The psychological battle has been won already. From the comments I have received on Chessable, the Rossolimo @@StartBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ seems to strike particular fear. It is certainly a sensible opening as White develops quickly, however, my recommendation of  3...Nf6  takes away much of its sting and is a system that I have found to be reliable throughout my career.The Alapin @@StartBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  @@EndBracket@@ is also sensible for White, and while there are several acceptable lines for Black @@StartBracket@@  2...d5  and  2...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@, I like to play in a straightforward way:  2...e6  and ...d5, countering in the middle of the board and not conceding territory. Black can often go on the offensive in the middlegame.As for the rest of White’s systems – they aren’t terribly impressive! The Morra Gambit one can accept with a clear conscience; the Grand Prix Attack often blows up in White’s face. The old Closed Sicilian – quite tame. Apart from the detailed repertoire, I have collated some model games that will enable you to get a handle on strategy, as well as serving as a reminder of some of the repertoire. Playing through complete games often aids the memory. Good luck! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Rossolimo: 4.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Rossolimo rightly has an excellent reputation. White brings out a piece and prepares to castle as quickly as possible. Very often the follow up is c3 and d4 attempting to set up a big pawn centre. Black must know how to fight that, and at the same time bring the king to safety. The task should not be underestimated.   The most popular continuations here are  3...g6  and  3...e6  , but I am recommending a move that cuts across White's plans. }
3... Nf6
{ Bringing out a piece and attacking the e-pawn. In this case, White does not have time to build up with c3 and d4. There are two main responses,  4.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@the most popular@@EndBracket@@ and  4.e5  .  Curiously, these variations can sometimes transpose into each other.In fact, there are so many different move orders available to White @@StartBracket@@which invariably lead to transpositions@@EndBracket@@ that understanding what you are aiming for is as necessary as learning the variations. Therefore I would strongly recommend looking at the model games section to complement your knowledge of variations here. }
4. Nc3
{ The most sensible move. The knight defends the e-pawn. However, notice that White is now unable to build a pawn centre with c3 and d4 - in that sense Black has already achieved something.   4.Bxc6  usually transposes to lines examined later on after  4...dxc6  5.d3  g6  6.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@for example@@EndBracket@@. See the line 4.Nc3 g6 5.  Bxc6 dxc6 6.h3, etc.   In general in the 3...Nf6 variation, be prepared for flexible move orders. That's why an understanding of typical manoeuvres is  particularly valuable, as well as knowing set lines.   After  4.Nc3  , at this point  4...Qc7  is the most popular response, but I would prefer not to bring out the queen at such an early stage in the game.  4...Nd4  has also been tried, but I find that too risky as it breaks a basic opening rule: do not move the same piece twice in the opening. Instead, let's continue developing. }
4... g6
{ If Black manages to fianchetto the bishop and get castled, the opening will have been concluded satisfactorily. White must cause some disruption. There are basically two ways to play - advance with e5, or don't advance!   The main continuations are  5.Bxc6  and  5.e5  , but  5.h3  should be checked out as Black reacts a little differently. @@StartBracket@@  5.O-O  Bg7  should transpose to one of these lines after  6.e5  or  6.Bxc6  . @@EndBracket@@ }
5. e5
{ The most direct move, attempting to disrupt Black's smooth development. We should pay the most attention to this continuation. }
5... Ng4 { The pawn on e5 is threatened, so White must take action. } 6. Bxc6
{ White will have to play this sooner or later. If  6.Qe2  Bg7  , the threat to the e-pawn forces White to play  7.Bxc6  and after  7...dxc6  there is a transposition to lines examined later. }
6... dxc6
{ In most cases, when White exchanges bishop for knight on c6, Black should recapture with the d-pawn. The bishop on c8 needs to come into play. }
7. h3 Nh6
{ The knight doesn't look well placed on the edge, but it's just a couple of steps from a beautiful outpost in the middle of the board: ...Nh6-f5-d4 - problem solved!Black's next moves are straightforward: ...Bg7, O-O, Nh6-f5-d4. White has a little more choice, but essentially there are two main decisions to take: castle kingside or queenside? Do you restrict the knight with g4?   At this point, White can play several moves.  8.g4  is the most popular, and  8.d3  ,  8.Ne4  , and  8.O-O  come in at roughly joint second in terms of frequency. There are often transpositions between these lines. For the sake of clarity, I will just be examining  8.g4  and  8.d3  . }
8. d3 { Here, I am going to consider lines where White castles kingside. } 8...
Bg7
{ At this point, White has a number of options.  9.Qe2  ,  9.Bf4  and  9.g4  will transpose to lines to be found elsewhere, or will lead into positions found after  9.O-O  . }
9. O-O O-O { The king is safely castled and the middlegame can begin. } 10. Re1
{ The rook belongs here and it is the most flexible move. } 10... Nf5
{ The knight heads for the outpost on d4. This manoeuvre recurs time and again in this variation and, in general, throughout our repertoire. }
11. Ne4
{ This is the most common move.  11.Bf4  Nd4  12.Ne4  b6  will transpose to the line 11.Ne4 b6 12.Bf4 Nd4. }
11... b6
{ At this point I am considering  12.c3  ,  12.b3  ,  12.Bf4  and  12.a4  . These represent the four major strategies for White when castling kingside. }
12. Bf4 Nd4
{ The knight reaches the outpost. Step 1 has been achieved. We will consider two different moves here:  13.c3  and  13.Nxd4  . Instead,  13.a4  will transpose to the line 12.a4 Nd4 13.Bf4. }
13. Nxd4 Qxd4
{ White has to look after the e5-pawn and the b2-pawn.  13...cxd4  is also playable. }
14. c3 Qd5
{ The queen has been pushed back, but as a consequence the d3-pawn has been weakened. }
15. d4 cxd4 16. cxd4 Rd8
{ Black has pressure on the d4 pawn and is already doing fine. Notice how the queen stands well on a light square in the middle of the board: White exchanged off that crucial bishop a long time ago! }
*

