1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Rossolimo rightly has an excellent reputation. White brings out a piece and prepares to castle as quickly as possible. Very often the follow up is c3 and d4 attempting to set up a big pawn centre. Black must know how to fight that, and at the same time bring the king to safety. The task should not be underestimated.   The most popular continuations here are  3...g6  and  3...e6  , but I am recommending a move that cuts across White's plans. }
3... Nf6
{ Bringing out a piece and attacking the e-pawn. In this case, White does not have time to build up with c3 and d4. There are two main responses,  4.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@the most popular@@EndBracket@@ and  4.e5  .  Curiously, these variations can sometimes transpose into each other.In fact, there are so many different move orders available to White @@StartBracket@@which invariably lead to transpositions@@EndBracket@@ that understanding what you are aiming for is as necessary as learning the variations. Therefore I would strongly recommend looking at the model games section to complement your knowledge of variations here. }
4. Nc3
{ The most sensible move. The knight defends the e-pawn. However, notice that White is now unable to build a pawn centre with c3 and d4 - in that sense Black has already achieved something.   4.Bxc6  usually transposes to lines examined later on after  4...dxc6  5.d3  g6  6.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@for example@@EndBracket@@. See the line 4.Nc3 g6 5.  Bxc6 dxc6 6.h3, etc.   In general in the 3...Nf6 variation, be prepared for flexible move orders. That's why an understanding of typical manoeuvres is  particularly valuable, as well as knowing set lines.   After  4.Nc3  , at this point  4...Qc7  is the most popular response, but I would prefer not to bring out the queen at such an early stage in the game.  4...Nd4  has also been tried, but I find that too risky as it breaks a basic opening rule: do not move the same piece twice in the opening. Instead, let's continue developing. }
4... g6
{ If Black manages to fianchetto the bishop and get castled, the opening will have been concluded satisfactorily. White must cause some disruption. There are basically two ways to play - advance with e5, or don't advance!   The main continuations are  5.Bxc6  and  5.e5  , but  5.h3  should be checked out as Black reacts a little differently. @@StartBracket@@  5.O-O  Bg7  should transpose to one of these lines after  6.e5  or  6.Bxc6  . @@EndBracket@@ }
5. e5
{ The most direct move, attempting to disrupt Black's smooth development. We should pay the most attention to this continuation. }
5... Ng4 { The pawn on e5 is threatened, so White must take action. } 6. Bxc6
{ White will have to play this sooner or later. If  6.Qe2  Bg7  , the threat to the e-pawn forces White to play  7.Bxc6  and after  7...dxc6  there is a transposition to lines examined later. }
6... dxc6
{ In most cases, when White exchanges bishop for knight on c6, Black should recapture with the d-pawn. The bishop on c8 needs to come into play. }
7. h3 Nh6
{ The knight doesn't look well placed on the edge, but it's just a couple of steps from a beautiful outpost in the middle of the board: ...Nh6-f5-d4 - problem solved!Black's next moves are straightforward: ...Bg7, O-O, Nh6-f5-d4. White has a little more choice, but essentially there are two main decisions to take: castle kingside or queenside? Do you restrict the knight with g4?   At this point, White can play several moves.  8.g4  is the most popular, and  8.d3  ,  8.Ne4  , and  8.O-O  come in at roughly joint second in terms of frequency. There are often transpositions between these lines. For the sake of clarity, I will just be examining  8.g4  and  8.d3  in the course. }
8. g4
{ This is by far the most popular move at this juncture. It is the only attempt to exploit the placement of the knight on h6, but advancing the g-pawn involves some weakening of White's position along the f-file. The stakes are raised.   8.Ne4  is occasionally played at this juncture. It will usually transpose to lines considered later, for example,  8...b6  9.d3  Bg7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Re1  Nf5  , etc.   8.O-O  should transpose to one of the other lines introduced by  8.d3  or  8.Ne4  . }
8... Bg7 { Calm development. } 9. d3 O-O
{ There is no danger to the king. Black's only problem in the position is how to bring the knight on h6 into play. Three moves have been played for White here in roughly equal numbers. }
10. Bf4
{ Supporting the pawn on e5 feels logical, although once the f-file opens, the bishop is vulnerable. }
10... f6
{ This puts pressure on the e5-pawn and prepares to bring the knight to f7. I prefer this to  10...f5  @@StartBracket@@which is also playable@@EndBracket@@ as Black has the chance to counter-attack along the f-file. }
11. Qe2 { Supporting the e-pawn. } 11... Nf7
{ The knight returns from the edge and puts pressure on the e5-pawn.   By the way,  11...Nxg4?  has been tried in a few games but this boldness rebounds badly. White gets a powerful attack after  12.hxg4  fxe5  13.Rxh7  Kxh7  14.Ng5+  Kg8  15.Be3  followed by queenside castling. }
12. O-O-O
{ It is essential that the king evacuates or there could be trouble in the middle.  12.exf6  wouldn't be a good idea: after  12...exf6  13.O-O-O  stepping out of the e-file we can follow up with  13...Re8  14.Qd2  f5  opening up diagonals for our bishop pair. }
12... fxe5
{ Black gains counterplay down the f-file. This exploits the move g4 which has created weaknesses on f4, f3, and f2. }
13. Bg3 Be6
{ It is unlikely that Black will be able to hold on to the extra pawn, but it will be possible to activate all the pieces. }
14. Nxe5 Bd5
{ Removing the bishop from its exposed position on the e-file and finding a useful diagonal. White will have to trade our powerful bishop. You can find more in the corresponding chapter. }
