1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin is a respectable, if rather pedestrian system. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  White would like to build a strong centre with  d4  and recapture with the c-pawn. In reply, for a long time I flipped between playing  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  @@StartBracket@@the two main lines, and both decent for Black@@EndBracket@@, but for me they are too well known. I like to make my opponent think.   By the way,  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.c3  e6  4.d4  d5  is another possible move order that will transpose to lines considered in the course. }
2... e6
{ This is an excellent move, yet, according to my database, it is played in fewer than 10% of games starting from this position. Black is going to play ...d5, but intends to recapture with the pawn, not the queen. }
3. d4 { White establishes the pawn centre. } 3... d5
{ Black plays the pawn into the middle. This variation is all about central control!Here White has a choice: exchange on d5 or play the pawn to e5 transposing to the Advance variation of the French Defence. The majority of my opponents exchanged on d5, and that is borne out by the database: it's by far the most common move here, so that needs the most attention. }
4. exd5 exd5
{ By recapturing with the pawn, Black maintains central control. This is classical chess. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 { The knight develops and influences a key square: d4. } 6. Bb5
{ The most popular move - and the best move. The position is similar to a French Tarrasch @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  c5  4.exd5  exd5  5.Ngf3  Nc6  6.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ except that in our variation the pawn stands on c3 and the queen's knight hasn't yet developed. The difference is small, but it means White is a little slower to develop, and that is already a sign that the variation is quite acceptable for Black. }
6... Bd6
{ The bishop moves to an excellent diagonal. In this position,  7.dxc5  and  7.O-O  are the best and also most popular moves, played in equal measure. In the vast majority of cases these lines will transpose into each other, so I am going to concentrate on  7.dxc5  . I will point out just one idea that is important to know against  7.O-O  . }
7. dxc5 { I will take this is as the main move. } 7... Bxc5
{ The bishop stands actively, pointing down to that perennially sensitive f2 square. }
8. O-O
{ The king should exit before anything else is undertaken. Traditionally, the normal move here is  8...Nge7  - with a probable transposition to a French Tarrasch after  9.Nbd2  . This is a reasonable way for Black to play. However, it has recently been discovered that Black can play more actively with  8...Nf6  . It was always thought that White could exploit the open e-file, but practice has shown that Black is not troubled and more than that, can often seize the initiative. }
8... Nf6 { A more active square than e7. } 9. Bg5
{ Considering that the bishop has moved to c5, this is potentially an annoying pin. There is already a threat to exchange on f6 and then capture the d5-pawn. }
9... Be6
{ Protecting the d-pawn and therefore meeting White's threat to take on f6. }
10. Nbd2 { The knight usually spins round via b3 to d4. } 10... O-O
{ The king exits. } 11. Nb3 Bb6
{ The bishop maintains its active position looking down at f2, but also keeping an eye on the strategically important d4 square. }
12. Nbd4
{ Here the recently published Alapin course by GMs Ganguly and Kazimdzhanov offers  12.Bxc6!?  bxc6  13.Nbd4  , with the idea that after  13...c5  14.Nxe6  fxe6  15.c4  our bishop on b6 is blocked in.Instead of 13...c5 I would recommend  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p4ppp/1bp1bn2/3p2B1/3N4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rc8  ,  keeping the bishop on b6 alive. If  14.Re1  h6  15.Bh4  Bd7  the chances are balanced. If White is careless, the bishops, together with the strong centre, will give Black the advantage. }
12... Nxd4
{ This is a good exchange: Black cannot waste time protecting the knight on c6. }
13. Nxd4
{ The alternative  13.cxd4  doesn't present any difficulties. In fact Black can take the initiative after  13...h6  14.Bh4  g5  15.Bg3  Ne4  . }
13... h6 { Black should deal with the pin straightaway. } 14. Bh4
{ Maintaining the pin is the most testing. Instead,  14.Be3  Bd7  is comfortable for Black. And  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Nxe6  fxe6  gives good counterplay against f2. That's why we kept the bishop on b6! }
14... g5
{ A simple way of dealing with the pin. Get used to this! It's really common in isolated queen's pawn positions. }
15. Bg3 Ne4
{ That's the important follow up. The knight hits the outpost and keeps an eye on the bishop as well as the f2 pawn. Black's queen can now move to an excellent square on f6. From there it looks at the key squares d4 and f2, but also protects the kingside. }
