[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Morra Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ The Morra Gambit is popular at club level so it is worth examining carefully. What does White gain for the pawn? A little bit of activity, a slight lead in development, but that is about it. Crucially, Black's pawn structure is still intact. If Black follows the right steps at the beginning there are good chances to consolidate the extra pawn. With great accuracy, White can equalise, but that is hardly a ringing recommendation for the opening. Remember, Black needs to play the first few moves correctly, and in the right order! }
2... cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 { The starting point of the Morra Gambit. } 4...
Nc6 { Sound development. A knight into the middle. } 5. Nf3 d6
{ This is like a normal open Sicilian position, except that White lacks a pawn on c2. }
6. Bc4
{ An important moment in the game. There are some ancient traps here. First of all, don't play  6...Nf6  - that allows  7.e5!  dxe5  8.Qxd8+  Nxd8  9.Nb5  with a great attack. And don't play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/8/2B1P3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , allowing  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Ng5+  . }
6... a6
{ A standard Sicilian move, guarding the b5 square, but there is a specific reason to play it at this moment. }
7. O-O Nf6
{ It's okay to play the knight here now that ...a6 has been played. } 8. Qe2
{ Against our setup, the  8.e5  trick is not working. See here. } 8... Bg4
{ This is the whole point of Black's careful opening moves. The pin restricts White's options and can lead to favourable exchanges. }
9. Rd1
{ If  10.h3  Black can just play  10...Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Ne5  and trade White's light-squared bishop or go for the solid  11...e6  with easy development @@StartBracket@@...Be7 and ...O-O next@@EndBracket@@. }
9... e6
{ This is already a diffcult position for White. Black threatens to play ...Ne5, followed by breaking up White's kingside pawns. }
10. Bf4
{ This is not the best move, but it is the most typical in this kind of position, attempting to put pressure on the d6-pawn.   Instead, White ought to compromise and play  10.h3  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Be7  , but Black is basically a sound pawn up. }
10... Nh5
{ This introduces some surprising attacking options. Instead, I once played  10...Qb8  @@StartBracket@@which is also good, but slower@@EndBracket@@. The game continued  11.h3  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  Be7  13.Rac1  O-O  14.Bb3  Rc8  , and slowly but surely I converted the extra pawn. }
11. Be3
{ Instead,  11.Bg3  Nxg3  12.hxg3  h5!  followed by ...h4, gives Black a huge attack.   Or  11.Qe3  Nxf4  12.Qxf4  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  Ne5!  14.Qe2  g5!  ,  securing the knight on e5 and launching a strong kingside intiative. }
11... Ne5
{ This is the idea: Black is able to damage White's kingside pawns and begin a strong attack. }
12. Bb3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qh4
{ White is in massive trouble. Black threatens moves such as ...Qh3, ...g5, ...Nf4 - depending on how White plays. }
*

