[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack with 5.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the favoured way of entering into the Grand Prix Attack for White.  2.f4  has been discredited because of  2...d5  - see the 2. f4 chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 { The launch of the f-pawn signifies The Grand Prix Attack. }
3... g6
{ The bishop belongs on the long diagonal, influencing the centre. In particular, the d4 square is pivotal in this opening. }
4. Nf3 Bg7
{ Move order is important. Notice that Black has not yet committed the d- or e-pawns. Having that flexibility is helpful in combatting White's strategy. Here White has a choice of where to play the king's bishop: c4 or b5. }
5. Bc4 { This is a direct attempt to attack, but it is a bit too crude. } 5...
e6
{ If the bishop is pointing down the diagonal, it makes perfect sense to block it out. }
6. f5
{ This is the most testing move. White offers a pawn while Black's king is still in the centre. Should you take the bait or ignore it? And if you take it, with which pawn? It's easy to see how such an early challenge succeeded in confusing so many players in tough weekend tournaments.   Let me sum up the options for Black. First, let's rule out  6...exf5  . No! That opens the diagonal for the bishop and is more trouble than it is worth.  6...gxf5  is playable for Black, but you need to have your eyes wide open. With the kingside opening up, this can get tricky. Instead of these, I recommend simple development with  6...Nge7  . }
6... Nge7
{ A solid and sound move. Black develops a piece and prepares to castle. In my experience this unpretentious response confounds the Grand Prix hackers! }
7. fxe6
{ To avoid serious disadvantage, White has to exchange on e6. For example,  7.O-O  d5  , or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pnpbp/2n1p1p1/2p2P2/2B1P3/2N2N2/PPPP2PP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.d3  d5  , and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pnpbp/2n1p1p1/2p2P2/2B1P3/2N2N2/PPPP2PP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.fxg6  hxg6!  followed by ...d5 and the semi-open h-file could be very useful for Black. }
7... dxe6
{ By recapturing with the d-pawn, Black maintains a solid pawn front on the kingside, which means it will be difficult for White to mount an attack. This is more reliable than  7...fxe6  which leaves the king a little open. }
8. d3 O-O
{ The king is safe behind a wall of pawns and the protection of the bishop on g7. }
9. O-O
{ Black is not under threat and has a range of options:  9...Na5  is the most popular move, preparing to pick off the bishop, but  9...Nd4  ,  9...b6  , and  9...h6  are all decent alternatives, demonstrating the essential soundness of Black's position. }
9... h6
{ This move is favoured by computers, covering the important g5-square. It also heralds a kingside counter-attack. }
10. Qe1
{ I know what Grand Prix Attack players like to do - nine times out of ten they will follow the standard scheme and transfer the queen to the kingside. But Black is ready! }
10... g5
{ According to any computer you may care to consult, Black already stands better! }
11. Qg3 { The queen heads towards the kingside, but Black can cover easily. }
11... Ng6
{ Packing out the kingside as well as taking control over some key squares. }
12. Be3 Nd4
{ In so many lines in the Grand Prix Attack, the key move for Black is to slam the knight on the outpost. White cannot live comfortably with such an imposing beast, but exchanging it off improves Black's pawn structure. }
13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Ne2 Kh7
{ Black is ready to strike out with ...f5, or potentially ...e5 and ...Nf4. The bishop on g7 and knight on g6 provide great cover for the king, so that White is unable to attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack with 5.Bb5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5
{ You may have noticed that in the variations against the 5. Bc4 Grand Prix Attack, Black often gains counterplay by planting the knight on d4, disrupting the flow of White's development and putting a massive spanner in the works of the kingside attack. That's what playing the bishop to b5 is all about: If  5...d6  6.Bxc6+!  bxc6  7.O-O  ,  White can be delighted with his position. Black cannot play the knight into d4 and White has a free hand to attack on the kingside with all the usual moves such as d3, Qe1, f5, Qh4, etc.I've seen it and played it a hundred times and, trust me, it is highly dangerous. Black has to avoid this. That's why the next move is clear. }
5... Nd4
{ As in so many variations of the closed Sicilians, the knight is powerful on d4, disrupting White's development. In this particular case, it leaves the bishop dangling on b5 with nothing to do. So was 5. Bb5 just a one-move trick? Was White just hoping to make that sneaky exchange on c6? Frankly, yes! }
6. Nxd4
{ This is the second most popular move, according to my database. It's not very good for White. }
6... cxd4 { Black gains time. } 7. Ne2
{ The knight has been pushed back to a poor square, blocking White's pieces. }
7... Nh6
{ I like this knight move! You'll see that in the main line with 6. O-O, it also features. Why does this appeal to me? Because if Black develops rapidly, there is more chance of catching out the opposition. The aim is to castle as quickly as possible, but more than that, the knight is sometimes able to leap to g4 causing problems, and if White's pawn advances to e5, it will establish itself on f5. }
8. O-O
{ The king needs to get out of the middle. That loose bishop on b5 is a cause for concern. Instead, if  8.d3?  Qa5+  wins a piece :@@EndBracket@@ Hehe. }
8... O-O
{ Don't waste time! Get the king to safety and then you will be ready to strike. Notice how Black has not wasted time on superfluous pawn moves. }
9. d3
{ 9.Ng3  is examined in the Model Games chapter: Mossong-Popovic, Vilnius 1995. }
9... d5
{ That's a big hit. Black starts to break up the pawn duo on e4 and f4. } 10.
Ba4 b5
{ Black seizes the initiative on the queenside. Neither capturing the pawn nor retreating the bishop offer White good play. We'll soon pose threats on the a7-g1 diagonal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack with 5.Bb5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5
{ You may have noticed that in the variations against the 5. Bc4 Grand Prix Attack, Black often gains counterplay by planting the knight on d4, disrupting the flow of White's development and putting a massive spanner in the works of the kingside attack. That's what playing the bishop to b5 is all about: If  5...d6  6.Bxc6+!  bxc6  7.O-O  ,  White can be delighted with his position. Black cannot play the knight into d4 and White has a free hand to attack on the kingside with all the usual moves such as d3, Qe1, f5, Qh4, etc.I've seen it and played it a hundred times and, trust me, it is highly dangerous. Black has to avoid this. That's why the next move is clear. }
5... Nd4
{ As in so many variations of the closed Sicilians, the knight is powerful on d4, disrupting White's development. In this particular case, it leaves the bishop dangling on b5 with nothing to do. So was 5. Bb5 just a one-move trick? Was White just hoping to make that sneaky exchange on c6? Frankly, yes! }
6. O-O
{ The most popular move. Black has a big choice here and to some extent it is a question of taste which move you select. For example, many players like to exchange off knight for bishop - that's fine. Instead, I recommend pushing back the bishop to an awkward square. }
6... a6 7. Bd3
{ The bishop needs to return here because Black would meet  7.Bc4  with  7...b5  , but really, what a dreadful square, blocking the d-pawn! Black has great chances to catch out his gummed up opponent. }
7... Nh6
{ Black has several decent moves available, but developing a piece appeals to me the most. This is not the most popular move @@StartBracket@@the unpretentious  7...d6  is number 1 in the database@@EndBracket@@, but I believe the knight move is highly dangerous for White. }
8. Nxd4 cxd4 { Disturbing the knight and gaining time. } 9. Ne2 d5
{ Breaking up White's centre pawns immediately makes sense considering that it will take an age for White to develop properly. }
10. e5 { The pawn cuts off the bishop on g7 from supporting the d-pawn. } 10...
f6 { Breaking down the pawn on e5 to free the bishop on g7. } 11. exf6 Bxf6
{ Reconnnecting with the d-pawn. } 12. b3 Bf5
{ Good development. Black has free play and can look to the future with confidence. For example,  13.Bxf5  Nxf5  threatens ...d3 and  14.d3  allows some timely ...Qb6 and ...Ne3 ideas. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Grand Prix/Rossolimo Hybrid with 4.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6
{ It looks like White is heading for a Grand Prix Attack with  3.f4  or perhaps a Closed Sicilian with  3.g3  . But no, something else appears on the board. }
3. Bb5
{ This a curious hybrid of the Rossolimo @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ and the Grand Prix Attack. If White's plan works out, there is still a chance to advance the f-pawn. Black has to take immediate measures. }
3... Nd4
{ The knight avoids the chop. Just as in the Grand Prix Attack proper, when White plays the bishop to b5, this exchange should be avoided and the knight jump highlights one of the drawbacks of playing the knight to c3. The knight stands well on d4, and leaves the bishop on b5 looking stranded.   There are two main moves here:  4.Bc4  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bc4 Nf6
{ A provocative move @@StartBracket@@and a good move!@@EndBracket@@ } 5. Nf3
{ 5.e5  is exactly what we want!  5...d5  6.exf6  dxc4  7.fxg7  Bxg7  and Black has two bishops and a wonderful knight on d4. }
5... e6 { Blocking out the bishop on c4. } 6. O-O
{ ATTENTION! This sets a devilish trap. } 6... a6
{ This a useful move, preparing to expand with ...b5. It might appear that instead of this,  6...d5  is a straightforward move - but in fact it is a terrible mistake.  7.exd5  exd5  8.Nxd5!  Ultimately, this wins a pawn:  8...Nxd5  9.Nxd4  cxd4  10.Qh5  Be6  11.Re1  .  White has two threats: to take on d5, and also to take on e6 and Black cannot escape. }
7. a4
{ Preventing ...b5, but in this case it is possible to hit out with ...d5.   By the way, as usual,  7.e5  would be met by  7...d5! }
7... d5 8. exd5 exd5 9. Ba2 Bg4 { An unpleasant pin for White. } 10. Qe1+
{ The only way out. } 10... Be7 { Preparing to castle. } 11. Nxd4
{ White has to exchange off the knight, but the pawn recapture attacking the knight, as on so many occasions in these closed Sicilian variations, is uncomfortable. }
11... cxd4 12. Ne2 d3
{ A fine disrupting move making it harder for White to develop. } 13. cxd3 O-O
{ Black's pieces are harmoniously placed and the compensation for the small material investment is more than enough. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Grand Prix/Rossolimo Hybrid with 4.Bc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6
{ It looks like White is heading for a Grand Prix Attack with  3.f4  or perhaps a Closed Sicilian with  3.g3  . But no, something else appears on the board. }
3. Bb5
{ This a curious hybrid of the Rossolimo @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ and the Grand Prix Attack. If White's plan works out, there is still a chance to advance the f-pawn. Black has to take immediate measures. }
3... Nd4
{ The knight avoids the chop. Just as in the Grand Prix Attack proper, when White plays the bishop to b5, this exchange should be avoided and the knight jump highlights one of the drawbacks of playing the knight to c3. The knight stands well on d4, and leaves the bishop on b5 looking stranded.   There are two main moves here:  4.Bc4  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bc4 Nf6
{ A provocative move @@StartBracket@@and a good move!@@EndBracket@@ } 5. Nge2
{ 5.e5  is exactly what we want!  5...d5  6.exf6  dxc4  7.fxg7  Bxg7  and Black has two bishops and a wonderful knight on d4. }
5... a6
{ A provocative move!  5...e6  is more common and will often transpose to the lines we are about to consider. }
6. a4 { Preventing Black from expanding with ...b5. } 6... e6
{ Blocking out the bishop. } 7. O-O
{ An important crossroads. Black can break out and equalise easily, or keep more tension. }
7... d5
{ This is the simplest way to equalise, however, if Black wishes to keep more tension, then it is possible to play  7...d6  8.d3  Nc6  9.d4  @@StartBracket@@at this juncture White doesn't have much better@@EndBracket@@  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  , transposing into an open Sicilian, specifically the Sozin variation. If that suits you - go for it! }
8. exd5 exd5 { That's a decent pawn centre. } 9. Ba2
{ Quite a common position. Objectively, it's about equal. The trick with  9.Nxd5  does not work - compare to my note on 6...a6 in the previous trainable:  9...Nxd5  10.Nxd4  cxd4  11.Re1+  Be6  12.Qh5  Nf4  .  In this case the  inclusion of the moves 5...a6 and 6. a4 is of great significance: there is no  check on b5 and therefore Black keeps the extra material. }
9... Bd6
{ The bishop points in the right direction. This attempts to keep a bit of life in the position and is more fun than  9...Nxe2+  10.Qxe2+  Be7  11.d3  Be6  12.Bg5  O-O  13.Qf3  Rb8  @@StartBracket@@Gajewski-Zawadzki, Aviles 2003@@EndBracket@@ which soon burned out to a draw. }
10. d3 Ne6
{ Keeping pieces on the board makes sense for Black considering that White is congested behind the first three ranks. The knight on e6 prevents the bishop from moving to g5. }
11. Ng3 h5 { Cry, God for Harry! Black can even take the intiative. } 12. Re1
Kf8
{ Considering that Black holds the centre, this flank attack is quite legitimate, and it is a lot more fun than simply exchanging pieces. The onus is on White to think how best to defend. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ This modest pawn move signals the start of the Closed Sicilian. When played by Vassily Smyslov or Boris Spassky, this could be a serious weapon. When played by everyone else, it was often insipid. These days, one rarely sees the opening ventured by the world's top players for three reasons: Black's responses are well worked out; the positions are too stable; Black often has more than one good way to respond, so there is very little jeopardy. }
3... g6
{ As in many Anti-Sicilian variations, the d4-square is of great importance, so the fianchetto is appropriate. }
4. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black's strong control over the d4-square makes it difficult for White to launch a meaningful kingside attack. }
5. d3
{ White could instead play  5.f4  or  5.Nge2  , but they will inevitably transpose into a later line. }
5... d6
{ This is the most flexible move: we know that the d-pawn will always move to d6, but it isn't yet clear where the e-pawn belongs: e6 or e5? First we see how White commits. }
6. f4
{ This is the most brazen way of playing for White. If the pawn can be forced through to f5, then there is some chance of an attack, but Black can prevent that easily. Often this pawn thrust does more harm than good, weakening the squares behind it. }
6... e6
{ The pawn makes room for the knight and the process of containing White's f-pawn begins. }
7. Nf3 Nge7
{ Notice that four of Black's pieces are directed towards the f5-square: it will be very difficult for White to advance it further. Developing the knight on e7 also ensures that the fianchettoed bishop is unimpeded and continues to control the d4-square. }
8. O-O O-O
{ Already, strong computers aren't particularly impressed by White's position - around minus 0.20 for those that take an interest in the digits. From a human viewpoint we can at least say that White will do well to equalise from the opening @@StartBracket@@with the proviso that Black plays well@@EndBracket@@. }
9. g4
{ White is determined to attack on the kingside, but this is too much. Black is perfectly set up to counter this ill-judged aggression. }
9... f5
{ This is the key move, ensuring that the f4-pawn is nailed down. That means the bishop on c1 is blocked in, not to mention the f1-rook. }
10. gxf5 exf5
{ Recapturing with the e-pawn ensures that the g-file remains closed. In this variation, White's king often suffers later on in the game as it lacks pawn cover. White doesn't want to take, as  11.exf5  Nxf5  gives us a powerful knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ This modest pawn move signals the start of the Closed Sicilian. When played by Vassily Smyslov or Boris Spassky, this could be a serious weapon. When played by everyone else, it was often insipid. These days, one rarely sees the opening ventured by the world's top players for three reasons: Black's responses are well worked out; the positions are too stable; Black often has more than one good way to respond, so there is very little jeopardy. }
3... g6
{ As in many Anti-Sicilian variations, the d4-square is of great importance, so the fianchetto is appropriate. }
4. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black's strong control over the d4-square makes it difficult for White to launch a meaningful kingside attack. }
5. d3
{ White could instead play  5.f4  or  5.Nge2  , but they will inevitably transpose into a later line. }
5... d6
{ This is the most flexible move: we know that the d-pawn will always move to d6, but it isn't yet clear where the e-pawn belongs: e6 or e5? First we see how White commits. }
6. f4
{ This is the most brazen way of playing for White. If the pawn can be forced through to f5, then there is some chance of an attack, but Black can prevent that easily. Often this pawn thrust does more harm than good, weakening the squares behind it. }
6... e6
{ The pawn makes room for the knight and the process of containing White's f-pawn begins. }
7. Nf3 Nge7
{ Notice that four of Black's pieces are directed towards the f5-square: it will be very difficult for White to advance it further. Developing the knight on e7 also ensures that the fianchettoed bishop is unimpeded and continues to control the d4-square. }
8. O-O O-O
{ Already, strong computers aren't particularly impressed by White's position - around minus 0.20 for those that take an interest in the digits. From a human viewpoint we can at least say that White will do well to equalise from the opening @@StartBracket@@with the proviso that Black plays well@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Be3
{ This is by far the most popular move at this juncture. The bishop covers the d4-square. Black has several good replies. The old move was  9...Nd4  , which is fine, although Black needs to be aware of  10.e5  , with which Spassky, and a few others, had some success. But I prefer 9...b6. }
9... b6
{ The bishop prepares to get into the game, sometimes via a6, sometimes via b7. The b6-pawn also bolsters c5, introducing another potential strategy - advancing with ...d6-d5. }
10. d4
{ The advance appears dangerous as exchanging would expose the d6 pawn. But instead Black has an excellent counter.   White may also retreat the bishop with  10.Bf2  to preempt our central push, in which case I recommend  10...e5  and land our knight on d4. See here. }
10... d5 { A disturbing move for White to meet. } 11. exd5
{ The best move.  11.dxc5  d4  drops a piece.   11.e5  Nf5  is a good French Defense for Black. }
11... Nf5
{ That's the clever idea: the e3-bishop is loose, as well as the pawn on d4. }
12. Bf2
{ Stepping away from lots of tactics. Alternatively,  12.Qd2  cxd4  13.dxc6  Nxe3  is rather nice for Black. }
12... Ncxd4
{ The knight hits the d4-outpost, supported by pawn, knight and bishop. } 13.
Ne5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Bb7
{ Attacking the knight in the middle.  14...Be6  is also playable. } 15. c4 Qd6
{ The recommended computer move, putting pressure on the e5-knight. The position is complex, but the strongly placed knight on d4 and the well-placed bishops on g7 and b7 give Black grounds for optimism. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ This modest pawn move signals the start of the Closed Sicilian. When played by Vassily Smyslov or Boris Spassky, this could be a serious weapon. When played by everyone else, it was often insipid. These days, one rarely sees the opening ventured by the world's top players for three reasons: Black's responses are well worked out; the positions are too stable; Black often has more than one good way to respond, so there is very little jeopardy. }
3... g6
{ As in many Anti-Sicilian variations, the d4-square is of great importance, so the fianchetto is appropriate. }
4. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black's strong control over the d4-square makes it difficult for White to launch a meaningful kingside attack. }
5. d3
{ White could instead play  5.f4  or  5.Nge2  , but they will inevitably transpose into a later line. }
5... d6
{ This is the most flexible move: we know that the d-pawn will always move to d6, but it isn't yet clear where the e-pawn belongs: e6 or e5? First we see how White commits. }
6. Be3
{ This is the most common move at this juncture. White intends supporting the bishop with Qd2 in order to exchange on h6. }
6... e5
{ In this case, it is appropriate to play the pawn forward two squares, clamping White in the middle. This gives Black strong central control. }
7. Qd2 Nge7 8. Bh6
{ White sticks to the programme, but ignoring development to pursue this plan just isn't worth it.   8.f4  will most likely transpose back into the line with 7.f4, for example:  8...O-O  9.Nf3  Nd4  10.O-O  etc. }
8... Bxh6 { This drags the queen offside. } 9. Qxh6 Nd4
{ A strong central counter-attack exposing the deficiencies of White's strategy. The knight is great in the middle! }
10. Qd2
{ The critical move is  10.O-O-O  but Black is well set up for a queenside attack with ...b5, ...Be6, ...Qa5 and so on. See here. }
10... h5
{ Black takes over the initiative. Hardly surprising given that White has wasted so much time. Now White does best to block with  11.h4  ,  but there are consequences: if White ever advances with f4, then the g4 square would be available for the bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ This modest pawn move signals the start of the Closed Sicilian. When played by Vassily Smyslov or Boris Spassky, this could be a serious weapon. When played by everyone else, it was often insipid. These days, one rarely sees the opening ventured by the world's top players for three reasons: Black's responses are well worked out; the positions are too stable; Black often has more than one good way to respond, so there is very little jeopardy. }
3... g6
{ As in many Anti-Sicilian variations, the d4-square is of great importance, so the fianchetto is appropriate. }
4. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black's strong control over the d4-square makes it difficult for White to launch a meaningful kingside attack. }
5. d3
{ White could instead play  5.f4  or  5.Nge2  , but they will inevitably transpose into a later line. }
5... d6
{ This is the most flexible move: we know that the d-pawn will always move to d6, but it isn't yet clear where the e-pawn belongs: e6 or e5? First we see how White commits. }
6. Nge2
{ In most king's pawn openings, this knight is best placed on f3 where it influences the e5-square. This applies here too. Would you be terrified facing this half-hearted development?   I know very well that this is not the most testing move - I've tried it myself. I had some ideas planned after  6...e5  7.h4!?  which weren't really much good, but they sometimes scared the opposition.   Instead, I believe that Black should keep control over the d5-square with  6...e6  .  The knight will still develop on e7, as is usually the case in the Closed Sicilian. This whole line is quite anemic for White. }
6... e6
{ Maintaining control over the d5 square. Black's choice of sixth move is important in all these variations. Against 6. f4 and 6. Nge2 - meet them with 6...e6; against 6. Be3, go the whole way with 6... e5. }
7. O-O Nge7
{ There are no threats to Black's position, so simple development is in order. }
8. Be3 Nd4
{ The knight lands on the traditional @@StartBracket@@and excellent@@EndBracket@@ d4-square disrupting the free flow of White's development. Giving up the dark-squared bishop with  9.Bxd4?  cxd4  would be highly suspect. }
9. Qd2 O-O { The king reaches safety. } 10. Nd1
{ White's most popular move, looking to drive away the knight with c3. } 10...
a5
{ Considering that White's pieces are going backwards, it is time to come forwards. }
11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Bh6 a4
{ Keep gaining space - the b2-pawn wil become a target. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Move Order Tricks: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ A tricky move. White keeps the option of playing an open Sicilian but waits to see how Black reacts before committing.   If you play the Dragon then this move order isn't an issue:  3...g6  is a useful move and  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  leads back into a Dragon. Likewise if you play the Taimanov, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  is a useful move and  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  is back to a normal position; or the Classical @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  , and the Scheveningen could also arise without a hitch. Even if you play the Sveshnikov you are okay: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6!  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e5  , etc.   But for the Kalashnikov, there isn't a good waiting move. For example  3...d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  and Black could play  5...e5  but this is not ideal. White can play  6.Nf5  and stands better. That's why I am recommending shutting the centre with 3...e5. }
3... e5
{ Preventing d4. In fact, if you are a Kalashnikov player, then you will already feel quite comfortable with this structure @@StartBracket@@the pawn on e5 claiming space - as well as the hole on d5!@@EndBracket@@. The strongest players in the world have regularly played like this, from Kasparov and Carlsen downwards, so you are in good company! }
4. Bc4
{ This is the drawback of Black's strategy: White is able to station the bishop on a dangerous diagonal and takes control over the d5-square. But as we know from the Kalashnikov, Black can fight for control of that square. }
4... Be7
{ Notice that Black is keeping an eye on the g5-square. Instead  4...Nf6?  5.Ng5  wouldn't be too bright. }
5. d3 d6
{ Black sets up solidly. There now comes a big divide. White has two main continuations:  6.O-O  and  6.Nd2  . They are played with roughly equal frequency. }
6. O-O
{ Another approach is  6.Nd2  The knight wants to spin round via f1 to e3 in order to gain greater control over the d5-square.  6...Nf6  Sensible development.  7.Nf1  The knight continues on its journey.  7...Bg4  This is a nice disruptive move. The queen doesn't want to move to the awkward square d2, but advancing the f-pawn also isn't ideal as it slightly weakens the kingside.  8.f3  Be6  This is the natural square for the bishop, challenging its counterpart on c4 and covering the d5-square.Anyone that plays the Kalashnikov, or indeed other variations of the Sicilian which feature a backward d-pawn such as the Sveshnikov or the Najdorf, will recognise that this is the correct spot. If White exchanges, the pawn on e6 will cover the important d5-square. }
6... Nf6 { Black is ready to castle if White attacks with Ng5. } 7. Ng5
{ A crude attack that can be easily parried. But the real point of the move is to unleash the f-pawn. }
7... O-O { The f7-pawn is covered. } 8. f4
{ White gets in a pawn break, but Black is solidly set up and this should not present difficulties. }
8... Bg4 { Bringing out the bishop and pushing the queen to a worse square. }
9. Qe1 exf4
{ It is important that White is prevented from pushing this pawn forward. Incidentally,  9...Nd4  10.Qh4!  is too dangerous. }
10. Bxf4 Nd4
{ The knight lands on the beautiful d4 square - as is so often the case in these closed Sicilian positions when a white knight stands on c3. The threat to the c2 pawn prevents White from taking active steps on the kingside. }
11. Qd2
{ The queen defends the c-pawn - a compromise as it really wanted to head for the kingside. }
11... h6 { The knight is pushed back from its strong position. } 12. Nf3
{ Instead,  12.Nxf7  Rxf7  13.Bxf7+  Kxf7  comes to nothing for White: the king is safe and if played correctly the two minor pieces are stronger than the rook and pawn. }
12... Nxf3+ 13. gxf3 Bh3
{ The bishop finds a safe square and gains a tempo by attacking the rook. } 14.
Rfd1 Kh7
{ The king protects the pawn on h6 and preempts an attack on the g-file. Next, ...Nh5 allows us to create some play of our own on the kingside. See here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Move Order Tricks: 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Nge2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nge2
{ For most Sicilian players, this move isn't an issue. For example, a Sveshnikov player can simply reply  3...Nf6  and the game will in all likelihood head that way:  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e5  . Likewise a Dragon player wouldn't have a problem after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPPNPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  etc. But for a Kalashnikov player, the 'threat' to head back into an open Sicilian causes a problem. If you aren't happy with one of the alternative Sicilians, then d4 must be stopped.   There are two reasonable ways of achieving this.  3...e5  is sensible, which is rather similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  e5  , as examined in the previous chapter. My only qualm is that the position could simplify too quickly. For example, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nge2  e5  4.Nd5  Nge7  5.Nec3  Nxd5  6.Nxd5  Be7  7.Bc4  ,  etc. But there is nothing wrong with this line for Black, and if you want something steady, solid and reliable, then go for it. For the more adventurous, I have an alternative recommendation. }
3... Nd4
{ Let's hope they get confused and play  4.g3  .  Hehe. According to my database, most White players exchange on d4 at this point, but a significant number also play  4.d3  , so we are looking at that one as well. }
4. Nxd4 cxd4 5. Ne2 { This is the most frequently played. } 5... e5
{ Black defends the pawn and with it takes control in the centre. I believe that  5...Nf6  is also a very sound option for Black. }
6. c3 d5
{ I like this move as it immediately sows confusion. Which pawn should White take? There is also the issue of how White is going to develop with that knight getting in the way on e2. This is almost uncharted territory! My database shows that only one other game has been played with this move. }
7. exd5 Qxd5
{ The queen assumes a strong central position. The knight on e2 hampers development, so White has to take the pawn in the middle. }
8. cxd4 exd4 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qxd4 Nf6 { Black develops calmly. } 11. Qxd5 Nxd5
{ Threatening ...Nb4. Black has a lead in development and it isn't clear to me how White is going to be able to castle. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Move Order Tricks: 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Nge2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nge2
{ For most Sicilian players, this move isn't an issue. For example, a Sveshnikov player can simply reply  3...Nf6  and the game will in all likelihood head that way:  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e5  . Likewise a Dragon player wouldn't have a problem after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPPNPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  etc. But for a Kalashnikov player, the 'threat' to head back into an open Sicilian causes a problem. If you aren't happy with one of the alternative Sicilians, then d4 must be stopped.   There are two reasonable ways of achieving this.  3...e5  is sensible, which is rather similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  e5  , as examined in the previous chapter. My only qualm is that the position could simplify too quickly. For example, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nge2  e5  4.Nd5  Nge7  5.Nec3  Nxd5  6.Nxd5  Be7  7.Bc4  ,  etc. But there is nothing wrong with this line for Black, and if you want something steady, solid and reliable, then go for it. For the more adventurous, I have an alternative recommendation. }
3... Nd4
{ Let's hope they get confused and play  4.g3  .  Hehe. According to my database, most White players exchange on d4 at this point, but a significant number also play  4.d3  , so we are looking at that one as well. }
4. Nxd4 cxd4 5. Ne2 { This is the most frequently played. } 5... e5
{ Black defends the pawn and with it takes control in the centre. I believe that  5...Nf6  is also a very sound option for Black. }
6. c3 d5
{ I like this move as it immediately sows confusion. Which pawn should White take? There is also the issue of how White is going to develop with that knight getting in the way on e2. This is almost uncharted territory! My database shows that only one other game has been played with this move. }
7. cxd4 exd4
{ The best capture as it continues to hamper White's development The alternative is not as good:  7...dxe4?  8.dxe5  Qd5  9.Nc3!  Qxe5  We are following the game Reti-Perlmutter Netherlands 1919 - yes, the famous Reti! Here he could have gained a large advantage by playing  10.Bb5+  ,  displacing Black's king. }
8. Nxd4 dxe4 { The knight on d4 is attacked by Black's queen. } 9. Bb5+
{ White needs to develop rapidly. } 9... Bd7 10. O-O Nf6
{ Black also needs to hurry with development. } 11. d3 Bc5
{ Gaining time by attacking the knight. } 12. dxe4 O-O
{ Castling is necessary - the position was too open. Black is a pawn down, but White's centre is under attack. White is forced to exchange some pieces and give the e-pawn back. More here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) The Rossolimo: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 4.e5"]
[Black "Rossolimo: 4.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Rossolimo rightly has an excellent reputation. White brings out a piece and prepares to castle as quickly as possible. Very often the follow up is c3 and d4 attempting to set up a big pawn centre. Black must know how to fight that, and at the same time bring the king to safety. The task should not be underestimated.   The most popular continuations here are  3...g6  and  3...e6  , but I am recommending a move that cuts across White's plans. }
3... Nf6
{ Bringing out a piece and attacking the e-pawn. In this case, White does not have time to build up with c3 and d4. There are two main responses,  4.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@the most popular@@EndBracket@@ and  4.e5  .  Curiously, these variations can sometimes transpose into each other.In fact, there are so many different move orders available to White @@StartBracket@@which invariably lead to transpositions@@EndBracket@@ that understanding what you are aiming for is as necessary as learning the variations. Therefore I would strongly recommend looking at the model games section to complement your knowledge of variations here. }
4. e5
{ The second most popular move. Curiously, the variations after  4.Nc3  and  4.e5  often transpose into each other. Watch for the knight and its journey from f6 to d4. After  4.e5  Nd5  the knight will often continue ...Nc7-e6-d4.   In the variation with  4.Nc3  g6  5.e5  Ng4  ,  the knight also reaches d4 but via a different route: ...Nh6-f5-d4. }
4... Nd5
{ I would have liked to advocate  4...Ng4  ,  in order to sync with the 4. Nc3 main lines, but unfortunately White has additional options involving c3 and d4 which are best to avoid @@StartBracket@@I'll spare you the details!@@EndBracket@@. In any case, everything is fine with  4...Nd5  ,  and lines often transpose into positions that are familiar. }
5. O-O
{ Instead of this,  5.Nc3  Nc7!  6.Bxc6  dxc6  will soon transpose back into our main line. }
5... g6 { As usual, the bishop develops on g7. } 6. c3
{ White wants to build a pawn centre with d4. This takes the game into slightly different paths, although once again, it's nothing for Black to be concerned about. }
6... Bg7 { Speedy development is called for - as usual. } 7. d4 Nc7
{ The knight attacks the bishop and soon White's centre will come under fire. This is a relatively modern move. The standard continuation used to be  7...cxd4  @@StartBracket@@which is also reasonable@@EndBracket@@ but  7...Nc7  gives White more to think about. }
8. Bxc6 dxc6
{ Opening up the diagonal for the bishop on c8 which threatens to move to g4 or e6. }
9. dxc5 { Taking the pawn is the only move which tests Black. } 9... Qxd1 10.
Rxd1 Bg4
{ With easy development and play on the light squares, Black has good compensation for the pawn. }
11. Nbd2 Rd8
{ The rook move makes it difficult for White to develop. Recapturing the pawn immediately would help to free White's pieces. }
12. Re1 Ne6
{ Black's pieces are so active that White cannot hope for an advantage here. }
13. b4 Rd3 { Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) The Rossolimo: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 4.e5"]
[Black "Rossolimo: 4.e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Rossolimo rightly has an excellent reputation. White brings out a piece and prepares to castle as quickly as possible. Very often the follow up is c3 and d4 attempting to set up a big pawn centre. Black must know how to fight that, and at the same time bring the king to safety. The task should not be underestimated.   The most popular continuations here are  3...g6  and  3...e6  , but I am recommending a move that cuts across White's plans. }
3... Nf6
{ Bringing out a piece and attacking the e-pawn. In this case, White does not have time to build up with c3 and d4. There are two main responses,  4.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@the most popular@@EndBracket@@ and  4.e5  .  Curiously, these variations can sometimes transpose into each other.In fact, there are so many different move orders available to White @@StartBracket@@which invariably lead to transpositions@@EndBracket@@ that understanding what you are aiming for is as necessary as learning the variations. Therefore I would strongly recommend looking at the model games section to complement your knowledge of variations here. }
4. e5
{ The second most popular move. Curiously, the variations after  4.Nc3  and  4.e5  often transpose into each other. Watch for the knight and its journey from f6 to d4. After  4.e5  Nd5  the knight will often continue ...Nc7-e6-d4.   In the variation with  4.Nc3  g6  5.e5  Ng4  ,  the knight also reaches d4 but via a different route: ...Nh6-f5-d4. }
4... Nd5
{ I would have liked to advocate  4...Ng4  ,  in order to sync with the 4. Nc3 main lines, but unfortunately White has additional options involving c3 and d4 which are best to avoid @@StartBracket@@I'll spare you the details!@@EndBracket@@. In any case, everything is fine with  4...Nd5  ,  and lines often transpose into positions that are familiar. }
5. O-O
{ Instead of this,  5.Nc3  Nc7!  6.Bxc6  dxc6  will soon transpose back into our main line. }
5... g6 { As usual, the bishop develops on g7. } 6. c3
{ White wants to build a pawn centre with d4. This takes the game into slightly different paths, although once again, it's nothing for Black to be concerned about. }
6... Bg7 { Speedy development is called for - as usual. } 7. d4 Nc7
{ The knight attacks the bishop and soon White's centre will come under fire. This is a relatively modern move. The standard continuation used to be  7...cxd4  @@StartBracket@@which is also reasonable@@EndBracket@@ but  7...Nc7  gives White more to think about. }
8. Ba4 { This is the most common move. } 8... cxd4
{ Simplifying the central situation. } 9. cxd4 O-O
{ The king exits in readiness for opening the centre. } 10. Nc3
{ White's central position looks impressive, but Black can hit back. } 10... d6
{ Attacking the spearhead and preparing to apply more pressure on the centre with ...Bg4. }
11. exd6 { White gives up the spearhead. } 11... Qxd6
{ Now the pressure is on the d4 pawn. } 12. d5
{ White does best to advance:  12.Bxc6  Qxc6  might save the d-pawn, but Black has claimed an important bishop. }
12... Na5
{ The knight is not badly placed at the side of the board: there is always the possibility to hop into the c4 square. }
13. Re1 { White puts pressure on the e7-pawn. } 13... Rd8
{ Black replies by putting pressure on the d5-pawn. The position is balanced. }
14. Bg5 Nxd5
{ After this the position burns out, although White has to find some precise moves in order to equalise. }
15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Bxe7 Qxd1 17. Rexd1 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Be6
{ Black's bishops are impressive but, with best play, White should be able to equalise. }
