[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) The Rossolimo: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 4.e5"]
[Black "Rossolimo: 4.e5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Rossolimo rightly has an excellent reputation. White brings out a piece and prepares to castle as quickly as possible. Very often the follow up is c3 and d4 attempting to set up a big pawn centre. Black must know how to fight that, and at the same time bring the king to safety. The task should not be underestimated.   The most popular continuations here are  3...g6  and  3...e6  , but I am recommending a move that cuts across White's plans. }
3... Nf6
{ Bringing out a piece and attacking the e-pawn. In this case, White does not have time to build up with c3 and d4. There are two main responses,  4.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@the most popular@@EndBracket@@ and  4.e5  .  Curiously, these variations can sometimes transpose into each other.In fact, there are so many different move orders available to White @@StartBracket@@which invariably lead to transpositions@@EndBracket@@ that understanding what you are aiming for is as necessary as learning the variations. Therefore I would strongly recommend looking at the model games section to complement your knowledge of variations here. }
4. e5
{ The second most popular move. Curiously, the variations after  4.Nc3  and  4.e5  often transpose into each other. Watch for the knight and its journey from f6 to d4. After  4.e5  Nd5  the knight will often continue ...Nc7-e6-d4.   In the variation with  4.Nc3  g6  5.e5  Ng4  ,  the knight also reaches d4 but via a different route: ...Nh6-f5-d4. }
4... Nd5
{ I would have liked to advocate  4...Ng4  ,  in order to sync with the 4. Nc3 main lines, but unfortunately White has additional options involving c3 and d4 which are best to avoid @@StartBracket@@I'll spare you the details!@@EndBracket@@. In any case, everything is fine with  4...Nd5  ,  and lines often transpose into positions that are familiar. }
5. O-O
{ Instead of this,  5.Nc3  Nc7!  6.Bxc6  dxc6  will soon transpose back into our main line. }
5... g6 { As usual, the bishop develops on g7. } 6. Nc3
{ Black must do something with the knight on d5. } 6... Nc7
{ The best move. Exchanging on c3 @@StartBracket@@  6...Nxc3  7.dxc3  @@EndBracket@@  would have speeded up White's development. }
7. Bxc6 dxc6 { Opening the diagonal for the bishop. } 8. Ne4 b6
{ Protecting the c-pawn. This keeps open the 'threat' of ...Bg4. Black lacks a bit of space, so exchanging off a pair of minor pieces is desirable. That's why  8...b6  should be preferred to  8...Ne6  ,  which would block the c8-bishop. }
9. h3 { Taking away the g4 square from the bishop. } 9... Bg7 10. d3 O-O
{ The king has reached safety and the middlegame can begin. } 11. Re1
{ At this point, Black has a lot of options, and most are reasonable.  11...Ne6  is the most popular, but  11...a5  and  11...h6  are also fine. Instead, I am going to recommend the immediate development of the queen's bishop. }
11... Be6 { Black would like to play ...c4. } 12. b3 f6
{ Challenging White's central control. } 13. exf6
{ White should take or sooner or later Black might play ....f5 - and no en passant would be available. }
13... exf6 14. Bb2 Re8
{ Black's well-placed pieces and sound pawn structure make it difficult for White to make any meaningful incursion. Chances are balanced. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Rossolimo: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 4.Nc3"]
[Black "Rossolimo: 4.Nc3 with 5.Bxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Rossolimo rightly has an excellent reputation. White brings out a piece and prepares to castle as quickly as possible. Very often the follow up is c3 and d4 attempting to set up a big pawn centre. Black must know how to fight that, and at the same time bring the king to safety. The task should not be underestimated.   The most popular continuations here are  3...g6  and  3...e6  , but I am recommending a move that cuts across White's plans. }
3... Nf6
{ Bringing out a piece and attacking the e-pawn. In this case, White does not have time to build up with c3 and d4. There are two main responses,  4.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@the most popular@@EndBracket@@ and  4.e5  .  Curiously, these variations can sometimes transpose into each other.In fact, there are so many different move orders available to White @@StartBracket@@which invariably lead to transpositions@@EndBracket@@ that understanding what you are aiming for is as necessary as learning the variations. Therefore I would strongly recommend looking at the model games section to complement your knowledge of variations here. }
4. Nc3
{ The most sensible move. The knight defends the e-pawn. However, notice that White is now unable to build a pawn centre with c3 and d4 - in that sense Black has already achieved something.   4.Bxc6  usually transposes to lines examined later on after  4...dxc6  5.d3  g6  6.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@for example@@EndBracket@@. See the line 4.Nc3 g6 5.  Bxc6 dxc6 6.h3, etc.   In general in the 3...Nf6 variation, be prepared for flexible move orders. That's why an understanding of typical manoeuvres is  particularly valuable, as well as knowing set lines.   After  4.Nc3  , at this point  4...Qc7  is the most popular response, but I would prefer not to bring out the queen at such an early stage in the game.  4...Nd4  has also been tried, but I find that too risky as it breaks a basic opening rule: do not move the same piece twice in the opening. Instead, let's continue developing. }
4... g6
{ If Black manages to fianchetto the bishop and get castled, the opening will have been concluded satisfactorily. White must cause some disruption. There are basically two ways to play - advance with e5, or don't advance!   The main continuations are  5.Bxc6  and  5.e5  , but  5.h3  should be checked out as Black reacts a little differently. @@StartBracket@@  5.O-O  Bg7  should transpose to one of these lines after  6.e5  or  6.Bxc6  . @@EndBracket@@ }
5. Bxc6
{ It isn't necessary to advance the e-pawn. White can take the game down more traditional routes by taking on c6 and leaving the pawn on e4. }
5... dxc6
{ In general in this variation, it is best to recapture with the d-pawn - it makes development easier. }
6. h3
{ This prevents Black from playing the bishop to g4. Later on, White will play Be3, and ...Ng4 is also excluded. }
6... Bg7 7. d3
{ If you put this position into an openings database you will notice that this position has been reached in more than 3000 games. Yes, we are back in a main line that normally arises from this move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  g6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.d3  Bg7  6.h3  Nf6  7.Nc3  .   So why don't we follow this move order as Black? The reason is that if one plays @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  , apart from  4.Bxc6  @@StartBracket@@and the many different ways that White can play from this position@@EndBracket@@ there is a whole universe to explore with  4.O-O  Bg7  5.c3  - that's tricky, and that's what we are avoiding by playing 3...Nf6. }
7... O-O 8. Be3 b6 9. O-O
{ This is much milder than castling queenside. Black occupies the centre, and is very comfortable. }
9... e5 { An important move, staking a claim in the centre of the board. } 10.
Qd2
{ If  10.Nxe5  Nxe4  11.Nxe4  Bxe5  , and White must take care in order to equalise. }
10... Ne8
{ The knight begins its journey to the outpost on d4. This is a key manoeuvre in the whole variation with 3...Nf6. }
11. Nh2
{ White gets ready to play f4 with some kingside initiative. But Black's position is quite strong enough to withstand the assault. }
11... Nc7 { Continuing the journey to d4. } 12. f4
{ The break has to be played now before the knight arrives on e6. } 12... exf4
{ Exchanging opens up the position for the bishop on g7. } 13. Bxf4 c4
{ Black changes strategy and attacks White's pawn structure. The strong pawn chain c2-d3-e4 gives White security to attack on the kingside. This pawn break weakens the d3-pawn and also brings the c8-bishop into play. Now White should not take:  14.dxc4  Qxd2  15.Bxd2  Be6  16.b3  Rad8  17.Be1  b5  gives Black tremendous play. }
14. Rad1 cxd3 15. cxd3 Ne6
{ The knight will land on d4 and Black can be content. } *

