4... g6
{ If Black manages to fianchetto the bishop and get castled, the opening will have been concluded satisfactorily. White must cause some disruption. There are basically two ways to play - advance with e5, or don't advance!   The main continuations are  5.Bxc6  and  5.e5  , but  5.h3  should be checked out as Black reacts a little differently. @@StartBracket@@  5.O-O  Bg7  should transpose to one of these lines after  6.e5  or  6.Bxc6  . @@EndBracket@@ }
5. h3
{ This takes away the g4 square from Black's knight, so the pawn push e5 is more disruptive. Nevertheless, it is hard to imagine that such a wasted move can cause real difficulties. What does this little pawn move do for White's development? Nothing! }
5... Qc7
{ Black can afford the time to play a 'slow' move, preventing White from advancing the e4-pawn. }
6. O-O Bg7 { A step closer to castling. } 7. Re1
{ White threatens to advance the e-pawn - Black must meet the threat. Instead,  7.Bxc6  Qxc6  is fine for Black has the two bishops. }
7... e5 { Blocking the e4-pawn and staking a claim in the centre. } 8. d3 O-O
9. Bc4
{ There is no point in exchanging on c6. White changes direction and seeks to occupy the d5-square. }
9... d6 10. Bg5 Be6
{ An important move, challenging the d5 square. If you play the Kalashnikov then this kind of position will look familiar @@StartBracket@@remove the c5 and d3-pawns and you'll understand what I mean@@EndBracket@@. Chances are level. }
