[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) The Alapin: 2.c3 e6 with exd5"]
[Black "Alapin with 4.Nd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ If one plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  e6  against the Alapin, the game can quickly transpose into a French Advance variation. This transposition does not occur very often @@StartBracket@@in my direct experience@@EndBracket@@, but one needs to be aware of the possibility and prepare accordingly.An important point to note is that the fixed pawn structure makes strategy easier to grasp: an understand of the principles of the opening will carry you through even if you aren't sure of the details. }
1... c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5
{ Most of my opponents have exchanged on d5 at this point - see the separate chapter on the Alapin. But a couple of players have advanced the e-pawn. }
4. Nd2
{ This is rarely seen as Black can head into a favourable Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@ position. }
4... cxd4 5. cxd4 dxe4 6. Nxe4 { There we are. The IQP is on the board. } 6...
Nf6 { Exchanges generally favour the side playing against the IQP. } 7. Nxf6+
Qxf6 8. Nf3 Bb4+ { Continuing the exchanges and enabling rapid castling. } 9.
Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Rd8 12. O-O Nc6
{ Normally White has kingside pressure to balance the potential weakness of the IQP, but after the exchanges Black's kingside is rock solid. }
13. Rad1 b6 14. Rfe1 Bb7
{ Black has a beautiful position. ...Ne7 is probably on the way, spinning round to the kingside and taking control over the d5-square. }
