1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin is a respectable, if rather pedestrian system. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  White would like to build a strong centre with  d4  and recapture with the c-pawn. In reply, for a long time I flipped between playing  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  @@StartBracket@@the two main lines, and both decent for Black@@EndBracket@@, but for me they are too well known. I like to make my opponent think.   By the way,  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.c3  e6  4.d4  d5  is another possible move order that will transpose to lines considered here. }
2... e6
{ This is an excellent move, yet, according to my database, it is played in fewer than 10% of games starting from this position. Black is going to play ...d5, but intends to recapture with the pawn, not the queen. }
3. d4 { White establishes the pawn centre. } 3... d5
{ Black plays the pawn into the middle. This variation is all about central control!Here White has a choice: exchange on d5 or play the pawn to e5 transposing to the Advance variation of the French Defence. The majority of my opponents exchanged on d5, and that is borne out by the database: it's by far the most common move here, so that needs the most attention. }
4. exd5 exd5
{ By recapturing with the pawn, Black maintains central control. This is classical chess. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 { The knight develops and influences a key square: d4. } 6. Be2
{ A modest move. There is no real pressure on Black's position so development is easy. }
6... Nf6
{ The knight should definitely stand on f6. From there it controls more centre squares. }
7. O-O
{ At this point, Black has two decent continuations. I am recommending  7...Bd6  , but  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bd6  is also reasonable, with a decent Isolated Queen's Pawn position. The bishop operates on an excellent diagonal pointing towards the kingside.   White can also play  8.cxd4  with completely symmetrical pawn structures. Squeezing an advantage out of this position isn't easy, but with  8...Bd6  , at least this bishop is a little better placed than its counterpart. }
7... Bd6
{ Instead of exchanging on d4, I am recommending  7...Bd6  as it has more in common with the main lines after 6. Bb5. }
8. dxc5
{ The most common way to play. White goes for the standard IQP position. It's just like the Bb5 main line, but the bishop stands more passively on e2. For that reason, Black should not have any difficulties in this line. }
8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2 { The knight spins out, as usual. } 9... O-O
{ By now it should be fairly clear where Black's pieces belong. That is the advantage of playing positions with a similar pawn structure, in this case the Isolated Queen's Pawn. }
10. Nb3 Bb6 { The bishop maintains its active position. } 11. Nbd4 Re8
{ It's always pleasant to move the long-range rook to the open file, hitting a bishop. }
12. Be3 Bg4
{ Black's pieces are active and the middlegame can be faced with confidence. }
