[White "3) The Alapin: 2.c3 e6 with exd5"]
[Black "Alapin 6.Bb5 with 9.Re1+ #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin is a respectable, if rather pedestrian system. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  White would like to build a strong centre with  d4  and recapture with the c-pawn. In reply, for a long time I flipped between playing  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  @@StartBracket@@the two main lines, and both decent for Black@@EndBracket@@, but for me they are too well known. I like to make my opponent think.   By the way,  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.c3  e6  4.d4  d5  is another possible move order that will transpose to lines considered here. }
2... e6
{ This is an excellent move, yet, according to my database, it is played in fewer than 10% of games starting from this position. Black is going to play ...d5, but intends to recapture with the pawn, not the queen. }
3. d4 { White establishes the pawn centre. } 3... d5
{ Black plays the pawn into the middle. This variation is all about central control!Here White has a choice: exchange on d5 or play the pawn to e5 transposing to the Advance variation of the French Defence. The majority of my opponents exchanged on d5, and that is borne out by the database: it's by far the most common move here, so that needs the most attention. }
4. exd5 exd5
{ By recapturing with the pawn, Black maintains central control. This is classical chess. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 { The knight develops and influences a key square: d4. } 6. Bb5
{ The most popular move - and the best move. The position is similar to a French Tarrasch @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  c5  4.exd5  exd5  5.Ngf3  Nc6  6.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ except that in our variation the pawn stands on c3 and the queen's knight hasn't yet developed. The difference is small, but it means White is a little slower to develop, and that is already a sign that the variation is quite acceptable for Black. }
6... Bd6
{ The bishop moves to an excellent diagonal. In this position,  7.dxc5  and  7.O-O  are the best and also most popular moves, played in equal measure. In the vast majority of cases these lines will transpose into each other, so I am going to concentrate on  7.dxc5  . I will point out just one idea that is important to know against  7.O-O  . }
7. dxc5 { I will take this is as the main move. } 7... Bxc5
{ The bishop stands actively, pointing down to that perennially sensitive f2 square. }
8. O-O
{ The king should exit before anything else is undertaken. Traditionally, the normal move here is  8...Nge7  - with a probable transposition to a French Tarrasch after  9.Nbd2  . This is a reasonable way for Black to play. However, it has recently been discovered that Black can play more actively with  8...Nf6  . It was always thought that White could exploit the open e-file, but practice has shown that Black is not troubled and more than that, can often seize the initiative. }
8... Nf6 { A more active square than e7. } 9. Re1+
{ Considering that the e-file is open and the king is still in the middle, this is a test of Black's strategy. But there are reasons to be cheerful. Look at the f2-square: it's more sensitive now that the rook has moved away. }
9... Be6
{ A solid block. The most popular moves here are  10.Nd4  and  10.Be3  , but we need to examine  10.Ng5  as well. }
10. Be3
{ This is the most popular move, although it doesn't present Black with any difficulties. White attempts to play positionally, exchanging off the dangerous bishop on c5, but it isn't possible to get a bind on the position. }
10... Bxe3 { No need to waste time. } 11. Rxe3
{ Black has good results from this position. } 11... O-O
{ First get the king out and then think again. } 12. Nbd2
{ The knight comes into play, but Black is the first to get in a threat. }
12... d4
{ This liberates Black's pieces. If you would like to keep more tension in the position,  12...Qb6  is a good move. Which you go for is a question of taste. }
13. cxd4
{ White should exchange. Instead,  13.Rd3  Bf5  traps the rook, and  13.Re1  dxc3  14.bxc3  splits the pawns giving Black a positional advantage. }
13... Nxd4 14. Rd3 Nxf3+ 15. Nxf3 Qb6
{ We can end the variation here. Although the pawn structure is symmetrical, Black's pieces are more active, so White has to take care. Two games have been played from this position - Black won both. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Alapin: French Advance"]
[Black "French Advance: 6.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ If one plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  e6  against the Alapin, the game can quickly transpose into a French Advance variation. This transposition does not occur very often @@StartBracket@@in my direct experience@@EndBracket@@, but one needs to be aware of the possibility and prepare accordingly.An important point to note is that the fixed pawn structure makes strategy easier to grasp: an understand of the principles of the opening will carry you through even if you aren't sure of the details. }
1... c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5
{ Most of my opponents have exchanged on d5 at this point - see the separate chapter on the Alapin. But a couple of players have advanced the e-pawn. }
4. e5
{ You thought you were playing the Sicilian? Not any more. We have transposed into the Advance Variation of the French Defence, normally arrived at via this move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  ,  etc.Even if you aren't a regular practitioner of the French Defence, do not be alarmed: from a theoretical viewpoint, the Advance Variation is not the most challenging of White's options. Having said that, we should still take it seriously. There are many ways for Black to play, but I am going for one of the main lines which has done well for me in practice. }
4... Nc6
{ The knight develops to its natural square, attacking the most important square in this opening - d4. That is so often the source of Black's counterplay. }
5. Nf3 { The knight develops, defending the d4-pawn. } 5... Bd7
{ This bishop move keeps options open for Black. For example, in some variations it will be useful to move the queen to b6, in others, not so useful. All will become clear!   In this position White has three main options,  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@the main line, quite strategic in nature@@EndBracket@@,  6.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@the Milner-Barry Gambit - aggressive@@EndBracket@@,  6.a3  @@StartBracket@@slow and strategic@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Bd3
{ With this French pawn structure, this is the best square for the bishop, slicing across the board towards Black's kingside, ready for a classic Greek Gift sacrifice.So why is this move considered @@StartBracket@@at least at top levels@@EndBracket@@ somewhat dubious? Because it involves the sacrifice of a pawn. This is the so-called Milner-Barry Gambit, named after Sir Stuart Milner-Barry, who played for England in the late 1930s and into the 1950s. He was an amateur player and in real life pursued a distinguished career as a top government civil servant. He was also one of the Enigma code breakers team at Bletchley Park during World War II. Apart from that, he was a fine and generous man and I am privileged to have known him personally.On the chessboard he was a daring attacking player who invented several opening ideas. His gambit against the French has been a favourite with club players for decades. As a kid, I played it too! It's dangerous if you don't have a clue, but thankfully, these days, we do. }
6... cxd4 { It is best to exchange pawns, before White decides to take on c5. }
7. cxd4 Qb6 { Black attacks the d4-pawn and White does best to give it up. } 8.
O-O
{ This is the starting position of the Milner-Barry Gambit. Instead of  8.O-O  , White could hold on to the pawn by playing  8.Bc2  but in that case Black snags the bishop with  8...Nb4  9.Nc3  Nxc2+  10.Qxc2  Ne7  and has a clear positional advantage. White cannot tolerate playing without the light-squared bishop.   8.Be2  would also not be great: White is simply a tempo down on usual lines. For the sake of completeness I should mention that  8.Be3  Qxb2  9.Nbd2  Nb4  is already winning for Black. }
8... Nxd4
{ It's worth taking this pawn - it is such an important point in White's position. By the way, this is only possible because Black's bishop stands on d7 :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Nbd2
{ This is a modern way of playing the position. White concentrates on development and certainly has some compensation. I recommend that Black exchanges off pieces to ease the complexity of the position. }
9... Nxf3+ 10. Nxf3 Bb5
{ Once White's bishop disappears from the board, so does a lot of the danger. }
11. Be3 Qa6 12. Bxb5+ Qxb5
{ If you are a pawn up, then exchanging pieces is definitely desirable. The downside is that in concentrating on exchanges, Black has neglected kingside development. White uses the lead in development to gain a little initiative. }
13. Nd4 Qd7 { Safely back home. } 14. Rc1 { Hitting the open file. } 14... Ne7
{ The knight leaps over to cover. } 15. Qd3 Nc6
{ This forces White to exchange and further reduces the danger. } 16. Nxc6 bxc6
17. Rc2 a5
{ Preventing the queen from moving to a6, but also setting up a press on the two queenside pawns. }
18. Rfc1 { White wins back the pawn, but the position is level. } 18... c5
{ White has to capture the pawn, but that helps Black to develop the kingside. }
19. Bxc5 Bxc5 20. Rxc5 O-O
{ The king has escaped and Black has developed, or rather exchanged off, all the minor pieces. White's rooks look impressive, but they can't do much. Black remains with the beautiful French pawn structure which makes the position very solid, and there are chances to counter-attack against the queenside pawns. For example, if  21.Rc7  Qa4  22.a3  Rab8  gives Black the initiative. }
*

