1. e4
{ If one plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  e6  against the Alapin, the game can quickly transpose into a French Advance variation. This transposition does not occur very often @@StartBracket@@in my direct experience@@EndBracket@@, but one needs to be aware of the possibility and prepare accordingly.An important point to note is that the fixed pawn structure makes strategy easier to grasp: an understand of the principles of the opening will carry you through even if you aren't sure of the details. }
1... c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5
{ Most of my opponents have exchanged on d5 at this point - see the separate chapter on the Alapin. But a couple of players have advanced the e-pawn. }
4. e5
{ You thought you were playing the Sicilian? Not any more. We have transposed into the Advance Variation of the French Defence, normally arrived at via this move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  ,  etc.Even if you aren't a regular practitioner of the French Defence, do not be alarmed: from a theoretical viewpoint, the Advance Variation is not the most challenging of White's options. Having said that, we should still take it seriously. There are many ways for Black to play, but I am going for one of the main lines which has done well for me in practice. }
4... Nc6
{ The knight develops to its natural square, attacking the most important square in this opening - d4. That is so often the source of Black's counterplay. }
5. Nf3 { The knight develops, defending the d4-pawn. } 5... Bd7
{ This bishop move keeps options open for Black. For example, in some variations it will be useful to move the queen to b6, in others, not so useful. All will become clear!   In this position White has three main options,  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@the main line, quite strategic in nature@@EndBracket@@,  6.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@the Milner-Barry Gambit - aggressive@@EndBracket@@,  6.a3  @@StartBracket@@slow and strategic@@EndBracket@@. }
6. a3
{ This is quite a trendy move. White intends shutting down Black's queenside counterplay by expanding with b4. This is quite a decent system against an early ...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@for example, in the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  e6  3.d4  d5  4.e5  Nc6  5.Nf3  Qb6  6.a3  @@EndBracket@@,  but in this particular position, with the queen still on d8, it is less effective. }
6... c4
{ This move discourages White from playing b4. The position becomes even more closed as the pawn structures lock together, and we are set for a period of manoeuvring. }
7. g3
{ Along with 7. Nbd2, this is one of the most popular moves. As before, Black faces a choice, to play a protracted manoeuvring game starting with  7...Na5  , when it will be a long time before either player is able to achieve a pawn break, or break in the centre immediately with  7...f6  .  The pawn advance is my recommendation against 7. Nbd2, so let's be consistent and also minimise the work load. The ideas are very similar and in some cases the variations transpose. }
7... f6 8. Qe2
{ In this line I am examining something a little different for White. The alternatives  8.exf6  Nxf6  and @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1b2pp/2n1pp2/3pP3/2pP4/P1P2NP1/1P3P1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bg2  fxe5  will in all likelihood transpose to variations considered under 7. Nbd2. }
8... fxe5 { Black opens up lines, looking to get a lead in development. } 9.
Nxe5 Nxe5 { The knight is strong and must be eliminated. } 10. Qxe5 Nf6 11. Bg2
Qb6 { The queen on e5 needs to be driven away. } 12. O-O Bd6 13. Qe2 O-O 14.
Nd2
{ Black has completed development, but there is a strategic issue that needs addressing: if White is able to get control over the e5-square there could be trouble. }
14... Be8
{ An excellent move, and so typical of the French. The 'bad' bishop bounces off the back rank to get to a great diagonal. The bad bishop bounce... where have I heard that before? The Kalashnikov! Yes, it is indeed very similar to that opening when Black plays ...Be7-d8-b6.   If Black had played  14...Rae8  , then White would be able to clamp with  15.Nf3  . }
15. Qxe6+ Bf7
{ Getting rid of the pawn means that Black's pieces will be able to attack down the e-file. }
16. Qh3 Rae8
{ Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. There is potential for the rook to land on e2 and for the bishop to pop out to g6 and then down to d3. In the meantime, it isn't easy for White to develop with the queen on b6 preventing the bishop on c1 from moving. }
