{ The knight develops to its natural square, attacking the most important square in this opening - d4. That is so often the source of Black's counterplay. }
5. Nf3 { The knight develops, defending the d4-pawn. } 5... Bd7
{ This bishop move keeps options open for Black. For example, in some variations it will be useful to move the queen to b6, in others, not so useful. All will become clear!   In this position White has three main options,  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@the main line, quite strategic in nature@@EndBracket@@,  6.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@the Milner-Barry Gambit - aggressive@@EndBracket@@,  6.a3  @@StartBracket@@slow and strategic@@EndBracket@@. }
