{ This move is favoured by Mikhail Gurevich, the 1985 Soviet champion, who is a noted expert on the French Defence. Black gains territory on the queenside. This continues the policy of pressing on the b2-pawn. White has a slight problem: three pieces are consigned to defending the d-pawn. How is it possible to free up the position? }
11. g4
{ Black's knight is pushed away from f5, relieving the pressure on the d4-pawn. All very well, but how does White's king feel now? }
11... Nfe7
{ Back again, but it has been worth it as White has been provoked into creating huge holes around the king. The only way for White to justify the g-pawn's advance is to bring the f-pawn into play as well. }
12. Nh4
{ The knight makes way for the f-pawn to advance @@StartBracket@@potentially@@EndBracket@@. }
12... f6
{ With this Black is able to break down White's pawn spearhead on e5. } 13.
exf6 { Instead,  13.f4?  fxe5  14.fxe5  Nxe5  wins a pawn. } 13... gxf6
{ The position is finely balanced. From a purely positional perspective, Black can be happy that he now has a majority of pawns in the centre, and there are also chances to attack White's weakened kingside. On the other hand, it isn't absolutely clear where Black's king should be heading: kingside or queenside? Or perhaps it remains in the middle. It really depends on how White plays. Black's next move will almost certainly be ...Ng6 and then the bishop can move to d6 or g7. }
