[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) The Morra Gambit"]
[Black "Morra Gambit: 8.h3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ The Morra Gambit is popular at club level so it is worth examining carefully. What does White gain for the pawn? A little bit of activity, a slight lead in development, but that is about it. Crucially, Black's pawn structure is still intact. If Black follows the right steps at the beginning there are good chances to consolidate the extra pawn. With great accuracy, White can equalise, but that is hardly a ringing recommendation for the opening. Remember, Black needs to play the first few moves correctly, and in the right order! }
2... cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 { The starting point of the Morra Gambit. } 4...
Nc6 { Sound development. A knight into the middle. } 5. Nf3 d6
{ This is like a normal open Sicilian position, except that White lacks a pawn on c2. }
6. Bc4
{ An important moment in the game. There are some ancient traps here. First of all, don't play  6...Nf6  - that allows  7.e5!  dxe5  8.Qxd8+  Nxd8  9.Nb5  with a great attack. And don't play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/8/2B1P3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , allowing  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Ng5+  . }
6... a6
{ A standard Sicilian move, guarding the b5 square, but there is a specific reason to play it at this moment. }
7. O-O Nf6
{ It's okay to play the knight here now that ...a6 has been played. } 8. h3
{ Considering that ...Bg4 is such an annoying move, it is understandable that White wishes to prevent it. But this little move at the side of the board cannot cause Black too much trouble. }
8... e6
{ Black can carry on developing normally knowing that White has essentially wasted a move with 8. h3. Black's strong central pawn cell is a great asset in the Sicilian. }
9. Qe2 Be7 { Simple and sound development. Black prepares to castle. } 10. Rd1
{ Now Black must pay attention as White threatens to play e5. } 10... b5
{ Black strikes back. The pawn carves out territory on the queenside. } 11. Bb3
{ Instead,  11.e5  bxc4  12.exf6  gxf6  13.Qxc4  Bb7  gives Black a huge attack down the g-file. The king is safe in the middle. }
11... Qb6
{ The queen moves away from trouble on the d-file and supports the b-pawn. }
12. Bf4
{ White targets the d-pawn. Instead,  12.Be3  Qb8  is perfectly safe for Black. }
12... Na5 { The knight activates and the queen now defends the pawn on d6. }
13. Bc2 Bb7
{ The bishop reaches the long diagonal. This is a good Sicilian Defence position - and Black has an extra pawn! }
14. e5 dxe5 15. Nxe5 Rc8
{ We are following the game Berg - Hillarp Persson, Gothenburg 2013. Black has a strong position: apart from the extra pawn, the queenside pieces are active, and the king is safe in the middle, although there is always the option to castle out of trouble. }
*

