{ It's okay to play the knight here now that ...a6 has been played. } 8. e5
{ With the pawn on a6, this does not hold any danger for Black. } 8... dxe5
{ Just to be clear, Black should not play  8...Nxe5?  9.Nxe5  dxe5  10.Bxf7+  Kxf7  11.Qxd8  . Yet another cheap trick! No wonder the Morra is so popular at certain levels. But we have to rise above it. }
9. Qxd8+
{ White has nothing better than the endgame.  9.Bxf7+  Kxf7  does not win Black's queen. }
9... Nxd8 10. Nxe5 Be6
{ Black is a safe pawn up. With every exchange, the extra pawn weighs more. }
11. Be2 { A clever retreat.  11.Bxe6  Nxe6  would only help Black. } 11... g6
{ Time to bring out the kingside pieces. } 12. Bf3
{ The bishop emerges on to a great diagonal, tying down Black's pieces. } 12...
Rc8 { The rook steps away from the beam of the bishop. } 13. Rd1 Bg7 14. Be3
O-O
{ Black is a pawn up and has a solid position. White has a little compensation as the knight on d8 gets in the way of the rooks. The knight can move out to c6, but that splits the queenside pawns. Against accurate play, Black might have problems squeezing out a win, but the pressure will be on White to hold the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) The Morra Gambit"]
[Black "Morra Gambit: 8.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ The Morra Gambit is popular at club level so it is worth examining carefully. What does White gain for the pawn? A little bit of activity, a slight lead in development, but that is about it. Crucially, Black's pawn structure is still intact. If Black follows the right steps at the beginning there are good chances to consolidate the extra pawn. With great accuracy, White can equalise, but that is hardly a ringing recommendation for the opening. Remember, Black needs to play the first few moves correctly, and in the right order! }
2... cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 { The starting point of the Morra Gambit. } 4...
Nc6 { Sound development. A knight into the middle. } 5. Nf3 d6
{ This is like a normal open Sicilian position, except that White lacks a pawn on c2. }
6. Bc4
{ An important moment in the game. There are some ancient traps here. First of all, don't play  6...Nf6  - that allows  7.e5!  dxe5  8.Qxd8+  Nxd8  9.Nb5  with a great attack. And don't play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/8/2B1P3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , allowing  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Ng5+  . }
6... a6
{ A standard Sicilian move, guarding the b5 square, but there is a specific reason to play it at this moment. }
7. O-O Nf6
{ It's okay to play the knight here now that ...a6 has been played. } 8. Bf4
{ This is the best move against Black's system. With accurate play, White should be able to equalise :@@EndBracket@@ }
8... Bg4
{ I believe that Black does best to continue with the original plan of pinning. One could also try  8...e6  , but that is more complicated. }
9. Qb3
{ A double attack on b7 and f7. Do not worry, one just has to be aware of a little tactic that will decide the game in Black's favour... }
9... e6 { Bxf7+ is prevented. } 10. Qxb7
{ This is unsound, but one has to prove it... } 10... Na5
{ A knight fork, forcing the queen backwards. } 11. Qb4 e5
{ This is the spectacular winning move. What is the point? It is all about allowing the bishop on g4 back to block on d7.   To understand, let's look at what would happen if Black played instead  11...Rb8  . Then White would win with  12.Qa4+  .   That defence does not hold now. After  11...e5  ,  Black threatens the bishop on f4 as well as ....Rb8 winning the loose bishop on c4. White cannot defend against both threats. }
12. Bxe5
{ This is an attempt to muddy the waters, but Black can safely win material. Instead  12.Bg5  Rb8  13.Qa3  d5  14.Qa4+  Bd7!  That's the point! Black wins material. }
12... Rb8 { This is even better than taking the bishop straightaway. } 13. Qa4+
{ 13.Qa3  dxe5!  attacks the queen with the bishop on f8. } 13... Bd7
{ That's the point! As the e-pawn advanced the bishop was able to drop back to block. }
14. Bxf6 gxf6
{ After the exchange, nothing has changed: White is still losing the bishop. }
15. Bxf7+ Kxf7 16. Qd1 Nc6
{ White has two pawns for the piece, but that is scant compensation. Black's position is essentially sound and the two bishops an important asset. With care it should be winning for Black. }
*

