[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) The Grand Prix Attack with 5.Bc4"]
[Black "GP Attack with 5.Bc4, 6.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the favoured way of entering into the Grand Prix Attack for White.  2.f4  has been discredited because of  2...d5  - see the 2. f4 chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 { The launch of the f-pawn signifies The Grand Prix Attack. }
3... g6
{ The bishop belongs on the long diagonal, influencing the centre. In particular, the d4 square is pivotal in this opening. }
4. Nf3 Bg7
{ Move order is important. Notice that Black has not yet committed the d- or e-pawns. Having that flexibility is helpful in combatting White's strategy. Here White has a choice of where to play the king's bishop: c4 or b5. }
5. Bc4 { This is a direct attempt to attack, but it is a bit too crude. } 5...
e6
{ If the bishop is pointing down the diagonal, it makes perfect sense to block it out. }
6. O-O Nge7
{ With the knight on e7, Black prepares to castle and to advance the d-pawn. }
7. Qe1
{ Because of the pin on the e-file, Black is unable to advance the d-pawn. By the way,  7.d3  will probably transpose back to this line after  7...d5  8.Bb3  O-O  9.Qe1  Nd4  etc. }
7... O-O { Black is very happy to castle, threatening to advance the d-pawn. }
8. e5
{ As usual if White advances the e-pawn, then Black should break it down immediately. }
8... d6 { Breaking down White's spearhead. } 9. exd6 Nf5
{ The knight stands beautifully here and might flip back to take the pawn.   It is also possible to play  9...Qxd6  ,  but that would give White the chance to attack the queen with Ne4 and reorganise a little. }
10. d3 Nxd6
{ White has no attack to speak of as the f-pawn cannot advance. Black's bishop on g7 powers through the middle and the knights both have potential. }
11. Bb3 b6 12. Ne5 Nd4 13. Ne4 Bb7
{ We are following the game Guevara Sanchez-Stefansson, Yerevan Olympiad 1996. White is already in trouble as the fianchettoed bishops give Black enormous potential. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) The Grand Prix Attack with 5.Bc4"]
[Black "GP Attack with 5.Bc4, 6.O-O #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the favoured way of entering into the Grand Prix Attack for White.  2.f4  has been discredited because of  2...d5  - see the 2. f4 chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 { The launch of the f-pawn signifies The Grand Prix Attack. }
3... g6
{ The bishop belongs on the long diagonal, influencing the centre. In particular, the d4 square is pivotal in this opening. }
4. Nf3 Bg7
{ Move order is important. Notice that Black has not yet committed the d- or e-pawns. Having that flexibility is helpful in combatting White's strategy. Here White has a choice of where to play the king's bishop: c4 or b5. }
5. Bc4 { This is a direct attempt to attack, but it is a bit too crude. } 5...
e6
{ If the bishop is pointing down the diagonal, it makes perfect sense to block it out. }
6. O-O Nge7
{ With the knight on e7, Black prepares to castle and to advance the d-pawn. }
7. Qe1
{ Because of the pin on the e-file, Black is unable to advance the d-pawn. By the way,  7.d3  will probably transpose back to this line after  7...d5  8.Bb3  O-O  9.Qe1  Nd4  etc. }
7... O-O { Black is very happy to castle, threatening to advance the d-pawn. }
8. d3 d5
{ Pushing the bishop back and at the same time, Black takes control in the centre. }
9. Bb3 Nd4
{ By planting the knight in the middle, Black is able to cut across White's kingside attacking plans. }
10. Nxd4
{ White cannot live with the magnificent knight on d4 and must exchange. }
10... cxd4 11. Ne2 dxe4 12. dxe4
{ After this exchange, play takes place in the centre and on the queenside. White has no possibility to initiate a kingside attack - which will frustrate your Grand Prix Attack opponents! }
12... b5
{ Black takes the initiative. Depending on how White plays, the follow up might be ...a5, or perhaps...d3, or the bishop might move to b7, raking down the long diagonal. }
