[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) The Grand Prix Attack with 5.Bc4"]
[Black "GP Attack with 5.Bc4, 6.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the favoured way of entering into the Grand Prix Attack for White.  2.f4  has been discredited because of  2...d5  - see the 2. f4 chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 { The launch of the f-pawn signifies The Grand Prix Attack. }
3... g6
{ The bishop belongs on the long diagonal, influencing the centre. In particular, the d4 square is pivotal in this opening. }
4. Nf3 Bg7
{ Move order is important. Notice that Black has not yet committed the d- or e-pawns. Having that flexibility is helpful in combatting White's strategy. Here White has a choice of where to play the king's bishop: c4 or b5. }
5. Bc4 { This is a direct attempt to attack, but it is a bit too crude. } 5...
e6
{ If the bishop is pointing down the diagonal, it makes perfect sense to block it out. }
6. e5
{ Frankly, if your opponent plays this, you know that they have very little strategic sense. White wants to play Ne4 and land the knight on d6, but this can be easily countered. The problem with advancing the e-pawn is that it allows Black to use the d5 and f5 squares. }
6... d6
{ Breaking down the pawn on e5 before White gets a chance to play the knight into e4. }
7. exd6 Nf6
{ A little finesse. The simple  7...Qxd6  is perfectly playable, but instead, let's develop the king's knight to its best square first, preventing White from playing the knight to e4. }
8. O-O O-O
{ The king reaches safety and then it's time to scoop up the pawn on d6. } 9.
d3 Qxd6
{ The central pawn duo has been broken up, which means it is hard for White to make progress on the kingside. The pawn on f4 has no hope of advancing and merely blocks the bishop on c1. Black has good control over the d5 and d4-squares and will play the queen's bishop to the long diagonal. }
10. Ne4 Qc7
{ The queen maintains control over the e5-square. That is why I prefer to put the queen on c7 instead of e7 @@StartBracket@@although that is also playable!@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Nxc5 { This would be a mistake: } 11... Na5 { Black recovers the pawn. }
12. Nb3 Nxc4 13. dxc4 Qxc4
{ Black has the two bishops. They are both powerful pieces but in particular the light-squared bishop, without an opponent, has the potential to be a monster. Black will soon be able to play ...b6 and ...Bb7 and has the better position. }
*

