5. Bc4 { This is a direct attempt to attack, but it is a bit too crude. } 5...
e6
{ If the bishop is pointing down the diagonal, it makes perfect sense to block it out. }
6. e5
{ Frankly, if your opponent plays this, you know that they have very little strategic sense. White wants to play Ne4 and land the knight on d6, but this can be easily countered. The problem with advancing the e-pawn is that it allows Black to use the d5 and f5 squares. }
6... d6
