d3 Qxd6
{ The central pawn duo has been broken up, which means it is hard for White to make progress on the kingside. The pawn on f4 has no hope of advancing and merely blocks the bishop on c1. Black has good control over the d5 and d4-squares and will play the queen's bishop to the long diagonal. }
10. Ne4 Qc7
{ The queen maintains control over the e5-square. That is why I prefer to put the queen on c7 instead of e7 @@StartBracket@@although that is also playable!@@EndBracket@@. }
11. c3 b6 { Supporting the c-pawn and getting ready to play ...Bb7. } 12. Kh1
Bb7
{ Black will play a rook to the d-file and put pressure on the d3-pawn. Both bishops are splendidly placed on the long diagonals. White's king has comparatively scant pawn cover, and in the long run that could give Black a chance to attack. }
