[White "6) The Grand Prix Attack with 5.Bc4"]
[Black "GP Attack with 5.Bc4, 6.f5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the favoured way of entering into the Grand Prix Attack for White.  2.f4  has been discredited because of  2...d5  - see the 2. f4 chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 { The launch of the f-pawn signifies The Grand Prix Attack. }
3... g6
{ The bishop belongs on the long diagonal, influencing the centre. In particular, the d4 square is pivotal in this opening. }
4. Nf3 Bg7
{ Move order is important. Notice that Black has not yet committed the d- or e-pawns. Having that flexibility is helpful in combatting White's strategy. Here White has a choice of where to play the king's bishop: c4 or b5. }
5. Bc4 { This is a direct attempt to attack, but it is a bit too crude. } 5...
e6
{ If the bishop is pointing down the diagonal, it makes perfect sense to block it out. }
6. f5
{ This is the most testing move. White offers a pawn while Black's king is still in the centre. Should you take the bait or ignore it? And if you take it, with which pawn? It's easy to see how such an early challenge succeeded in confusing so many players in tough weekend tournaments.   Let me sum up the options for Black. First, let's rule out  6...exf5  . No! That opens the diagonal for the bishop and is more trouble than it is worth.  6...gxf5  is playable for Black, but you need to have your eyes wide open. With the kingside opening up, this can get tricky. Instead of these, I recommend simple development with  6...Nge7  . }
6... Nge7
{ A solid and sound move. Black develops a piece and prepares to castle. In my experience this unpretentious response confounds the Grand Prix hackers! }
7. fxe6
{ To avoid serious disadvantage, White has to exchange on e6. For example,  7.O-O  d5  , or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pnpbp/2n1p1p1/2p2P2/2B1P3/2N2N2/PPPP2PP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.d3  d5  , and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pnpbp/2n1p1p1/2p2P2/2B1P3/2N2N2/PPPP2PP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.fxg6  hxg6!  followed by ...d5 and the semi-open h-file could be very useful for Black. }
7... dxe6
{ By recapturing with the d-pawn, Black maintains a solid pawn front on the kingside, which means it will be difficult for White to mount an attack. This is more reliable than  7...fxe6  which leaves the king a little open. }
8. d3 O-O
{ The king is safe behind a wall of pawns and the protection of the bishop on g7. }
9. O-O
{ Black is not under threat and has a range of options:  9...Na5  is the most popular move, preparing to pick off the bishop, but  9...Nd4  ,  9...b6  , and  9...h6  are all decent alternatives, demonstrating the essential soundness of Black's position. }
9... h6
{ This move is favoured by computers, covering the important g5-square. It also heralds a kingside counter-attack. }
10. Qe1
{ I know what Grand Prix Attack players like to do - nine times out of ten they will follow the standard scheme and transfer the queen to the kingside. But Black is ready! }
10... g5
{ According to any computer you may care to consult, Black already stands better! }
11. a3
{ White gives the bishop an escape square on a2. This is not the most active move on the board and is an indication that the standard kingside attack has ground to a halt. }
11... Ng6 12. Nd1 g4 13. Nd2 Nce5
{ We are following the game Boghossian-Grollemund, France 2004 @@StartBracket@@see the model games section@@EndBracket@@. Black has already taken over the initiative and won convincingly. }
