[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Grand Prix Attack with 5.Bb5"]
[Black "GP Attack with 5.Bb5, 6.Nxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5
{ You may have noticed that in the variations against the 5. Bc4 Grand Prix Attack, Black often gains counterplay by planting the knight on d4, disrupting the flow of White's development and putting a massive spanner in the works of the kingside attack. That's what playing the bishop to b5 is all about: If  5...d6  6.Bxc6+!  bxc6  7.O-O  ,  White can be delighted with his position. Black cannot play the knight into d4 and White has a free hand to attack on the kingside with all the usual moves such as d3, Qe1, f5, Qh4, etc.I've seen it and played it a hundred times and, trust me, it is highly dangerous. Black has to avoid this. That's why the next move is clear. }
5... Nd4
{ As in so many variations of the closed Sicilians, the knight is powerful on d4, disrupting White's development. In this particular case, it leaves the bishop dangling on b5 with nothing to do. So was 5. Bb5 just a one-move trick? Was White just hoping to make that sneaky exchange on c6? Frankly, yes! }
6. Nxd4
{ This is the second most popular move, according to my database. It's not very good for White. }
6... cxd4 { Black gains time. } 7. Ne2
{ The knight has been pushed back to a poor square, blocking White's pieces. }
7... Nh6
{ I like this knight move! You'll see that in the main line with 6. O-O, it also features. Why does this appeal to me? Because if Black develops rapidly, there is more chance of catching out the opposition. The aim is to castle as quickly as possible, but more than that, the knight is sometimes able to leap to g4 causing problems, and if White's pawn advances to e5, it will establish itself on f5. }
8. O-O
{ The king needs to get out of the middle. That loose bishop on b5 is a cause for concern. Instead, if  8.d3?  Qa5+  wins a piece :@@EndBracket@@ Hehe. }
8... O-O
{ Don't waste time! Get the king to safety and then you will be ready to strike. Notice how Black has not wasted time on superfluous pawn moves. }
9. d3
{ 9.Ng3  is examined in the Model Games chapter: Mossong-Popovic, Vilnius 1995. }
9... d5
{ That's a big hit. Black starts to break up the pawn duo on e4 and f4. } 10.
Kh1 { Trick alert! } 10... Qa5 { traps the bishop on b5! } 11. a4 a6 12. Ra3
{ White can only delay the inevitable. } 12... Bg4
{ Now that the rook on a8 is protected, it will be safe to capture the bishop. }
*

