{ You may have noticed that in the variations against the 5. Bc4 Grand Prix Attack, Black often gains counterplay by planting the knight on d4, disrupting the flow of White's development and putting a massive spanner in the works of the kingside attack. That's what playing the bishop to b5 is all about: If  5...d6  6.Bxc6+!  bxc6  7.O-O  ,  White can be delighted with his position. Black cannot play the knight into d4 and White has a free hand to attack on the kingside with all the usual moves such as d3, Qe1, f5, Qh4, etc.I've seen it and played it a hundred times and, trust me, it is highly dangerous. Black has to avoid this. That's why the next move is clear. }
