[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5
{ You may have noticed that in the variations against the 5. Bc4 Grand Prix Attack, Black often gains counterplay by planting the knight on d4, disrupting the flow of White's development and putting a massive spanner in the works of the kingside attack. That's what playing the bishop to b5 is all about: If  5...d6  6.Bxc6+!  bxc6  7.O-O  ,  White can be delighted with his position. Black cannot play the knight into d4 and White has a free hand to attack on the kingside with all the usual moves such as d3, Qe1, f5, Qh4, etc.I've seen it and played it a hundred times and, trust me, it is highly dangerous. Black has to avoid this. That's why the next move is clear. }
5... Nd4
{ As in so many variations of the closed Sicilians, the knight is powerful on d4, disrupting White's development. In this particular case, it leaves the bishop dangling on b5 with nothing to do. So was 5. Bb5 just a one-move trick? Was White just hoping to make that sneaky exchange on c6? Frankly, yes! }
6. O-O
{ The most popular move. Black has a big choice here and to some extent it is a question of taste which move you select. For example, many players like to exchange off knight for bishop - that's fine. Instead, I recommend pushing back the bishop to an awkward square. }
6... a6 7. Bd3
{ The bishop needs to return here, but really, what a dreadful square, blocking the d-pawn! Black has great chances to catch out his gummed up opponent. }
7... Nh6
{ Black has several decent moves available, but developing a piece appeals to me the most. This is not the most popular move @@StartBracket@@the unpretentious  7...d6  is number 1 in the database@@EndBracket@@, but I believe the knight move is highly dangerous for White. }
8. f5
{ This attacking stab is ineffective when White has no prospect of bringing the queen's bishop into play. }
8... e6
{ I like this calm move, encouraging White to exchange off the pawn on f5 which immediately renders the whole pawn sacrifice as useless. }
9. Nxd4 cxd4 { Gaining time and pushing the knight to a poor square. } 10. Ne2
O-O
{ First things first - Black brings the king to safety before taking any direct action. There is time to do this as White's pieces are in such a jam. }
11. Nf4 d5
{ Before White has a chance to develop the queenside, Black strikes in the middle. Playing with Black, I would already be thinking about a quick win. There is a threat to take on e4 and then on f5, so White has to exchange pawns. }
12. fxe6 fxe6 { The f-file opens. Yum. } 13. exd5 Be5
{ A finesse that allows Black to damage White's kingside. } 14. Nxe6 Bxh2+
{ A highly successful Greek Gift sacrifice. This is not complicated! } 15. Kxh2
Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Bxe6 17. dxe6 Ng4 { And game over. } *

