{ This pawn thrust highlights the problem with playing the immediate 2. f4. The pawn duo on e4 and f4 are broken up and that prevents White from building a kingside attack. White has three responses, all of them are satisfactory for Black. }
3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black has succeeded in getting rid of the e-pawn and with such a fluid centre it will be difficult for White to launch a kingside attack. The pawn on f4, now on its own, is more of a liability than an asset: White's king isn't very secure with just the g and h pawns as cover.Structurally, Black is much more comfortable than White: the c-pawn does a good job of securing the d4-square, and Black's king will have four pawns for cover once it castles.   The most popular move at this point is  4...Qc7  and development is easy;  4...e6  is also playable; as is  4...Nd7  .  Databases show that results are more than satisfactory for Black. Instead of these, the move I would like to recommend is somewhat unusual. I want to shake up the opposition! }
4... Nf6
{ This challenges White right at the start of the game. Who knows, they might already make a mistake. The move also has the bonus of being sound. }
5. Bb5+
{ This is probably the safest choice for White, looking to exchange some pieces and in that way speed up development @@StartBracket@@a little@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bd7 6. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ The knight develops and at the same protects the c5 pawn. } 7. Qe2
{ Threatening mate in one, by the way. } 7... Qc7
{ Threatening the f-pawn, as well as preventing the mate. If instead  7...e6  , then  8.f5  is mildly irritating. }
8. d3 { Guarding the f-pawn. } 8... g6 9. Nf3 Bg7
{ The bishop develops on the most active square, raking down the diagonal. }
10. O-O O-O
{ The middlegame begins. With the pawn on c5 Black has a little more control in the centre than White.I believe that this is the best White can achieve in the variation after 4...Nf6: clear proof that the pawn push with 2. f4 is simply premature. }
