4... Nf6
{ This challenges White right at the start of the game. Who knows, they might already make a mistake. The move also has the bonus of being sound. }
5. Nxc5
{ Grabbing the pawn is risky in the extreme as it turbo-charges Black's development. In practice, only one player has grabbed the pawn, and they achieved a lost position after just a few more moves. For the record, the machines believe that Black's position is more than satisfactory after the pawn grab. }
5... e5
{ With this, we are about to transpose into a kind of King's Gambit. What did you say? KG? Yes, really! }
6. Nb3
{ This is the most prudent reaction, although Black will still gain excellent chances. }
6... exf4
{ Compare the position on the board to this variation of the King's Gambit: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.f4  exf4  3.Nf3  d5  4.exd5  Nf6  5.Bb5+  c6  6.dxc6  Nxc6  .  Very similar! This line also has a good reputation for Black. In both cases you can see that Black has very free development, on the other hand, it isn't so easy for White.   By the way, instead of  6...exf4  , there is another intriguing possibility,  6...e4  , which has the hallmarks of a Falkbeer counter gambit. }
7. Nf3 Nc6
{ The knight moves into the centre: stick to the opening principles! } 8. d4
{ White threatens to capture on f4. } 8... Bd6
{ The bishop moves into play and protects the pawn on f4. } 9. Bd3 O-O
{ With a threat to check on e8. } 10. O-O Nb4 11. c4
{ White has to compromise and give up the bishop pair. Instead,  11.Be2  Bf5  12.Ne1  Re8  is more trouble for White than it is worth. }
11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 a5
{ This is an awkward stab for White to meet and highlights the poor position of the knight on b3. }
13. a4
{ This prevents the knight from being attacked, but the pawn on a4 can turn out to be a weakness and the b4-square is weakened. }
13... Re8 14. Bd2 b6
{ Depending on how White plays, the bishop might appear on a6 or b7. White's centre is vulnerable to attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Grand Prix Attack: 2.f4"]
[Black "GP Attack 2.f4: 3.Nc3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ This has been discredited as a way of entering the Grand Prix Attack. Instead, those in the know play  2.Nc3  so as to prevent Black from playing ...d5. }
2... d5
{ This pawn thrust highlights the problem with playing the immediate 2. f4. The pawn duo on e4 and f4 are broken up and that prevents White from building a kingside attack. White has three responses, all of them are satisfactory for Black. }
3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black has succeeded in getting rid of the e-pawn and with such a fluid centre it will be difficult for White to launch a kingside attack. The pawn on f4, now on its own, is more of a liability than an asset: White's king isn't very secure with just the g and h pawns as cover.Structurally, Black is much more comfortable than White: the c-pawn does a good job of securing the d4-square, and Black's king will have four pawns for cover once it castles.   The most popular move at this point is  4...Qc7  and development is easy;  4...e6  is also playable; as is  4...Nd7  .  Databases show that results are more than satisfactory for Black. Instead of these, the move I would like to recommend is somewhat unusual. I want to shake up the opposition! }
4... Nf6
{ This challenges White right at the start of the game. Who knows, they might already make a mistake. The move also has the bonus of being sound. }
5. Nxc5
{ Grabbing the pawn is risky in the extreme as it turbo-charges Black's development. In practice, only one player has grabbed the pawn, and they achieved a lost position after just a few more moves. For the record, the machines believe that Black's position is more than satisfactory after the pawn grab. }
5... e5
{ With this, we are about to transpose into a kind of King's Gambit. What did you say? KG? Yes, really! }
6. fxe5 { This is foolhardy. } 6... Bxc5
{ The bishop snaps off the knight and arrives at a prime location for attacking the enemy king. }
7. exf6 O-O
{ It's all about speedy development. This looks like a game from the 19th century where Morphy slaps down a rank amateur with a couple of powerful moves. }
8. Nf3 Re8+ 9. Be2 Bg4
{ Black has a winning lead in development. I'll leave you to investigate this one further if you want to explore the attacking possibilities. If you get this in a game - congratulations! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Grand Prix Attack: 2.f4"]
[Black "GP Attack 2.f4: 3.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ This has been discredited as a way of entering the Grand Prix Attack. Instead, those in the know play  2.Nc3  so as to prevent Black from playing ...d5. }
2... d5
{ This pawn thrust highlights the problem with playing the immediate 2. f4. The pawn duo on e4 and f4 are broken up and that prevents White from building a kingside attack. White has three responses, all of them are satisfactory for Black. }
3. e5
{ This changes the nature of the position - the pawn structure now has more in common with the French Defence. But there are a couple of big differences: White does not have a pawn on d4; and Black's bishop on c8 isn't blocked by a pawn on e6. These factors only benefit Black who has greater control in the centre, and the 'bad' bishop can escape before the pawn chain shuts tight with pawn e7-e6. }
3... Nc6
{ First of all, bring out the knight and don't commit the queen's bishop. } 4.
Nf3 { The knight develops to its best square. } 4... Bg4
{ Once the knight has committed, the bishop knows where to go. It doesn't matter too much that the bishop may be exchanged off: the knight on f3 is a strong piece that influences the important d4 and e5-squares. }
5. Be2 e6
{ The French pawn chain locks into place. This is a very secure position for Black. }
6. O-O
{ Move order for White is flexible. Instead of this,  6.d3  ,  6.c3  @@StartBracket@@most commonly@@EndBracket@@ could be played instead. On the other hand, what Black plays doesn't vary too much - the first task is to establish a knight on f5. }
6... Nh6
{ Once the knight lands on f5, White's chances for active play are severely limited and Black has good chances to seize the initiative. }
7. c3 Nf5
{ That's a big beast. White is unable to play the pawn to d4 - Black has too much pressure. }
8. d3 h5
{ The pawn supports the bishop and in a sense secures the position of the knight as it discourages a later g4. White has many moves here:  9.Na3  ,  9.Kh1  ,  9.Qe1  ,  9.h3  .  Fundamentally, I don't believe that any of these moves changes the assessment of the position. To my mind, Black already has the better chances and that is confirmed by the computers.Rather than get lost in the detail of these moves, I would like to show one line that demonstrates the dynamic possibilities available to Black. }
9. Na3
{ A plausible move. The knight cannot move to d2 because of the knight fork, but instead looks to sit on c2. However, it's a mistake. }
9... c4 { Opening up the diagonals. Very tricky! } 10. Nc2
{ Black has a couple of good options. Both keep the open a7-g1 diagonal. }
10... d4
{ Causing a huge amount of confusion.  10...cxd3  is also good for Black. } 11.
dxc4 dxc3 { Opening the a7-g1 diagonal. White is close to getting checkmated! }
12. Qxd8+ Rxd8 13. bxc3 Bc5+ 14. Kh1 h4
{ Black threatens ...Ng3+ and the game is over! } *

