[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Grand Prix Attack: 2.f4"]
[Black "GP Attack 2.f4: 3.exd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ This has been discredited as a way of entering the Grand Prix Attack. Instead, those in the know play  2.Nc3  so as to prevent Black from playing ...d5. }
2... d5
{ This pawn thrust highlights the problem with playing the immediate 2. f4. The pawn duo on e4 and f4 are broken up and that prevents White from building a kingside attack. White has three responses, all of them are satisfactory for Black. }
3. exd5 Nf6
{ 3...Qxd5  is also okay, but at least White gains a bit of time by attacking the queen. Playing out the knight is the speediest way to develop - and that is the most important thing in the opening. White can attempt to hang on to the pawn, but Black gets excellent compensation. }
4. c4
{ Compared with  4.Bb5+  ,  this straightforward defence of the d-pawn is played less frequently than the bishop check and it does not have a particularly good reputation. }
4... e6
{ Black exchanges off the d-pawn to expose White's poor pawn formation. } 5.
dxe6 Bxe6
{ Black is playing a pure gambit - do not expect to recover your pawn any time soon. In return for the small investment, Black gets easy development and White has an ugly pawn structure. Look how the bishops are blocked by the pawns on c4 and f4. }
6. Nf3 Nc6 { Knights in the middle - that is sound development. } 7. d3
{ At this point, Black has a number of promising options.  7...Qc7  and long castles is fun, but I prefer the kingside fianchetto. }
7... g6 8. Nc3 Bg7
{ On the long diagonal, the bishop casts a long and ominous shadow over White's position. It highlights the lack of scope for White's bishops. }
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O { Both sides castle safely. Sound. } 10... Re8
{ The rook moves to the open file and looks down at the weak squares on the e-file. There is no need for Black to rush matters, simply positioning the pieces well is good enough, because White is unable to play in the same way. The backward pawn on d3, as well as being potentially weak, gets in the way of White's pieces. Notice how the advanced pawns on c4 and f4 weaken the d4, d3 and e3-squares. }
11. Kh1 Qe7 12. Bd2 Rad8
{ With simple developing moves, Black has achieved a promising position. Given another moment, Black will play ...Bf5 to target the d3-pawn. }
*

