{ This is the most interesting way of parrying the check.  4...Bd7  is perfectly acceptable, but can lead to positions that are a bit too stable. }
5. Nc3
{ This is a mild way of protecting the d-pawn and there is no particular rush for Black to recover it. }
5... g6
{ The bishop is going to the long diagonal. The plan is to develop, castle, then take back the d-pawn with ...Nb6. }
6. Nf3 Bg7 { The best diagonal for the bishop. } 7. O-O O-O
{ Black is ready to play...Nb6. } 8. d4
{ This is risky as White's king is vulnerable on the a7-g1 diagonal. } 8...
cxd4 { This opens the diagonals. } 9. Qxd4 Ng4
{ The knight moves to a dangerous square and the queen on d4 is attacked. White must already be careful not to lose material. }
10. Qd3 Nc5
{ Instead of this, watch out for  10...Qb6+  11.Kh1  Nf2+??  12.Rxf2  Qxf2  13.Be3  trapping the queen. }
11. Qe2 a6 { Pushing the bishop back to a poor square. } 12. Bd3 b5
{ Preparing either to attack the knight or move the bishop to the long diagonal. }
13. h3 Nf6
{ Black will soon collect the d-pawn with an excellent position. The bishops slash across the board and White has no chance of a kingside attack. }
*

