[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Grand Prix Attack: 2.f4"]
[Black "GP Attack 2.f4: 3.exd5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ This has been discredited as a way of entering the Grand Prix Attack. Instead, those in the know play  2.Nc3  so as to prevent Black from playing ...d5. }
2... d5
{ This pawn thrust highlights the problem with playing the immediate 2. f4. The pawn duo on e4 and f4 are broken up and that prevents White from building a kingside attack. White has three responses, all of them are satisfactory for Black. }
3. exd5 Nf6
{ 3...Qxd5  is also okay, but at least White gains a bit of time by attacking the queen. Playing out the knight is the speediest way to develop - and that is the most important thing in the opening. White can attempt to hang on to the pawn, but Black gets excellent compensation. }
4. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ This is the most interesting way of parrying the check.  4...Bd7  is perfectly acceptable, but can lead to positions that are a bit too stable. }
5. c4
{ White protects the pawn, but this move has consequences: it does nothing to aid development and creates potential weaknesses in White's position. }
5... a6 6. Ba4 { This a risky move. } 6... b5
{ This strike undermines the d-pawn's support and helps Black's development. }
7. cxb5
{ Black is prepared to give away a stack of pawns to gain a lead in development and expose White's ragged pawn structure. Here, there are three decent moves:  7...Nxd5  has been the most popular continuation, but  7...Nb6  and  7...g6  are also good. Which one you go for is a matter of taste, but I am going to focus on  7...Nb6  , for the simple reason that I would like to grab that light-squared bishop. }
7... Nb6 8. bxa6+ Nxa4 9. Qxa4+ Bd7 10. Qc4
{ According to my database, seven previous games have arrived at this position and the results have all been decisive! For the record, Black has won more often than White, and the cold-eyed computer believes that Black has a slight advantage. }
10... e6
{ Black needs to open up the position for the bishops to realise their potential. In this position, the majority have played  11.Nc3  , but that gives Black the advantage. }
11. Nc3 exd5
{ Exchanging everything in the middle clears the way for the bishops and major pieces. }
12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Rxa6 { The rook swings across to upset White's king. }
14. Nf3 Re6+ 15. Kf2
{ White's king has to step very carefully - watch out for the discovered check on b5. }
15... Re2+ { A great shot. White is rocking. } 16. Kf1 Bb5 17. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ We are following the game Varkentin-Krassilnikov, Orsk 2001 where Black's sustained initiative resulted in a win. }
