[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 1.e4 c5 2.Be2"]
[Black "2. Be2 line #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Be2
{ In this chapter I am examining a strange kind of Grand Prix Attack where White plays the bishop to e2. Compared to the standard GPA where the bishop is placed on either c4 or b5, this appears somewhat passive. But as we have seen, if Black is alert in those lines, in fact that bishop ends up getting pushed around or frequently redundant as Black's knight leaps into d4. So that is the rationale behind Be2: the bishop avoids trouble, and can also help secure the c2-d3-e4 pawn chain while getting on with the kingside attack  @@StartBracket@@Qe1-h4 and the traditional pawn break f4-f5@@EndBracket@@.Naturally there is a down side to it. Over the first few moves, there is next to no pressure on Black's position, so it is possible to stake a strong claim in the centre making it difficult for White to pursue the kingside attack.   I should mention that move order in this system is flexible, so one sometimes sees, for example,  2.d3  Nc6  3.f4  g6  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  which transposes to the main line of this chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 g6
{ I am recommending the fianchetto, the traditional set up that can be employed against many Closed Sicilian systems, but if you prefer something else @@StartBracket@@for example  3...d5  is not bad here@@EndBracket@@ then go for it. Against such unassuming development from White it is hardly surprising that there are several decent options for Black. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. d3 Nf6
{ Notice how Black maintains flexibility by keeping the d and e-pawns on the their starting squares. Besides, if one has the option, it is best to develop a piece rather than move a pawn. This is a provocative move. Black would very much like to see White play  6.e5  . }
6. e5
{ This is a dubious move. White is not set up for this kind of aggression because there isn't the piece development to back it up. }
6... Nd5
{ With the pawn on c5, Black has good control over the centre and is ready to break down White's pawn chain with ...d6. Having advanced the e-pawn it is difficult for White to achieve a kingside attack by pushing forward with f5. }
7. c4
{ This only makes matters worse. Although the knight retreats, remember that White is not improving the position with such pawn moves: they have nothing to do with real development. }
7... Nc7 { The knight spins back, but is ready to take up a strong post. } 8.
Nc3 Ne6 { The knights take control over the d4-square. } 9. O-O d6
{ The crucial pawn break, freeing the bishop on g7. } 10. exd6 Qxd6
{ With such control over the d4-square, Black has a clear positional advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 1.e4 c5 2.Be2"]
[Black "2. Be2 line #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Be2
{ In this chapter I am examining a strange kind of Grand Prix Attack where White plays the bishop to e2. Compared to the standard GPA where the bishop is placed on either c4 or b5, this appears somewhat passive. But as we have seen, if Black is alert in those lines, in fact that bishop ends up getting pushed around or frequently redundant as Black's knight leaps into d4. So that is the rationale behind Be2: the bishop avoids trouble, and can also help secure the c2-d3-e4 pawn chain while getting on with the kingside attack  @@StartBracket@@Qe1-h4 and the traditional pawn break f4-f5@@EndBracket@@.Naturally there is a down side to it. Over the first few moves, there is next to no pressure on Black's position, so it is possible to stake a strong claim in the centre making it difficult for White to pursue the kingside attack.   I should mention that move order in this system is flexible, so one sometimes sees, for example,  2.d3  Nc6  3.f4  g6  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  which transposes to the main line of this chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 g6
{ I am recommending the fianchetto, the traditional set up that can be employed against many Closed Sicilian systems, but if you prefer something else @@StartBracket@@for example  3...d5  is not bad here@@EndBracket@@ then go for it. Against such unassuming development from White it is hardly surprising that there are several decent options for Black. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. d3 Nf6
{ Notice how Black maintains flexibility by keeping the d and e-pawns on the their starting squares. Besides, if one has the option, it is best to develop a piece rather than move a pawn. This is a provocative move. Black would very much like to see White play  6.e5  . }
6. O-O O-O
{ Swift castling is absolutely correct. White's kingside attack should hold no fear - with the queenside pieces all on their starting squares, there is insufficient firepower; and there is insufficient control in the centre.   At this juncture White can try various moves, none particularly good.  7.Qe1  and  7.c3  are the most popular, but we should also consider  7.Nc3  and  7.e5  . }
7. c3
{ Carlsen once played like this @@StartBracket@@although it was only an online rapid game@@EndBracket@@. He managed to win, but he didn't achieve a good position. The pawn takes away the d4-square from the knight, but gives Black a clear plan: advance the b-pawn to put pressure on c3. }
7... b5
{ Black is not threatened and can immediately initiate the standard plan of opening the b-file and softening up the long diagonal for the bishop on g7. We are seeing the disadvantage of White's pawn push.   As before,  8.e5  Nd5  only helps Black: it will be easy to break open the centre with ...d6. }
8. a3
{ Holding up the b-pawn for the moment as  8...b4?!  9.axb4  cxb4  10.e5  Nd5  11.d4  gives White a potent central pawn majority. }
8... d6 { The time has come to commit a pawn in the centre. } 9. Kh1
{ At some point the king needs to be tucked away into the corner. } 9... a5
{ Black is still aiming to push through with ...b5-b4. } 10. Be3
{ We can see another reason why the king was tucked into the corner: it prepares a retreat for the bishop in case it is attacked by ...Ng4. }
10... Bb7
{ Apart from developing the bishop to an excellent square on the long diagonal, Black sets up the push ...b5-b4 - if it is appropriate.   The bishop move is cannier than  10...b4  11.axb4  cxb4  12.Nbd2  when once again, the majority of pawns in the centre, and semi-open a-file, give White more options. }
11. Nbd2 e6
{ Black is well set up to deal with any advance that White might make in the centre of the board. If the position opens, the bishops are beautifully placed on the long diagonals. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 1.e4 c5 2.Be2"]
[Black "2. Be2 line #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Be2
{ In this chapter I am examining a strange kind of Grand Prix Attack where White plays the bishop to e2. Compared to the standard GPA where the bishop is placed on either c4 or b5, this appears somewhat passive. But as we have seen, if Black is alert in those lines, in fact that bishop ends up getting pushed around or frequently redundant as Black's knight leaps into d4. So that is the rationale behind Be2: the bishop avoids trouble, and can also help secure the c2-d3-e4 pawn chain while getting on with the kingside attack  @@StartBracket@@Qe1-h4 and the traditional pawn break f4-f5@@EndBracket@@.Naturally there is a down side to it. Over the first few moves, there is next to no pressure on Black's position, so it is possible to stake a strong claim in the centre making it difficult for White to pursue the kingside attack.   I should mention that move order in this system is flexible, so one sometimes sees, for example,  2.d3  Nc6  3.f4  g6  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  which transposes to the main line of this chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 g6
{ I am recommending the fianchetto, the traditional set up that can be employed against many Closed Sicilian systems, but if you prefer something else @@StartBracket@@for example  3...d5  is not bad here@@EndBracket@@ then go for it. Against such unassuming development from White it is hardly surprising that there are several decent options for Black. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. d3 Nf6
{ Notice how Black maintains flexibility by keeping the d and e-pawns on the their starting squares. Besides, if one has the option, it is best to develop a piece rather than move a pawn. This is a provocative move. Black would very much like to see White play  6.e5  . }
6. O-O O-O
{ Swift castling is absolutely correct. White's kingside attack should hold no fear - with the queenside pieces all on their starting squares, there is insufficient firepower; and there is insufficient control in the centre.   At this juncture White can try various moves, none particularly good.  7.Qe1  and  7.c3  are the most popular, but we should also consider  7.Nc3  and  7.e5  . }
7. e5
{ This is exactly the advance that Black would like to see: the knight can easily hop out of trouble, and then the pawn on e5 will be broken down. }
7... Nd5
{ Given half a chance, Black will play ...d6 to exchange off the e5 pawn, and then the bishop flies down the diagonal. }
8. Nc3
{ White may as well bring a piece into the game. Instead  8.c4  Nc7  only weakens the d4-square. }
8... Nc7
{ Black is getting ready for ...d6.   8...Nxc3  is also pleasant for Black. For instance,  9.bxc3  d6  10.d4  dxe5  11.fxe5  Be6  . }
9. Ne4 d6 10. c3 f5
{ Driving away the knight leaves White with a passive position and is the best way to go for Black. }
11. exf6 exf6 12. Bd2 f5 13. Nf2 h6
{ Preventing the knight coming to g5 and so preparing ...Be6. Although the pawn structures are nearly symmetrical, Black has the better chances because White's pieces are poorly placed. The passive bishops on d2 and e2 just get in the way of White's major pieces. Both Black's bishops will soon be far better placed. }
*

