{ Notice how Black maintains flexibility by keeping the d and e-pawns on the their starting squares. Besides, if one has the option, it is best to develop a piece rather than move a pawn. This is a provocative move. Black would very much like to see White play  6.e5  . }
6. O-O O-O
{ Swift castling is absolutely correct. White's kingside attack should hold no fear - with the queenside pieces all on their starting squares, there is insufficient firepower; and there is insufficient control in the centre.   At this juncture White can try various moves, none particularly good.  7.Qe1  and  7.c3  are the most popular, but we should also consider  7.Nc3  and  7.e5  . }
7. Nc3
{ With the knight on c3, the position returns to more standard positions, akin to the Closed Sicilian and the Grand Prix Attack, except with the bishop standing on e2. It's not a version that should have us terrified. }
7... d5
{ Because the bishop on e2 is somewhat passively placed, Black has the opportunity to strike out in the middle of the board. }
8. e5 Ng4
{ The knight is happy to go on an excursion, it will be safe on h6 @@StartBracket@@this is a recurring theme in so many of my recommendations! Take a look at the Rossolimo and the Grand Prix Attack@@EndBracket@@ and the e5-pawn will be broken down by ...f6. }
9. h3 Nh6
{ Knights on the rim often have their purpose. If White plays a move like  10.Qe1  , Black responds with  10...f6  and the knight will enter the game via f5 or f7. }
10. d4 cxd4
{ Before playing ... f6,Black has to resolve the situation in the middle of the board. }
11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 e6
{ The d-pawn had to be defended, and in any case, Black now has a strong pawn chain, very much the same as the French Defence. }
13. Bd3 f6
{ The pressure on the e5-pawn makes it easier to play Black than White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 1.e4 c5 2.Be2"]
[Black "2. Be2 line #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Be2
{ In this chapter I am examining a strange kind of Grand Prix Attack where White plays the bishop to e2. Compared to the standard GPA where the bishop is placed on either c4 or b5, this appears somewhat passive. But as we have seen, if Black is alert in those lines, in fact that bishop ends up getting pushed around or frequently redundant as Black's knight leaps into d4. So that is the rationale behind Be2: the bishop avoids trouble, and can also help secure the c2-d3-e4 pawn chain while getting on with the kingside attack  @@StartBracket@@Qe1-h4 and the traditional pawn break f4-f5@@EndBracket@@.Naturally there is a down side to it. Over the first few moves, there is next to no pressure on Black's position, so it is possible to stake a strong claim in the centre making it difficult for White to pursue the kingside attack.   I should mention that move order in this system is flexible, so one sometimes sees, for example,  2.d3  Nc6  3.f4  g6  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  which transposes to the main line of this chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 g6
{ I am recommending the fianchetto, the traditional set up that can be employed against many Closed Sicilian systems, but if you prefer something else @@StartBracket@@for example  3...d5  is not bad here@@EndBracket@@ then go for it. Against such unassuming development from White it is hardly surprising that there are several decent options for Black. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. d3 Nf6
{ Notice how Black maintains flexibility by keeping the d and e-pawns on the their starting squares. Besides, if one has the option, it is best to develop a piece rather than move a pawn. This is a provocative move. Black would very much like to see White play  6.e5  . }
6. O-O O-O
{ Swift castling is absolutely correct. White's kingside attack should hold no fear - with the queenside pieces all on their starting squares, there is insufficient firepower; and there is insufficient control in the centre.   At this juncture White can try various moves, none particularly good.  7.Qe1  and  7.c3  are the most popular, but we should also consider  7.Nc3  and  7.e5  . }
7. Qe1 { This is the most direct, sending the queen towards the kingside. }
7... d5
{ Countering in the centre is an appropriate response to White's kingside overture. }
8. Nc3 { Holding the pawn steady on e4. } 8... b6
{ A steady move, supporting the c-pawn and allowing the bishop to move out to b7 or a6. }
9. Qh4 Nd4
{ Once again, we see the drawback of playing the knight to c3: Black is able to plant the knight on d4. }
10. Nxd4 cxd4
{ Even when the knight is exchanged, Black gains time as the knight is attacked. }
11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 f5
{ This is a fascinating moment, and I believe highly instructive. Black would like to recapture the pawn on d5, but  12...Qxd5  allows  13.Bf3  . So what about @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p3ppbp/1p4p1/3P4/3p1P1Q/3P4/PPP1B1PP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bb7?  Then White starts a tasty attack on the kingside:  13.f5  Bxd5  14.Bh6  .  It doesn't take too much imagination to see a rook swing to the h-file, and that could be curtains.   That's why  12...f5  is such a strong move: by blocking the pawn on f4, White's attacking potential is completely nullified: the bishop on c1 cannot get into the game and the queen cannot achieve too much on its own. }
13. Bf3 Bf6 { The queen is pushed back in disgrace. } 14. Qf2 Bb7
{ If Black can capture on d5 and pile up pressure on the c-file, then life will be sweet. White has to stir up trouble. }
15. d6 { This wins a pawn as the bishop on f3 has to be exchanged off. } 15...
Bxf3 16. dxe7
{ A Zwischenzug, attacking the queen, so Black has to recapture. } 16... Qxe7
17. Qxf3 Rac8
{ White is a pawn up but Black has excellent compensation as there is pressure on the c-file, and it is possible to occupy the e-file too. }
*

