[Black "2. Be2 line #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Be2
{ In this chapter I am examining a strange kind of Grand Prix Attack where White plays the bishop to e2. Compared to the standard GPA where the bishop is placed on either c4 or b5, this appears somewhat passive. But as we have seen, if Black is alert in those lines, in fact that bishop ends up getting pushed around or frequently redundant as Black's knight leaps into d4. So that is the rationale behind Be2: the bishop avoids trouble, and can also help secure the c2-d3-e4 pawn chain while getting on with the kingside attack  @@StartBracket@@Qe1-h4 and the traditional pawn break f4-f5@@EndBracket@@.Naturally there is a down side to it. Over the first few moves, there is next to no pressure on Black's position, so it is possible to stake a strong claim in the centre making it difficult for White to pursue the kingside attack.   I should mention that move order in this system is flexible, so one sometimes sees, for example,  2.d3  Nc6  3.f4  g6  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  which transposes to the main line of this chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 g6
{ I am recommending the fianchetto, the traditional set up that can be employed against many Closed Sicilian systems, but if you prefer something else @@StartBracket@@for example  3...d5  is not bad here@@EndBracket@@ then go for it. Against such unassuming development from White it is hardly surprising that there are several decent options for Black. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. d3 Nf6
{ Notice how Black maintains flexibility by keeping the d and e-pawns on the their starting squares. Besides, if one has the option, it is best to develop a piece rather than move a pawn. This is a provocative move. Black would very much like to see White play  6.e5  . }
6. O-O O-O
{ Swift castling is absolutely correct. White's kingside attack should hold no fear - with the queenside pieces all on their starting squares, there is insufficient firepower; and there is insufficient control in the centre.   At this juncture White can try various moves, none particularly good.  7.Qe1  and  7.c3  are the most popular, but we should also consider  7.Nc3  and  7.e5  . }
7. Qe1 { This is the most direct, sending the queen towards the kingside. }
7... d5
{ Countering in the centre is an appropriate response to White's kingside overture. }
8. e5 Ng4
{ The knight provocatively hops over the fourth rank - a testing move for White. In fact  8...Ne8  has been more popular @@StartBracket@@and it is also reasonable@@EndBracket@@ but I would prefer not to clutter up the back rank. }
9. h3
{ The knight should be pushed back before it ends up going further forward. }
9... Nh6 10. c3 f6
{ Attacking the spearhead and looking to bring the knight on h6 back into play. }
11. d4
{ If White exchanges off the e5 pawn it is clear that the strategy has failed.   11.Bd1  Snigurov-Bakhmatsky, Lichess.org INT 2021 is examined in the Model Games section. }
11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Nf5 { The knight returns, attacking the d4-pawn. } 13. Qf2
Qb6 { More pressure. } 14. Rd1 g5
{ Undermining the pawn on e5. The battle is raging for the centre and White is under severe pressure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) The Grand Prix/Rossolimo Hybrid: 4.Bc4"]
[Black "GP/Rossolimo with 4.Bc4, 5.e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6
{ It looks like White is heading for a Grand Prix Attack with  3.f4  or perhaps a Closed Sicilian with  3.g3  . But no, something else appears on the board. }
3. Bb5
{ This a curious hybrid of the Rossolimo @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ and the Grand Prix Attack. If White's plan works out, there is still a chance to advance the f-pawn. Black has to take immediate measures. }
3... Nd4
{ The knight avoids the chop. Just as in the Grand Prix Attack proper, when White plays the bishop to b5, this exchange should be avoided and the knight jump highlights one of the drawbacks of playing the knight to c3. The knight stands well on d4, and leaves the bishop on b5 looking stranded.   There are two main moves here:  4.Bc4  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bc4 Nf6
{ A provocative move @@StartBracket@@and a good move!@@EndBracket@@ } 5. e5
{ This is premature. } 5... d5
{ A great strike. White now has a problematic choice.  6.exf6  dxc4  gives Black the two bishops and excellent development, while  6.Bb3  Nd7  7.f4  e6  is a superb French Defence; and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/8/2ppP3/3n4/1BN5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bxd5  Nxe5  is also pleasant for Black - the knight on d4 is beautiful. }
6. exd6 a6
{ I must admit, this is a computer choice, but I'm jumping on the silicon bandwagon as it is such a clever idea! Black wants to push away the bishop with ...b5 and station the c8 bishop on the long diagonal.   Of course, there is nothing wrong with the more pedestrian  6...exd6  . }
7. dxe7 Bxe7 8. Nf3 b5 9. Be2 Bb7
{ With fantastic compensation. Compare Black's development with White's. In the line that follows, I have given some plausible moves by White - not always best! - but it's still a reasonable way to play, and I want to illustrate Black's chances. }
10. O-O Qc7
{ Taking control of another important diagonal - this is a key move. Black introduces the attacking idea of ...Ng4. White is under pressure already! }
11. h3 { Preventing ...Ng4. } 11... h5 { Black insists! } 12. Re1 Ng4
{ A brazen attack! Black throws some wood on the fire in order to open lines. White's pieces on the queenside will take an age to get into the game and in the meantime Black plays for checkmate. This line is a lesson in attacking chess. }
13. hxg4 hxg4 { With the h-file open, Black is on the edge. } 14. Ne5 f5
{ Black needs to play this. Instead,  14...Qxe5?  15.Bxb5+  wins for White. }
15. Bxg4 O-O-O { Castling queenside brings the queen's rook into the game. }
16. d3 Rh4 { Black is ready to double on the h-file. } 17. Bh3 Bf6
{ Black has a crushing attack. This line is not completely forced! However, it illustrates Black's possibilities very well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
