[Round "?"]
[White "10) The Grand Prix/Rossolimo Hybrid: 4.Bc4"]
[Black "GP/Rossolimo with 4.Bc4, 5.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6
{ It looks like White is heading for a Grand Prix Attack with  3.f4  or perhaps a Closed Sicilian with  3.g3  . But no, something else appears on the board. }
3. Bb5
{ This a curious hybrid of the Rossolimo @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ and the Grand Prix Attack. If White's plan works out, there is still a chance to advance the f-pawn. Black has to take immediate measures. }
3... Nd4
{ The knight avoids the chop. Just as in the Grand Prix Attack proper, when White plays the bishop to b5, this exchange should be avoided and the knight jump highlights one of the drawbacks of playing the knight to c3. The knight stands well on d4, and leaves the bishop on b5 looking stranded.   There are two main moves here:  4.Bc4  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bc4 Nf6
{ A provocative move @@StartBracket@@and a good move!@@EndBracket@@ } 5. Nf3 e6
{ Blocking out the bishop on c4. } 6. O-O
{ ATTENTION! This sets a devilish trap. } 6... a6
{ This a useful move, preparing to expand with ...b5. It might appear that instead of this,  6...d5  is a straightforward move - but in fact it is a terrible mistake.  7.exd5  exd5  8.Nxd5!  Ultimately, this wins a pawn:  8...Nxd5  9.Nxd4  cxd4  10.Qh5  Be6  11.Re1  .  White has two threats: to take on d5, and also to take on e6 and Black cannot escape. }
7. a4
{ Preventing ...b5, but in this case it is possible to hit out with ...d5.   By the way, as usual,  7.e5  would be met by  7...d5! }
7... d5 8. exd5 exd5 9. Nxd5
{ Why can't White play this? The inclusion of ...a6 and a4 scuppers White's plans. }
9... Nxd5 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Qh5 Be6 12. Re1
{ In this case, Black has a defence. } 12... Nf4
{ Black wins material. In the line above, @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/4b3/3n3Q/2Bp4/8/PPPP1PPP/R1B1R1K1 b kq - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nf4  12.Bb5+  Ke7  and now  13.Qg5+  picks up the knight on f4. Here, that is plainly impossible as the pawn on a6 covers the b5 square. A small move makes a massive difference! }
*

