[Black "GP/Rossolimo with 4.Bc4, 5.Nge2 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6
{ It looks like White is heading for a Grand Prix Attack with  3.f4  or perhaps a Closed Sicilian with  3.g3  . But no, something else appears on the board. }
3. Bb5
{ This a curious hybrid of the Rossolimo @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ and the Grand Prix Attack. If White's plan works out, there is still a chance to advance the f-pawn. Black has to take immediate measures. }
3... Nd4
{ The knight avoids the chop. Just as in the Grand Prix Attack proper, when White plays the bishop to b5, this exchange should be avoided and the knight jump highlights one of the drawbacks of playing the knight to c3. The knight stands well on d4, and leaves the bishop on b5 looking stranded.   There are two main moves here:  4.Bc4  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bc4 Nf6
{ A provocative move @@StartBracket@@and a good move!@@EndBracket@@ } 5. Nge2
a6
{ A provocative move!  5...e6  is more common and will often transpose to the lines we are about to consider. }
6. d3 { With this, White makes sure the bishop doesn't get trapped. } 6... b5
7. Bb3 Nxb3 { Take that bishop! } 8. axb3 Bb7
{ The two bishops are a valuable asset in this kind of position: White finds it difficult to advance pawns in the middle without unleashing the laser on b7. }
9. O-O
{ 9.Bg5  was played in the model game Thomas Rendle - Daniel Gormally, Hastings 2011. }
9... e6
{ Black remains flexible in the middle of the board. This is quite a popular position which computers already believe is favourable for Black. }
10. f4
{ That's the move that all Grand Prix Attack players cannot resist - yet it is extremely double-edged: the bishop on b7 is more likely to come into play and potentially the diagonals towards White's king could be used by Black. }
10... Qc7
{ Perhaps contemplating queenside castling, but simply on a good square, looking all over the board. }
11. f5 Bd6 12. Bf4
{ In this line, at least White manages to develop the queenside. } 12... Bxf4
13. Nxf4 b4 { Pushing the knight to an awkward square. } 14. Na4 exf5
{ A principled move, striving to open the long diagonal for the unopposed bishop on b7. }
15. exf5 O-O
{ Black has the better chances: compare the raking bishop on b7 with the sidelined knight on a4. }
