1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6
{ It looks like White is heading for a Grand Prix Attack with  3.f4  or perhaps a Closed Sicilian with  3.g3  . But no, something else appears on the board. }
3. Bb5
{ This a curious hybrid of the Rossolimo @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@ and the Grand Prix Attack. If White's plan works out, there is still a chance to advance the f-pawn. Black has to take immediate measures. }
3... Nd4
{ The knight avoids the chop. Just as in the Grand Prix Attack proper, when White plays the bishop to b5, this exchange should be avoided and the knight jump highlights one of the drawbacks of playing the knight to c3. The knight stands well on d4, and leaves the bishop on b5 looking stranded.   There are two main moves here:  4.Bc4  and  4.Nf3  . }
4. Bc4 Nf6
{ A provocative move @@StartBracket@@and a good move!@@EndBracket@@ } 5. Nge2
a6
{ A provocative move!  5...e6  is more common and will often transpose to the lines we are about to consider. }
6. a4 { Preventing Black from expanding with ...b5. } 6... e6
{ Blocking out the bishop. } 7. O-O
{ An important crossroads. Black can break out and equalise easily, or keep more tension. }
7... d5
{ This is the simplest way to equalise, however, if Black wishes to keep more tension, then it is possible to play  7...d6  8.d3  Nc6  9.d4  @@StartBracket@@at this juncture White doesn't have much better@@EndBracket@@  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  , transposing into an open Sicilian, specifically the Sozin variation. If that suits you - go for it! }
8. exd5 exd5 { That's a decent pawn centre. } 9. Ba2
{ Quite a common position. Objectively, it's about equal. The trick with  9.Nxd5  does not work - we have already encountered this variation by transposition:  9...Nxd5  10.Nxd4  cxd4  11.Re1+  Be6  12.Qh5  Nf4  .  In this case the  inclusion of the moves 5...a6 and 6. a4 is of great significance: there is no  check on b5 and therefore Black keeps the extra material. }
9... Bd6
{ The bishop points in the right direction. This attempts to keep a bit of life in the position and is more fun than  9...Nxe2+  10.Qxe2+  Be7  11.d3  Be6  12.Bg5  O-O  13.Qf3  Rb8  @@StartBracket@@Gajewski-Zawadzki, Aviles 2003@@EndBracket@@ which soon burned out to a draw. }
10. Nxd4 { runs into typical Hellenic trouble: } 10... cxd4 11. Ne2 Bxh2+
{ Boom - a very familiar kind of boom. } 12. Kxh2 Ng4+ 13. Kg3 h5
{ With a winning attack as White's queenside pieces cannot move across to defend. }
