[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Grand Prix/Rossolimo Hybrid: 4.Nf3"]
[Black "GP/Rossolimo with 4.Nf3, 5.Nxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 { The key move! Stranding the bishop on b5. } 4.
Nf3 { 4.Bc4  is the alternative, considered in the previous chapter. } 4... e6
{ Preparing to develop the kingside. This appeals to me as it leaves the bishop dangling ineffectively on b5.   Nevertheless, Black can also play  4...Nxb5  5.Nxb5  d6  6.d4  Nf6  7.Nc3  cxd4  8.Qxd4  e5  10.Qd3  h6  which is closely related to the Najdorf and 3.Bb5+ Nd7 lines. Which fourth move you choose is a question of taste. }
5. Nxd4 { This is an error. } 5... cxd4
{ Leaving the knight with an unfortunate choice. } 6. Nb1 Nf6
{ The knight develops but also provokes. None of White's responses is truly satisfactory. For example:  7.d3  Qa5+  winning! That bishop so often lands in trouble!   7.Qe2  Qc7  is also awkward for White. }
7. e5 { This pawn turns out to be too weak. } 7... Qa5
{ That is an excellent response, cutting through to the e5-pawn. } 8. Qe2
{ Instead,  8.exf6  Qxb5  gives Black two bishops and beautiful centre pawns. }
8... Nd5 9. Bc4 d6 10. Na3
{ Don't be afraid of White's bishop check  10.Bb5+  the Black's king is safe in the middle, protected by the pawn wall. The best answer is  10...Kd8!  keeping the White's bishop in the muddle waters within limited operational range.  11.O-O  Nf4  12.Qf3  g5!  13.a4  a6  14.Bd3  Qxe5  with clear advantage for Black, and attack against the White's king will follow. }
10... Bd7 11. O-O Rc8 12. d3 Qc5
{ Preparing ...b5. Black has a space advantage and the knight on a3 is oddly placed. Black just needs to complete development to have an advantage. }
*

