[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Grand Prix/Rossolimo Hybrid: 4.Nf3"]
[Black "GP/Rossolimo with 4.Nf3, 5.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 { The key move! Stranding the bishop on b5. } 4.
Nf3 { 4.Bc4  is the alternative, considered in the previous chapter. } 4... e6
{ Preparing to develop the kingside. This appeals to me as it leaves the bishop dangling ineffectively on b5.   Nevertheless, Black can also play  4...Nxb5  5.Nxb5  d6  6.d4  Nf6  7.Nc3  cxd4  8.Qxd4  e5  10.Qd3  h6  which is closely related to the Najdorf and 3.Bb5+ Nd7 lines. Which fourth move you choose is a question of taste. }
5. O-O { Prudent. } 5... a6
{ This pushes the bishop back to an awkward square.  6.Bc4  would be met by  6...b5  ,  so that leaves d3 or e2. }
6. Be2 Ne7
{ The king's knight enters the game and perhaps prepares to support its mighty brother on d4. If  7.d3  Nec6  ,  it is hard to see how White can sensibly shake Black's grip in the middle, therefore I believe the immediate exchange is necessary. }
7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Nb1
{ If White loses time in this manner, it is obvious that the line does not challenge Black. }
8... Nc6
{ The knight supports the pawn on d4 and prepares to bring the king's bishop into play. }
9. d3 Be7 { Preparing to castle. } 10. Nd2 O-O
{ The king is safe. From this point Black can set up in various ways: perhaps with ...b5 and ...Bb7; perhaps ...d6 and ...Bd7; or ...d5. You have to react according to how White plays. }
11. f4
{ Let's consider the most aggressive. Who can resist launching the f-pawn? Very few on this side of The Channel. In fact, this can turn out to be quite weakening to White's king. }
11... b5
{ Black claims space on the queenside and prepares to develop the queen's bishop. }
12. Nf3 Bb7
{ At the moment the long diagonal is blocked by the pawn on e4, but if White is intent on attacking on the kingside, the centre could easily open and the bishop on b7 will turn into a monster. }
13. Qe1 f5
{ This advance is common in such positions: you will also see it in the Closed Sicilian and the Grand Prix Attack, for example. The pawn on f4 is blocked, restricting White's attacking options and there is pressure on the e4 pawn. The bishop on b7 might well come into play. Black controls more space and therefore has more freedom to manoeuvre. There is also potential to attack down the c-file. A good outcome from the opening. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Grand Prix/Rossolimo Hybrid: 4.Nf3"]
[Black "GP/Rossolimo with 4.Nf3, 5.O-O #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 { The key move! Stranding the bishop on b5. } 4.
Nf3 { 4.Bc4  is the alternative, considered in the previous chapter. } 4... e6
{ Preparing to develop the kingside. This appeals to me as it leaves the bishop dangling ineffectively on b5.   Nevertheless, Black can also play  4...Nxb5  5.Nxb5  d6  6.d4  Nf6  7.Nc3  cxd4  8.Qxd4  e5  10.Qd3  h6  which is closely related to the Najdorf and 3.Bb5+ Nd7 lines. Which fourth move you choose is a question of taste. }
5. O-O { Prudent. } 5... a6
{ This pushes the bishop back to an awkward square.  6.Bc4  would be met by  6...b5  ,  so that leaves d3 or e2. }
6. Bd3
{ This is the most popular move but, frankly, what a dreadful place for the bishop, blocking the d-pawn. }
6... Nc6
{ The knight withdraws, leaving the bishop in an odd position. Instead, if  6...Ne7  7.Nxd4!  cxd4  8.Ne2  Nc6  9.c3  Bc5  10.b4  White has some initiative. }
7. Re1
{ The rook move looks plausible, however, it runs into a stunning riposte. }
7... g5
{ I love this move! It looks outlandish, but in fact it is completely justified. Black threatens to advance again, winning the knight on f3. The rook move had consequences - it took away the e1-square from the knight. White has to waste a move in dealing with the threat, and after that, Black is able to take the initiative. }
8. Kh1
{ This has been the most popular move in the position, but according to the computer, it is not the best. }
8... g4 9. Ng1 h5
{ By pushing the knight away, Black has secured greater control over the e5 and d4-squares, and that can often lead to a kingside attack. }
10. b3
{ At this point, the computer throws up some fascinating options for Black.  10...Bg7  and  10...Nge7  are both very sensible, but I like the development of the queen's bishop - it's the most aggressive. }
10... b6 11. Bb2 { White threatens to play Nd5, causing a spot of confusion. }
11... Rh6 { Moving out of trouble on the long diagonal. } 12. Nce2 Bb7
{ Putting the bishop here makes it very difficult for White to undertake active play as the king is highly vulnerable in the corner. }
13. c4 Qc7
{ Seizing control of an important diagonal and preparing the option of queenside castling. }
14. Bc2 Bd6 15. h3 O-O-O
{ This position looks like something out of Fischer-Random chess. White has a big problem: how is the king going to escape its difficulties? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Grand Prix/Rossolimo Hybrid: 4.Nf3"]
[Black "GP/Rossolimo with 4.Nf3, 5.O-O #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 { The key move! Stranding the bishop on b5. } 4.
Nf3 { 4.Bc4  is the alternative, considered in the previous chapter. } 4... e6
{ Preparing to develop the kingside. This appeals to me as it leaves the bishop dangling ineffectively on b5.   Nevertheless, Black can also play  4...Nxb5  5.Nxb5  d6  6.d4  Nf6  7.Nc3  cxd4  8.Qxd4  e5  10.Qd3  h6  which is closely related to the Najdorf and 3.Bb5+ Nd7 lines. Which fourth move you choose is a question of taste. }
5. O-O { Prudent. } 5... a6
{ This pushes the bishop back to an awkward square.  6.Bc4  would be met by  6...b5  ,  so that leaves d3 or e2. }
6. Bd3
{ This is the most popular move but, frankly, what a dreadful place for the bishop, blocking the d-pawn. }
6... Nc6
{ The knight withdraws, leaving the bishop in an odd position. Instead, if  6...Ne7  7.Nxd4!  cxd4  8.Ne2  Nc6  9.c3  Bc5  10.b4  White has some initiative. }
7. b3
{ The queen's bishop needs developing.   Instead, White could play the odd  7.Be2  . How many moves does White want to play with that king's bishop? The idea is to transpose into an open Sicilian. One could allow that -  7...b5  8.d4  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Bb7  , for example is a very respectable line - or play  7...Nd4  , thwarting the pawn push. In which case  8.Bd3  repeats the position! We could be heading for an early and unusual draw! }
7... g6 8. Bb2 Bg7
{ Black maintains good control over the centre and it hard for White to gain active play. }
9. Na4
{ White challenges Black's control by exchanging the bishops. But there is a drawback. }
9... Bxb2 10. Nxb2 { The exchange has left the knight poorly placed on b2. }
10... d6 11. c3 Nf6 12. Bc2 e5
{ Having got rid of the dark-squared bishop, it makes perfect sense to set up the pawns on the dark squares. }
13. Nc4 O-O
{ Black has a sound structure and easy development. Chances are balanced. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) The Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.g3"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian: 6.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ This modest pawn move signals the start of the Closed Sicilian. When played by Vassily Smyslov or Boris Spassky, this could be a serious weapon. When played by everyone else, it was often insipid. These days, one rarely sees the opening ventured by the world's top players for three reasons: Black's responses are well worked out; the positions are too stable; Black often has more than one good way to respond, so there is very little jeopardy. }
3... g6
{ As in many Anti-Sicilian variations, the d4-square is of great importance, so the fianchetto is appropriate. }
4. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black's strong control over the d4-square makes it difficult for White to launch a meaningful kingside attack. }
5. d3
{ White could instead play  5.f4  or  5.Nge2  , but they will inevitably transpose into a later line. }
5... d6
{ This is the most flexible move: we know that the d-pawn will always move to d6, but it isn't yet clear where the e-pawn belongs: e6 or e5? First we see how White commits. }
6. Be3
{ This is the most common move at this juncture. White intends supporting the bishop with Qd2 in order to exchange on h6. }
6... e5
{ In this case, it is appropriate to play the pawn forward two squares, clamping White in the middle. This gives Black strong central control. }
7. f4 Nge7
{ Black's set up will be familiar to those that play the English with White - this is essentially a Botvinnik System, which has an excellent reputation. }
8. Nf3
{ White would like to exchange on e5 when it would be impossible to recapture with the d-pawn. Black has several ways of meeting this, but throwing the knight into the middle feels natural, forthright and menacing. }
8... Nd4 { That is a powerful piece. } 9. O-O O-O 10. Qd2
{ Black has a wide choice of decent moves here:  10...Bg4  and  10...exf4  both have good reputations. But let's go straight on to the attack. }
10... b5
{ The pawn gets ready to push the knight from its perch. White has a wide range of options. I'm selecting a couple of the more plausible to consider. }
11. Bxd4 { We need to consider what happens if White captures the pawn on b5. }
11... cxd4 12. Nxb5
{ In general, Black should be very happy about the exchange of White's bishop for knight. Black's dark-squared bishop has potential to enter the game on the long diagonal @@StartBracket@@if the centre opens@@EndBracket@@ or perhaps along the h6-c1 diagonal. Remember, the bishop has no opponent now. Black also has a space advantage and open files to use on the queenside. }
12... Rb8 { A mini-skewer. } 13. c4 dxc3
{ Opening the position for the bishop on g7. } 14. Nxc3 Qb6+
{ A useful check, demonstrating that those dark squares are there for the taking. }
15. Rf2 { Defending the b-pawn, but a self-pin is never very desirable. } 15...
exf4 { The bishop on g7 sparkles down the long diagonal. } 16. gxf4 Bg4
{ With the two bishops and open files for the rooks, Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. }
*

