[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) The Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.g3"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian: 6.Be3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ This modest pawn move signals the start of the Closed Sicilian. When played by Vassily Smyslov or Boris Spassky, this could be a serious weapon. When played by everyone else, it was often insipid. These days, one rarely sees the opening ventured by the world's top players for three reasons: Black's responses are well worked out; the positions are too stable; Black often has more than one good way to respond, so there is very little jeopardy. }
3... g6
{ As in many Anti-Sicilian variations, the d4-square is of great importance, so the fianchetto is appropriate. }
4. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black's strong control over the d4-square makes it difficult for White to launch a meaningful kingside attack. }
5. d3
{ White could instead play  5.f4  or  5.Nge2  , but they will inevitably transpose into a later line. }
5... d6
{ This is the most flexible move: we know that the d-pawn will always move to d6, but it isn't yet clear where the e-pawn belongs: e6 or e5? First we see how White commits. }
6. Be3
{ This is the most common move at this juncture. White intends supporting the bishop with Qd2 in order to exchange on h6. }
6... e5
{ In this case, it is appropriate to play the pawn forward two squares, clamping White in the middle. This gives Black strong central control. }
7. Qd2 Nge7 8. Bh6
{ White sticks to the programme, but ignoring development to pursue this plan just isn't worth it.   8.f4  will most likely transpose back into the line with 7.f4, for example:  8...O-O  9.Nf3  Nd4  10.O-O  etc. }
8... Bxh6 { This drags the queen offside. } 9. Qxh6 Nd4
{ A strong central counter-attack exposing the deficiencies of White's strategy. The knight is great in the middle! }
10. O-O-O
{ White consistently plays for the attack, but the king is desperately insecure on the queenside. }
10... b5
{ The pawn storm is absolutely appropriate as Black has such good control in the middle of the board. }
11. Qg7 { White continues consistently and swipes a pawn. } 11... Rf8
{ The most secure, guarding the f7-pawn. } 12. Qxh7
{ Let's examine the most consistent continuation, grabbing the pawn. It is better to develop a piece,  12.Nf3  , but Black gets a good attack with  12...Qa5  . }
12... Qa5
{ Black is able to move straight into the attack. The threat is ...b4 and then ...Qxa2. }
13. Kb1 Bg4
{ A finesse, poking the rook and inducing the pawn move f3 - which takes away the square from the knight on g1. }
14. f3 Be6
{ A fine square for the bishop, reinstating the threat of ...b4. Black already has a winning attack. }
