[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) The Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.g3"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian: 6.Nge2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ This modest pawn move signals the start of the Closed Sicilian. When played by Vassily Smyslov or Boris Spassky, this could be a serious weapon. When played by everyone else, it was often insipid. These days, one rarely sees the opening ventured by the world's top players for three reasons: Black's responses are well worked out; the positions are too stable; Black often has more than one good way to respond, so there is very little jeopardy. }
3... g6
{ As in many Anti-Sicilian variations, the d4-square is of great importance, so the fianchetto is appropriate. }
4. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black's strong control over the d4-square makes it difficult for White to launch a meaningful kingside attack. }
5. d3
{ White could instead play  5.f4  or  5.Nge2  , but they will inevitably transpose into a later line. }
5... d6
{ This is the most flexible move: we know that the d-pawn will always move to d6, but it isn't yet clear where the e-pawn belongs: e6 or e5? First we see how White commits. }
6. Nge2
{ In most king's pawn openings, this knight is best placed on f3 where it influences the e5-square. This applies here too. Would you be terrified facing this half-hearted development?   I know very well that this is not the most testing move - I've tried it myself. I had some ideas planned after  6...e5  7.h4!?  which weren't really much good, but they sometimes scared the opposition.   Instead, I believe that Black should keep control over the d5-square with  6...e6  .  The knight will still develop on e7, as is usually the case in the Closed Sicilian. This whole line is quite anemic for White. }
6... e6
{ Maintaining control over the d5 square. Black's choice of sixth move is important in all these variations. Against 6. f4 and 6. Nge2 - meet them with 6...e6; against 6. Be3, go the whole way with 6... e5. }
7. O-O Nge7
{ There are no threats to Black's position, so simple development is in order. }
8. Be3 Nd4
{ The knight lands on the traditional @@StartBracket@@and excellent@@EndBracket@@ d4-square disrupting the free flow of White's development. Giving up the dark-squared bishop with  9.Bxd4?  cxd4  would be highly suspect. }
9. Qd2 O-O { The king reaches safety. } 10. Nd1
{ White's most popular move, looking to drive away the knight with c3. } 10...
a5
{ Considering that White's pieces are going backwards, it is time to come forwards. }
11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Bh6 a4
{ Keep gaining space - the b2-pawn wil become a target. } 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. c4
Qa5
{ We are following the game Janaszak-Mikhaletz, Poznan 2004 in which Black got ready for the ...b7-b5 pawn break. How do you think the knight on d1 is feeling about the position? }
*

