[White "12) The Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.g3"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian: 6.f4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ This modest pawn move signals the start of the Closed Sicilian. When played by Vassily Smyslov or Boris Spassky, this could be a serious weapon. When played by everyone else, it was often insipid. These days, one rarely sees the opening ventured by the world's top players for three reasons: Black's responses are well worked out; the positions are too stable; Black often has more than one good way to respond, so there is very little jeopardy. }
3... g6
{ As in many Anti-Sicilian variations, the d4-square is of great importance, so the fianchetto is appropriate. }
4. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black's strong control over the d4-square makes it difficult for White to launch a meaningful kingside attack. }
5. d3
{ White could instead play  5.f4  or  5.Nge2  , but they will inevitably transpose into a later line. }
5... d6
{ This is the most flexible move: we know that the d-pawn will always move to d6, but it isn't yet clear where the e-pawn belongs: e6 or e5? First we see how White commits. }
6. f4
{ This is the most brazen way of playing for White. If the pawn can be forced through to f5, then there is some chance of an attack, but Black can prevent that easily. Often this pawn thrust does more harm than good, weakening the squares behind it. }
6... e6
{ The pawn makes room for the knight and the process of containing White's f-pawn begins. }
7. Nf3 Nge7
{ Notice that four of Black's pieces are directed towards the f5-square: it will be very difficult for White to advance it further. Developing the knight on e7 also ensures that the fianchettoed bishop is unimpeded and continues to control the d4-square. }
8. O-O O-O
{ Already, strong computers aren't particularly impressed by White's position - around minus 0.20 for those that take an interest in the digits. From a human viewpoint we can at least say that White will do well to equalise from the opening @@StartBracket@@with the proviso that Black plays well@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Be3
{ This is by far the most popular move at this juncture. The bishop covers the d4-square. Black has several good replies. The old move was  9...Nd4  , which is fine, although Black needs to be aware of  10.e5  , with which Spassky, and a few others, had some success. But I prefer 9...b6. }
9... b6
{ The bishop prepares to get into the game, sometimes via a6, sometimes via b7. The b6-pawn also bolsters c5, introducing another potential strategy - advancing with ...d6-d5. }
10. Qd2 d5
{ Now that the c5-pawn is protected, this is possible. It's a disruptive move as it contains a threat: ...d4 winning a piece. White has a number of ways to meet the threat, none of them is promising. }
11. Bf2 { Stepping away from the threat of ...d4. } 11... dxe4
{ Heading for a pleasant endgame. White should not play  12.Nxe4  as the b2-pawn hangs. }
12. dxe4 Qxd2 13. Nxd2 e5
{ This is an important move, preventing White from advancing to e5. Black is ready to play the knight into the outpost on d4. }
14. Rfe1 Ba6
{ Black's bishops streak across the board and the knight is preparing to leap into d4. }
