1. e4 c5 2. g3
{ This is closely related to the Closed Sicilian @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nc3  Nc6  3.g3  etc.@@EndBracket@@ but with the difference that White has not played the knight to c3. What is White trying to achieve with this?You may have noticed that in many Anti-Sicilian variations, for example, the Closed Sicilian as above, and the Grand Prix Attack, Black often gains counterplay by playing the knight to d4 - a fine outpost. With White's knight on c3 it is difficult to drive away, and if it is exchanged, let's say with a knight, then the c5-pawn recaptures, attacking the knight on c3. Black gains excellent counterplay. By delaying the development of the queen's knight, White keeps the option of playing the pawn to c3, keeping the d4-square under control.I have dabbled with this system when playing White and it has its moments, but if Black understands the issues, it's harmless. Playing the pawn to c3 is time consuming and means the knight on b1 has to find another way into the game.   One of the immediate drawbacks of omitting Nc3 is that Black can already strike out with  2...d5  .  This is often recommended, but I would prefer not to go down this path as the positions reached are non-standard and a bit tricky. As Black, I see nothing wrong with treating this as a Closed Sicilian. Sometimes White attempts to get into these systems with the move order 2. d3, but they will quickly transpose into lines I am considering here. }
2... Nc6
{ Black follows the standard development of the Closed Sicilian. The d4 and e5-squares are of great importance. }
3. Bg2 g6 4. d3 Bg7
{ As ever, the bishop exerts great influence on the long diagonal. } 5. f4
{ The standard kingside aggression. When playing with Black, I am always delighted to see the f-pawn advance. Are there any weaknesses in Black's position? No. Are there weaknesses in White's position? Yes, a great vacuum behind the pawns! }
5... d6 6. Nf3 e5
{ In this case, I believe Black is right to strike out in the middle - but I should emphasise this is a question of taste.  6...e6  and  6...Nf6  are both entirely playable.   In order to explain why I am recommending  6...e5  , let me show what White might be intending:  6...e6  7.c3  That's the  idea - the d4-square is taken under control.  7...Nge7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Be3  b6  10.Re1  Ba6  11.d4  Rc8  12.Na3  cxd4  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Bxd4  1-0 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Amin,B @@StartBracket@@2686@@EndBracket@@  -Kryakvin,D @@StartBracket@@2595@@EndBracket@@ Hoogeveen 2018. White has succeeded in engineering a kind  of open Sicilian where Black has no pressure on the c-file. White has a  pleasant position. }
7. c3
{ Sensing there could be trouble on the long diagonal, White blocks, but it's slow. Look how many pawn moves White has made - that's already breaking an important opening principle. }
7... Nge7 8. O-O h6
{ Having warned about too many pawn moves, Black is committing the same sin! But there is a good reason for this one. The intention is to play ...Be6 - without allowing Ng5.   Instead,  8...O-O ?!  9.f5!  gxf5  10.Nh4  is the typical pawn sacrifice that gives  White a potent kingside attack - one to avoid. }
9. Na3 Be6
{ All according to plan. With this pawn structure, the bishop sits nicely on e6, looking in two different directions and covering the d5-square. Mikhail Botvinnik pioneered this set up in the 1950s and it is still valid. }
10. Be3 exf4 11. Bxf4 O-O 12. Qd2 Kh7
{ Black has a solid set up and can perhaps play the knight into e5, perhaps advance with ...d5, or perhaps play ...b5-b4 - all depending on how White continues. }
*

