[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) A move order trick: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 with 6.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ A tricky move. White keeps the option of playing an open Sicilian but waits to see how Black reacts before committing.   If you play the Dragon then this move order isn't an issue:  3...g6  is a useful move and  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  leads back into a Dragon. Likewise if you play the Taimanov, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  is a useful move and  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  is back to a normal position; or the Classical @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  , and the Scheveningen could also arise without a hitch. Even if you play the Sveshnikov you are okay: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6!  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e5  , etc.   But for the Kalashnikov, there isn't a good waiting move. For example  3...d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  and Black could play  5...e5  but this is not ideal. White can play  6.Nf5  and stands better. That's why I am recommending shutting the centre with 3...e5. }
3... e5
{ Preventing d4. In fact, if you are a Kalashnikov player, then you will already feel quite comfortable with this structure @@StartBracket@@the pawn on e5 claiming space - as well as the hole on d5!@@EndBracket@@. The strongest players in the world have regularly played like this, from Kasparov and Carlsen downwards, so you are in good company! }
4. Bc4
{ This is the drawback of Black's strategy: White is able to station the bishop on a dangerous diagonal and takes control over the d5-square. But as we know from the Kalashnikov, Black can fight for control of that square. }
4... Be7
{ Notice that Black is keeping an eye on the g5-square. Instead  4...Nf6?  5.Ng5  wouldn't be too bright. }
5. d3 d6
{ Black sets up solidly. There now comes a big divide. White has two main continuations:  6.O-O  and  6.Nd2  . They are played with roughly equal frequency. }
6. Nd2
{ The knight wants to spin round via f1 to e3 in order to gain greater control over the d5-square. }
6... Nf6 { Sensible development. } 7. Nf1
{ The knight continues on its journey. } 7... Bg4
{ This is a nice disruptive move. The queen doesn't want to move to the awkward square d2, but advancing the f-pawn also isn't ideal as it slightly weakens the kingside. }
8. f3 Be6
{ This is the natural square for the bishop, challenging its counterpart on c4. and covering the d5-square. Anyone that plays the Kalashnikov, or indeed other variations of the Sicilian which feature a backward d-pawn such as the Sveshnikov or the Najdorf, will recognise that this is the correct spot. If White exchanges, the pawn on e6 will cover the important d5-square. }
9. Ne3
{ The knight has finally reached its destination, taking control over the d5-square. }
9... O-O 10. O-O Rb8 { Potentially looking to expand with ...b5. } 11. Ned5 Nh5
{ There is no need to relieve the traffic jam of pieces on d5. The knight prepares a path for the bishop to g5, and might one day hop into f4. We can see a benefit of 'forcing' the pawn to f3 - the queen on d1 is blocked. }
12. a4 Bg5
{ This is a standard manoeuvre in many Sicilian variations @@StartBracket@@the Kalashnikov, the Sveshnikov, the Najdorf@@EndBracket@@. In my Kalashnikov course, I called this idea the 'Break-out bishop': it exchanges off the bad bishop for a good bishop and later gives Black greater control over the d4 square and other dark squares. Chances are balanced. }
*

