7. cxd4 exd4
{ The best capture as it continues to hamper White's development The alternative is not as good:  7...dxe4?  8.dxe5  Qd5  9.Nc3!  Qxe5  We are following the game Reti-Perlmutter Netherlands 1919 - yes, the famous Reti! Here he could have gained a large advantage by playing  10.Bb5+  ,  displacing Black's king. }
8. Nxd4 { 8.exd5  Qxd5  would transpose back to the line 7.exd5 Qxd5. } 8...
dxe4 { The knight on d4 is attacked by Black's queen. } 9. Bb5+
{ White needs to develop rapidly. } 9... Bd7 10. O-O Nf6
{ Black also needs to hurry with development. } 11. d3 Bc5
{ Gaining time by attacking the knight. } 12. dxe4 O-O
{ Castling is necessary - the position was too open. Black is a pawn down, but White's centre is under attack. }
13. Bxd7 { White's pieces were loose, so exchanging was necessary. } 13... Qxd7
{ The knight is attacked as well as the e-pawn. } 14. Nb3
{ Attacking the bishop and so gaining a little time. } 14... Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Bb6
{ The bishop stands well, looking down at the perennially weak point on f2. }
16. Re1 Rfe8 { Black will win back the e-pawn and the game is even. } *

