1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nge2
{ For most Sicilian players, this move isn't an issue. For example, a Sveshnikov player can simply reply  3...Nf6  and the game will in all likelihood head that way:  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e5  . Likewise a Dragon player wouldn't have a problem after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPPNPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  etc. But for a Kalashnikov player, the 'threat' to head back into an open Sicilian causes a problem. If you aren't happy with one of the alternative Sicilians, then d4 must be stopped.   There are two reasonable ways of achieving this.  3...e5  is sensible, which is rather similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  e5  , as examined in the previous chapter. My only qualm is that the position could simplify too quickly. For example, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nge2  e5  4.Nd5  Nge7  5.Nec3  Nxd5  6.Nxd5  Be7  7.Bc4  ,  etc. But there is nothing wrong with this line for Black, and if you want something steady, solid and reliable, then go for it. For the more adventurous, I have an alternative recommendation. }
3... Nd4
{ Let's hope they get confused and play  4.g3  .  Hehe. According to my database, most White players exchange on d4 at this point, but a significant number also play  4.d3  , so we are looking at that one as well. }
4. Nxd4 cxd4 5. Ne2 { This is the most frequently played. } 5... e5
{ Black defends the pawn and with it takes control in the centre. I believe that  5...Nf6  is also a very sound option for Black. For example,  6.Nxd4  Nxe4  7.Nf3  g6  8.d4  Bg7  9.Bd3  d5  is roughly equal. }
6. c3 d5
{ I like this move as it immediately sows confusion. Which pawn should White take? There is also the issue of how White is going to develop with that knight getting in the way on e2. This is almost uncharted territory! My database shows that only one other game has been played with this move. }
7. cxd4 exd4
{ The best capture as it continues to hamper White's development The alternative is not as good:  7...dxe4?  8.dxe5  Qd5  9.Nc3!  Qxe5  We are following the game Reti-Perlmutter Netherlands 1919 - yes, the famous Reti! Here he could have gained a large advantage by playing  10.Bb5+  ,  displacing Black's king. }
8. e5 Qc7 { Threatening the e-pawn.  8...Bc5  is also reasonable. } 9. f4
{ An ambitious move, holding on to the advanced pawn. But it is risky considering that White's development is poor, and the king still in the middle. }
9... Qb6
{ The queen protects the d-pawn, but also moves to a dangerous diagonal. White has a lot of options here @@StartBracket@@  10.g3  ,  10.Ng3  ,  10.d3  ,  10.b3  ,  10.Qa4+  ,  10.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@ and it is not immediately obvious which is the best path to take. That's why I think this is an interesting line for Black to play: it challenges White to think at an early stage of the game. Let me explore a few of these options. }
10. d3 { This standard move creates a massive hole on e3. } 10... Bb4+ 11. Bd2
Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Nh6
{ The knight is heading into e3, and Black already has the advantage. } *

