[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) The Early Bc4"]
[Black "3.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This isn't better or worse than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Bc4  ,  it simply runs into the same problem - the bishop gets blocked. }
3... e6 { The pawn on e6 takes away the joy from White. } 4. Nc3
{ Preventing ...d5, and keeping the option of playing d4. } 4... Nf6
{ The knight develops to the best square and is ready to support the ...d5 advance. }
5. e5
{ Putting the question to the knight, but Black is solid enough to cope with the push. Instead  5.d4  d5  is similar to the main line. }
5... Ng4 { The e-pawn is vulnerable. } 6. Qe2 { Protecting the e-pawn. } 6...
Qc7 { Black is able to win the advanced e-pawn. } 7. Nb5
{ White must somehow attempt to stir up trouble in order to gain compensation. }
7... Qb8
{ The queen has to step backwards, but fundamentally the position has not changed: White cannot save the e-pawn. }
8. d4
{ This is the best attempt to complicate @@StartBracket@@although it is insufficient@@EndBracket@@. }
8... a6
{ Forcing the win of a pawn. Instead,  8...cxd4  9.Bf4  allows White to hold onto the e-pawn and the position is getting very messy. }
9. Nd6+
{ Making the best of the situation: at least White is able to exchange off the important dark-squared bishop. }
9... Bxd6 10. exd6 Qxd6 { Black has won a pawn. } 11. h3
{ White needs to push back the knight. Instead  11.O-O  Nxd4  would be embarrassing for White. }
11... Nf6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. O-O O-O
{ The king is safe and the middlegame begins. } 14. c3 b5
{ Black could also push the d-pawn, but I prefer playing around the edge, and putting the bishop on the long diagonal. }
15. Bd3 Bb7
{ With well-developed pieces and a healthy pawn structure @@StartBracket@@not forgetting the extra pawn@@EndBracket@@, Black has the advantage. }
*

