[Black "3.Bc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This isn't better or worse than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Bc4  ,  it simply runs into the same problem - the bishop gets blocked. }
3... e6 { The pawn on e6 takes away the joy from White. } 4. d4
{ It's possible to bring the game back into an open Sicilian, but it's an insipid variation for White. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Black develops rapidly and puts pressure on the centre. } 6. Nc3
{ Defending the pawn. Instead, the lunge ends in disaster:  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.e5?  Qa5+  loses a pawn. }
6... d5
{ Gaining space in the centre is the simplest way to equalise and is a logical rebuttal to the early bishop move.  6...Bb4  is also possible, but lines where Black takes the e-pawn, e.g.  7.O-O  Bxc3  8.bxc3  Nxe4  always offers White compensation in the form of that unopposed bishop on c1. But if you like grabbing pawns - then go for it! }
7. exd5 exd5 8. Bb5 { White wins back time by attacking the knight. } 8... Bd7
{ Defending the knight. } 9. O-O Be7 { Prudently covering the black king. } 10.
Bg5 O-O { Both sides have castled and the middlegame begins. } 11. Re1 h6
{ It is often useful to include this move: there might be the chance to push with ...g5, and looking a little further, the king has an escape square off the back rank. }
12. Bh4 Re8 13. Qd3
{ We are following an online game, Salinas Herrera-Rychagov, Chess.com INT 2021. Here, Black should play... }
13... a6 14. Ba4 Nb4 { It is time for Black to leap forward. } 15. Qd1 Bxa4 16.
Nxa4 g5 17. Bg3 Ne4
{ Black has typical Isolated Queen's Pawn activity - it is worth comparing this kind of position with those in the 1.e4 c5 2.c3 chapter. An understanding of IQP positions is generally helpful! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) The Early Bc4"]
[Black "2.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Bc4
{ 'Knights before bishops' runs one of our opening maxims. Why? Because we generally know where we want to place the knights - in the middle of the board where they have the greatest influence - whereas it is better to wait with the development of the bishops until a useful diagonal appears. }
2... e6
{ Blocking the bishop's diagonal. This simple move reveals why playing the bishop to c4 is premature. Given half a chance, Black might well push the bishop away with ...d5. }
3. Nc3
{ Preventing ...d5.   3.Nf3  would transpose to the variation beginning with 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4. }
3... a6 { Threatening to drive the bishop away. } 4. a4
{ Squarely preventing ...b5, but it was useful for Black to include these moves as the b5-square is taken away from the bishop. }
4... Nf6 { Preparing to gain time and space by playing ...d5. } 5. e5
{ This is a mistake. } 5... d5
{ A response that will be familiar from the chapter 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Bb5. }
6. exf6
{ Instead,  6.Ba2  Nfd7  7.f4  Nc6  is a promising French Defence for Black as the bishop on a2 is quite out of play. }
6... dxc4 7. fxg7 Bxg7 { The two bishops are about to rule the board. } 8. Qg4
{ White can take a pawn, but it only wastes time. } 8... O-O 9. Qxc4 Nc6
{ Black is ahead in development and threatens to take the initiative with ...Nd4. }
*

