[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Wing Gambits: 2.b4 and 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.b4"]
[Black "Wing Gambit with 3.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. b4
{ The Wing Gambit. In my long playing career, I don't believe I ever had to face the Wing Gambit. More's the pity. As far as I can see, Black can take the pawn with impunity. It's not even that complicated.   I will also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.b4  . }
2... cxb4
{ Thank you very much. At this point White has two main moves:  3.a3  and  3.d4  . }
3. a3
{ Attempting to bring the queenside pieces into play. This is the most popular move. }
3... d5
{ While White is footling around on the edge, Black strikes in the middle. A classical response. }
4. exd5
{ Best. Instead, if  4.e5  , White just arrives in a poor French Defence position a pawn down:  4...Nc6  5.d4  Qb6  6.Be3  Bf5  ,  Black follows with ...e6 and is in control. }
4... Qxd5
{ White has to be a little bit careful. The game Shirazi-Peters, US Championship 1984, famously continued  5.axb4  Qe5+  . Most unfortunate. }
5. Nf3
{ White finally brings out a piece. Here, the most popular move has been  5...e5  , but I like the solidity of  5...e6  , and in practice it has scored better. }
5... e6
{ Black has a regular kingside pawn structure with no weaknesses. The bishop on f8 protects the pawn on b4. }
6. Bb2
{ This is the second most popular move but actually scores better than  6.axb4  , so we should take a look. }
6... Nf6
{ Black's aim is to castle as quickly as possible. There is no need to worry about  7.Bxf6  gxf6  , as Black would relish playing with the two bishops and the king is secure behind the clump of pawns. }
7. Bd3 { Once again, I am taking the most popular move as the main line. } 7...
Nc6 { The knight on c6 covers important squares. } 8. O-O
{ Instead,  8.axb4?!  Nxb4  is worse as White is forced to move the bishop. }
8... Be7 { The king must be brought to safety on the kingside. } 9. Re1
{ This is the most sensible move, bringing the rook into play and looking to fling the knight onto the outpost. }
9... O-O 10. Ne5
{ In this line White has at least succeeded in generating some activity, so Black has to be a little careful. Nevertheless, the computers aren't impressed. }
10... b3
{ A neat little counter-sacrifice. @@StartBracket@@By the way,  10...Bd7  was also possible@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Nc3
{ The best that White can do is develop as quickly as possible and hope that something turns up. }
11... bxc2 { With this Black keeps the extra pawn. } 12. Bxc2
{ Instead,  12.Qxc2  Qc5  is a safe extra pawn. Or @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2bppp/2n1pn2/3qN3/8/P1NB4/1BpP1PPP/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nxd5  cxd1=Q  13.Nxe7+  Nxe7  14.Rexd1  Rd8  .  Black is a clear pawn up. }
12... Qd4
{ It looks perilous to keep the queen in the middle, but it actually restricts White's pieces. }
13. Nf3
{ Keeping pieces on the board - that is White's best chance.  13.Nxc6  bxc6  makes things easier for Black. }
13... Qf4
{ With the queen lurking around the kingside, it is hard for White to build up an attack. }
14. Ne4 Rd8
{ Putting a little pressure on the d-pawn and preparing ...Bd7. If  15.g3  ,  the queen happily drops back to h6. }
