[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Wing Gambits: 2.b4 and 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.b4"]
[Black "Wing Gambit with 3.a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. b4
{ The Wing Gambit. In my long playing career, I don't believe I ever had to face the Wing Gambit. More's the pity. As far as I can see, Black can take the pawn with impunity. It's not even that complicated.   I will also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.b4  . }
2... cxb4
{ Thank you very much. At this point White has two main moves:  3.a3  and  3.d4  . }
3. a3
{ Attempting to bring the queenside pieces into play. This is the most popular move. }
3... d5
{ While White is footling around on the edge, Black strikes in the middle. A classical response. }
4. exd5
{ Best. Instead, if  4.e5  , White just arrives in a poor French Defence position a pawn down:  4...Nc6  5.d4  Qb6  6.Be3  Bf5  ,  Black follows with ...e6 and is in control. }
4... Qxd5
{ White has to be a little bit careful. The game Shirazi-Peters, US Championship 1984, famously continued  5.axb4  Qe5+  . Most unfortunate. }
5. Nf3
{ White finally brings out a piece. Here, the most popular move has been  5...e5  , but I like the solidity of  5...e6  , and in practice it has scored better. }
5... e6
{ Black has a regular kingside pawn structure with no weaknesses. The bishop on f8 protects the pawn on b4. }
6. axb4
{ This has been the most popular move, so I am taking this as my main line. Frankly, whatever White plays Black has a comfortable position with an extra pawn. }
6... Bxb4 7. c3 Be7
{ The bishop returns to a square where it is out of trouble and does not get in the way of the other pieces. }
8. Na3 Nc6
{ The knight develops and at the same time covers the a7 pawn. That is useful when it comes to White's next move.   8...Nf6?!  would be a mistake:  9.Nb5  Qd8  10.Rxa7  Rxa7  11.Nxa7  and White succeeds in equalizing. }
9. Nb5 Qd8
{ The queen dips back out of trouble and covers the c7-square. The knight on c6 protects the a7-pawn. }
10. d4 Nf6
{ Black hastens to bring the king to safety. This is essentially a normal 'hanging pawns' position @@StartBracket@@i.e. pawns on c3 and d4@@EndBracket@@ but with the exception that White is missing an a-pawn - which brings no benefit as Black is safe on the a-file. In other words, Black is a pawn up for nothing. }
11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O b6
{ Having brought the king to safety, the queen's bishop can be developed. } 13.
Ne5 Bb7
{ With development completed, we can conclude the line. Black is a pawn up with a promising position. The immediate threat is to exchange on e5 and play ...Qd5; ...a6 followed by ...b5 also looks good. This position is further covered in the model game Simensen-Stigar, Namses 1995. }
