[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Wing Gambits: 2.b4 and 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.b4"]
[Black "Delayed Wing Gambit: 3.b4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4
{ Another version of the Wing Gambit. With the knight already on c6, Black has to play a little differently to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.b4  . }
3... Nxb4
{ There is nothing wrong with  3...cxb4  , but I have a preference for the knight capture. }
4. c3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4
{ I think this is the most straightforward option. One could also play  5...d6  6  d5  Na5  and, with the centre closed, turn to developing the kingside. However, I would not recommend @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/P4PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d5  because of  6.exd5  Qxd5  7.Na3!  which is actually rather tricky. }
6. cxd4 e6
{ White has a fine centre, but Black has an extra pawn - and no real weaknesses. }
7. Nc3
{ Sound development. Instead,  7.d5  Qf6!  wins the rook in the corner. And @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P4PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  d5  8.e5  Nb4  grabs the important bishop as  9.Be2  Qc7  wins material. }
7... Bb4
{ I prefer rapid development over anything else, but  7...d5  , heading for a French Defence, is also possible. }
8. Bd2 Nf6
{ A provocative move, but I think it's good to put a little pressure on White's centre. }
9. Bd3 { Instead, if  9.e5  Bxc3  10.Bxc3  Ne4  is very awkward for White. }
9... O-O { The king gets out and Black can prepare to hit back in the middle. }
10. e5
{ Striking out, but Black can cope. Instead,  10.O-O  d6  11.Rb1  a5  ,  and Black is ready to play ...e5, with a strong foothold in the centre. }
10... Bxc3
{ By removing the knight on c3, Black gains control over the d5-square. } 11.
Bxc3 Nd5 { That is a beautiful piece! } 12. Bd2
{ Those bishops are strong and Black has to switch on! } 12... f5
{ Blocking out the bishop: White has to exchange off the pawn. } 13. exf6 Qxf6
{ The queen emerges onto an excellent square, looking down the f-file and attacking the d4-pawn. }
14. O-O b6
{ Once the queen's bishop emerges on b7, Black has an excellent position. The extra pawn cannot be denied. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi vs. Li, Chao, Summit Rapid 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ White is forced to make a decision about what to do with the e-pawn, and that makes it harder to build a big pawn centre with c3 and d4. }
4. Nc3 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. e5
{ Black does not need to fear this pawn push. It is worth asking the question, does e4-e5 help White's development? Actually, no! Because of that, Black is actually fine as the knight can easily re-route. }
6... Ng4 7. Bxc6 dxc6
{ Recapturing with the d-pawn makes it much easier to develop the queen's bishop. }
8. Re1 O-O 9. d3 Nh6 { A step on the journey towards the outpost on d4. } 10.
h3 Nf5
{ The knight heads for the outpost on d4, perhaps the most important idea in this variation. }
11. Ne4 b6 12. Bf4 Nd4 { The knight hits the outpost - mission accomplished. }
13. c3 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Be6
{ You will find this line in the repertoire. There are no real weaknesses in Black's position, and while the e5-pawn gives White a little space, Black always has some pressure on the d-file, so it is rarely possible to mount an attack on the kingside. }
15. Qe3 Qd5
{ Black's play is going to come down the d-file, and this provokes White into playing c4.   15...Qd7  followed by ...Rfd8 and ...a5 is also a good option. }
16. c4 Qd7 { 16...Qd4  is a good option as  17.Qxd4  cxd4  feels comfortable. }
17. Bh6 Rfd8 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Rad1 Qd4
{ Now we can see why it was pleasant for Black to provoke c4: the d4-square can be occupied. After the exchange of queens, Black can recapture with the rook and double on the d-file. }
20. Qg5 Rd7 21. Nc3 h6 22. Qg3 Bf5 23. Rd2 g5
{ This is a very important idea, ensuring that the bishop remains on an excellent diagonal, and introducing the idea of ...g4, opening the kingside. }
24. Qf3
{ After this Black takes the initiative.   White should have tried  24.Ne2  Qh4  25.Qf3  Bg6  and it is complicated:  26.Qxc6  Rad8  27.Nc1  g4  28.hxg4  Qxg4  29.Re3  Rd4  Black has decent compensation for the pawn. }
24... Qf4 25. Qxf4
{ 25.Qd1  is a better try, although  25...g4  is messy and I can understand why Vidit didn't want to go down this route. }
25... gxf4 { The d-pawn is about to fall. } 26. Ne2 Rxd3 27. Rxd3 Bxd3 28. Nxf4
Bxc4 29. b3 Bd5
{ With an extra pawn and good control in the centre, Black has a technically winning position. }
30. Rd1 e6 31. Nh5+ Kg6 32. g4 a5
{ That's it: the queenside pawn mass decides. } 33. Nf6 a4 34. h4 axb3 35. axb3
Bxb3 36. Rd6 Bd5 37. f4 Kg7 38. Kf2 b5 39. Ke3 b4 40. Rd7 Rb8 41. f5 b3 42.
Nxd5 cxd5 43. fxe6 b2 44. Rxf7+ Kg8 *

