[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Buksa, Nataliya vs. Vovk, Yuri, Lvov 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ What is this? That's not the repertoire move! I'm not changing my tune, I am not advocating  3...g6  . I'll explain why in a couple of moves... }
4. O-O Bg7
{ At this point, White can play in a far more challenging way:  5.c3  and after  5...Nf6  6.Re1  and then d4. This has a decent reputation for White and it is not easy to secure equality. Even  6.d4  ,  sacrificing a pawn for the initiative, is worth considering. However, White plays more tamely... }
5. Re1 Nf6
{ Even here, White could still transpose back into the line I mentioned in the previous note with  6.c3  . }
6. e5 Nd5 7. Nc3 Nc7 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Ne4 Ne6 10. d3 b6 11. a4 Nd4 12. h3 O-O
13. Bf4
{ By transposition, we have arrived back into one of the lines in the repertoire @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.Nc3  g6  5.e5  Ng4  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.h3  Nh6  8.d3  Bg7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Re1  Nf5  11.Ne4  b6  12.a4  Nd4  13.Bf4  @@EndBracket@@ except in this game Black's knight has taken a different route to d4. }
13... Be6 { Black's set up is very solid. } 14. Ned2
{ White hesitates and retreats the knight, but that gives Black the freedom to come forward without hindrance. }
14... Qd7 15. Qc1 f6
{ Advancing the f-pawn nearly always raises the stakes. There was a safer option:  15...Bd5  playing the bishop to the long diagonal. }
16. Bg3
{ White is spooked by Black's activity and makes another retreat. Mistake! }
16... Bh6 { A fine diagonal for the bishop. } 17. Qd1 f5
{ The f-pawn takes away the e4 square from White's pieces. Gaining ground on the kingside could well pay off for Black at some stage. }
18. Bh4 Bd5 19. c4
{ White can't stand the presence of Black's menacing pieces and decides to push away the bishop, but the c-pawn's advance creates serious weaknesses. }
19... Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Ne6
{ This is even better than exchanging knights: White remains bottled in with more pieces on the board. }
21. Bg3 Rad8 22. Ra3
{ Not a pleasant move to have to make, but it is the only way to defend the d-pawn. }
22... Bg7
{ In fact there was no need to delay:  22...g5  immediately is excellent for Black. }
23. h4
{ Perhaps Black was correct in waiting a moment: the h-pawn's advance merely weakens White's kingside. }
23... h6 { Nothing can stop the pawn advance. } 24. Bh2 g5 25. hxg5 hxg5 26.
Nd2 g4 27. Rc3 Qe8
{ Black is spoiled for choice. Moving the queen towards the kingside is sound, but it was also possible to play  27...Kf7  or  27...Bh6  . }
28. f3 Qg6 29. fxg4 fxg4 30. Ne4 Rf5 31. a5 Nd4 32. axb6 Nf3+ 33. gxf3 gxf3+
34. Bg3 f2+ 35. Kg2 fxe1=Q 36. Qxe1 axb6 37. Rb3 Bxe5 38. Qe3 Bf4 39. Qe2 Bxg3
40. Nxg3 Rg5 41. d4 Rxd4 *

