1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ Pay attention! This is not my repertoire recommendation!  3...g6  is one of the most popular moves, but I don't particularly like the main lines where White plays  4.O-O  Bg7  5.c3  , etc.  That is why I am advocating 3... Nf6.   Nevertheless, in this game White is content to play one of the milder lines, which in due course transposes to a position that can be found in my repertoire. Our move order would run:  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  g6  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.d3  Bg7  7.h3  O-O  8.Be3  b6  9.Qd2  e5  and we are back in the game here. }
4. Bxc6 { A more strategic way of playing than  4.O-O  Bg7  5.c3 } 4... dxc6 5.
d3 Bg7 6. h3 Nf6 7. Nc3 { We have transposed to lines in the repertoire. } 7...
O-O 8. Be3 b6 9. Qd2
{ In this line, White can choose between castling queenside or kingside castling. }
9... e5
{ Black takes the opportunity to clamp White in the middle of the board. } 10.
Bh6
{ By exchanging off the king's bishop, White is hoping to weaken the king's position.   10.Nxe5  Nxe4  11.Nxe4  Bxe5  The position is roughly level }
10... Qd6 { At this point the e-pawn needed protecting. } 11. O-O-O
{ With kings on opposite sides of the board, the game sharpens and both sides seek to set up an attack. }
11... b5
{ The pawn storm begins.  11...a5  ,  with the idea of pushing the pawn as far down the board as possible, also has a good reputation. }
12. g4 { White responds in kind. } 12... a5 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qg5
{ The queen heads into the danger zone, but without an open file, it's not clear how much can be achieved.   14.g5  Nh5 }
14... Re8 { The e-pawn needed defending. } 15. Ne2
{ The knight swings round to the kingside to add more firepower, but there aren't any threats yet, so it is best to continue on the queenside. }
15... a4 16. Nh4 b4
{ Black is getting closer to a breakthrough, probably with ...b3, but ...a3 could also work if the queen can gain entry. }
17. Ng3
{ White finally threatens the big check on f5, so Black's king steps back. }
17... Kh8 18. Rhf1
{ White is still looking to open a file, but Black prevents it with a nifty defensive manoeuvre. }
18... Ng8 19. Nf3
{ 19.f4?  h6  traps White's queen, which costs them a piece. } 19... h6 20. Qe3
Be6 { White has fallen back and Black takes the initiative. } 21. Kb1 Red8
{ 21...a3  22.b3   21...b3  22.cxb3  axb3  23.a3 } 22. Ne2 Kg7
{ Protecting the h-pawn allows the knight to return to activity. } 23. Nc1 Ne7
24. Nd2 g5
{ Since the attack failed to break through, White has just retreated and Black has taken the initiative - even on the kingside where the knight looks to manoeuvre to the splendid f4 square. }
25. Nc4
{ White cracks under pressure.   25.h4  f6   25...gxh4  26.Rh1  Ng6  27.g5  h5 }
25... Bxc4 26. dxc4 Qxd1 27. Rxd1 Rxd1
{ White's king is unable to escape from the back rank, thanks to the advance of the queenside pawns. }
28. a3 { 28.Qxc5  is too slow:  28...Ng6  29.Qxb4  Nf4  followed by ...Ne2. }
28... Ng6 29. Qxc5 b3 30. cxb3 Nf4 31. Qe3
{ 31.Qxe5+  Kg8  and the checks run out. } 31... axb3 32. Qxb3 Rad8
{ Ultimately White cannot prevent ...Ne2. } 33. Kc2 R8d2+ 34. Kc3 Rd3+
{ ...or the loss of the queen. Mind you, this needed to be calculated correctly in advance as a pawn race now ensues. }
35. Nxd3 Rxd3+ 36. Kc2 Rxb3 37. Kxb3 Nxh3 38. a4 Nxf2 39. a5 Nxe4 40. Kb4 Nd6
41. a6 Nc8 { Just in time. } 42. Kc5 e4 43. Kxc6 e3 44. Kb7 e2 45. Kxc8 e1=Q
46. a7 Qa1 *

