[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 Nc6 6. Be3
{ This is not the most challenging move. Black is happy to exchange in the middle anyway. }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Be2 Bd6
{ This is an important diagonal avenue for Black and it is a good demonstration of how the extra space can be used to launch a kingside attack. }
9. Nd2 O-O 10. h3
{ Not really necessary. White wants to prevent a knight moving in to g4 at a later stage, but it would have been better just to castle. }
10... Re8 11. O-O Bc7 12. N2f3 a6 13. Re1 Qd6
{ Instead,  13...Rxe3  14.fxe3  Qd6  gives Black excellent compensation for the exchange. It is hard for White to take the pressure off the dark squares. }
14. Bf1 Ne4
{ 14...Nxd4  15.Qxd4  Bf5  is a better option. It's not yet clear whether the bishop, knight or rook belongs on the e4-square. }
15. Qc2
{ White should have tried  15.g3  as  15...Nxg3  can be met by  16.Bf4! } 15...
Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bf5
{ 16...Bxh3?  17.gxh3  Ng5  18.Bg2  Nxf3+  19.Bxf3  Qh2+  20.Kf1  White survives and wins. }
17. Qa4 { 17.Qb3?  Nd2  wouldn't be too clever. } 17... Re6
{ Black's threat is ...Nd2. } 18. Qb4
{ 18.g3  Nxg3  looked scary for White, so he begged for an exchange of queens. }
18... Nd2 { Forcing liquidation into an ending. } 19. Qxd6 Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 Bxd6
{ I thought the ending should be good for me due to White's wrecked kingside pawns, but I had overlooked the next move. }
21. Be3
{ White gets quick pressure against the d-pawn to off-set the weakness of his kingside. }
21... Rae8 22. Red1 Rg6+ 23. Kh1 Bd7 24. Bg2
{ 24.Rxd5?!  Bc6  25.Rg5   25.Rf5  Re5  26.Rf4  Rh5  wins for Black.  25...Rxe3  26.Rxg6  Rxf3  27.Rg2  Rxh3+  28.Kg1  Rh6  is better for Black. }
24... Re5 25. f4 Rh5
{ White is under pressure but, with accuracy, the position is still tenable. }
26. Rxd5 Rxg2 27. Rxd6
{ 27.Rxh5  Would have led to an immediate draw:  27...Bc6  28.Rd1!  The only move that draws.  28...Rg5+  29.Kh2  Rg2+  30.Kh1  Rg5+  etc. }
27... Rg6
{ 27...Rg4  Doesn't quite force mate:  28.Kh2  and Black is in the soup. } 28.
Rxg6 hxg6
{ The ending should be drawn, but White must be a little careful due to his exposed king. }
29. Rd1
{ Accompanied by a draw offer - which gave me some hope.   29.Kg2  Bxh3+  30.Kf3  Bringing the king to the centre is best. }
29... Bxh3 30. Rd8+ Kh7 31. Kg1
{ 31.b3  Would still have been okay for White. } 31... Be6 32. Kg2
{ 32.b3?  Bd5  33.Kf1  Bf3  34.Ke1  Rh1+  35.Kd2  Rd1+  is why the pawn can't be saved. }
32... Bxa2 33. b4 Bd5+ 34. Kg3 Bc6 35. Rd1 f6 36. Kg4 Kg8 37. Kg3 Kf7
{ The ending isn't much fun for White, a pawn down and with big holes on the kingside. }
38. Bb6 g5 { Creating a two to one pawn majority. } 39. fxg5 Rxg5+ 40. Kf4 Re5
41. Bd4 g5+ 42. Kg3 Re4 43. Be3 { Losing immediately. } 43... f5 44. Bc5 Rg4+
{ White resigned because of  44...Rg4+  45.Kh2  Rh4+  46.Kg3  f4  .  One could say that I was a little lucky to squeeze a win from this position, but don't underestimate the power of Black's activity in these Isolated Queen's Pawn positions. White was under pressure, and that is when mistakes occur. }
