1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. O-O
{ This is a kind of French Tarrasch @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  c5  4.exd5  exd5  5.Ngf3  Nc6  ,  etc.@@EndBracket@@ except that in our line the pawn stands on c3, and White's knight still on b1. That gives Black a little bit more latitude to develop more aggressively than in the French. }
7... Nf6
{ Magnus plays the daring move examined in the repertoire chapters.   Instead,  7...Nge7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Nbd2  O-O  is standard and also perfectly acceptable for Black - this is one of the main lines of the French Tarrasch. }
8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nd4
{ This looks quite worrying for Black as  9...Bd7  10.Re1+  is better for White. However... }
9... O-O { This position is discussed in detail in the repertoire. } 10. Be3
{ 10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bxc6  Ng4!  is close to winning for Black. } 10... Qd6
{ A standard move for IQP positions, claiming an important diagonal towards the king.   10...Ng4  is, however, even stronger - as discussed in the repertoire. }
11. h3 { Preventing the knight from moving to g4, but weakening the diagonal. }
11... Bb6
{ Magnus immediately spies an opportunity to attack on the b8-h2 diagonal. }
12. Nd2 Nxd4
{ This ensures that Black has a clear advantage.   12...Bc7  13.N2f3  defends adequately. }
13. cxd4 { 13.Bxd4?  Bxd4  14.cxd4  Qb4 } 13... Bf5
{ The pawn structure might be symmetrical, but Black has the advantage because of his more active pieces. }
14. Nf3 Rac8 15. Bd3 Ne4
{ A great square for the knight, looming over into White's position. } 16. Qb3
{ 16.Ne5  does not have the same effect as Black can drive away the knight with ...f6. }
16... Rce8 { Black's pieces exude harmony. Beautiful classical chess! } 17. Ne5
f6 18. Nf3 g5 19. Rfc1 h5 20. Nd2 Kg7 { 20...Rf7! } 21. Bxe4 { 21.a4 } 21...
Bxe4 22. Nxe4 Rxe4 23. a4 Rf7 24. Rc8 Bc7 25. Rc1 { 25.g3  25...h4 } 25... Qh2+
26. Kf1 Bf4 { 26...Qh1+  27.Ke2  Qxc1 } 27. Qxd5 Qh1+ 28. Ke2 Qxg2 29. Kd1 Qf3+
30. Kc2 Rxe3 *

