[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7
{ This is my favourite way of tackling the Advance Variation. Black retains flexibility. But there are many good systems. At this point White has to choose which line to go for. }
6. a3
{ White would like to play, gaining ground on the queenside and shutting down counterplay.   6.Bd3  and  6.Be2  are the main alternatives. }
6... c4
{ Black prevents b4 and looks to take control of the b3 square. The position closes and the manoeuvring starts. }
7. Be2 Na5
{ I remember speaking to Lev Psakhis - former Soviet champion, renowned French player and author of the 'Complete French' - about this line. He just said, play ...Na5, ...Bc6 and ...Qd7, and Black is fine. So I did. }
8. Nbd2 Bc6 9. O-O Qd7
{ Black's strategy - to play the bishop to a4 establishing control over the queenside - is direct to say the least, but with the central pawn structure closed, it's possible. This is why it's good not to commit the queen to b6 too early! }
10. g3
{ By the way if White tries to stop ...Ba4 with  10.a4  , then  10...Ne7  with the manoeuvre Nc8-b6 and munching a4, is a nasty threat. }
10... Ba4 11. Qe1
{ The bishop on a4 cramps White's game, but it might also slide into enemy territory on c2 at some awkward juncture. Who said the light-squared bishop is a bad piece in the French? }
11... Be7
{ To prevent Nh4-g2 followed by f4, when White has managed to regroup successfully. }
12. h4 { Otherwise Black might advance with ...g5. } 12... O-O-O 13. Kg2 f5 14.
Ng5
{ This makes it easy for Black to open a file on the kingside, but the alternatives weren't terribly attractive:  14.exf6  gxf6  gives up the centre and opens the g-file. }
14... Bxg5 15. hxg5 Ne7 16. Rh1
{ If White plays  16.Nf3  , then  16...Bc2  threatening ...Nb3 is embarrassing. }
16... f4
{ This pawn sacrifice is the simplest way to open lines on the kingside. } 17.
gxf4
{ 17.Nf3  fxg3  18.fxg3  Bc2  threatening ...Nb3 and also thinking about ...Be4, is excellent for Black. }
17... Rdf8 18. Nf1 Nb3 19. Be3
{ White has to give up the exchange:  19.Rb1  Nxc1  20.Qxc1  Ng6  21.Ne3  Nxf4+  22.Kf1  Qe7  gives Black a lethal attack. }
19... Nxa1 20. Qxa1 Bc2
{ An enjoyable move to play. The bishop controls some crucial squares and threatens to join the attack. }
21. Ng3 Nf5 22. Qc1 Qa4 23. Rh3 h6
{ Time to open the kingside for the final attack. } 24. Bg4 hxg5 25. fxg5 Rxh3
26. Bxh3 Rh8 27. Qd2
{ 27.Nxf5  exf5  28.f3  Bd3  with the idea of transferring the queen to the kingside should be winning. }
27... Nh4+ 28. Kf1 Bd3+ 29. Ne2 Nf3
{ 29...Nf3  30.Bxe6+  Kb8  31.Qc1  Rh1+  32.Kg2  Rxc1  33.Nxc1  Be4  leaves Black a queen up. }
