[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 { In those days I was intent on playing the Najdorf! } 3. d4
cxd4 4. c3 dxc3 5. Nxc3 Nc6 { We have returned to the standard line. } 6. Bc4
a6
{ The key move, so that White is unable to play Nb5 when the position breaks open. }
7. O-O Nf6 8. h3
{ Such little pawn moves are hardly terrifying, but ...Bg4 was a serious threat.   If White plays the standard  8.Qe2  , Black gets an excellent game with  8...Bg4  9.Rd1  e6  10.Bf4  Qb8  Removing the queen from the d-file is sensible and sound. In fact 10...Nh5 is perhaps even stronger, as I discuss in the repertoire.  11.h3  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  Be7  13.Rac1  O-O  14.Bb3  Rc8  15.Qe3  b5  16.Bg5  Na5  0-1 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Ackermann-King, Bern 1992. Apart from the extra pawn, Black has good play on the queenside.   You'll find this line in the repertoire:  8.e5  dxe5  9.Qxd8+  Nxd8  10.Nxe5  Be6  with no difficulties. We can see the point of 6...a6: White is unable to attack with Nb5. }
8... e6 9. Qe2 Be7 10. Rd1
{ White plays the standard Morra moves, and finally there is a threat: e5. But it's easy to parry. }
10... Qc7 11. Bf4 Ne5
{ This is an important idea. Black should not fear the doubled pawns. } 12. Bb3
{ 12.Nxe5  The exchange opens the position for Black's pieces.  12...dxe5  13.Bg3  Bd7  The bishop will sit very happily on c6. The e-pawns control important squares in the centre. }
12... O-O 13. Rac1 Qb8
{ The queen removes itself from any trouble on the c-file. This is a safe square in many lines. }
14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Bg3 Nc6
{ Preempting f4 and chopping pieces - that's what you do when you have an extra pawn! }
16. Nxc6 Bxc6 { A beautiful square for the bishop. Rock solid. } 17. e5
{ White feels the need to break open the position, but Black has no real weaknesses to attack. }
17... dxe5 18. Bxe5 Qe8 19. g4 Rd8
{ Calmly preparing to exchange more pieces, getting closer to a winning endgame. }
20. Bc2 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Nd5 { Another exchange offered! } 22. Ne4
{ White wants to avoid exchanges, but that leaves Black's knight in a beautiful position. }
22... f6 23. Bg3 Kh8 24. Nd6 Qd7 25. Nc4 b5 26. Ne3 Qb7
{ White might have been regretting his decision to advance the g-pawn. Things are looking critical on the long diagonal. }
27. a3 Bc5 28. Qd3 g6 29. g5 Nxe3 30. fxe3 Qb6 31. gxf6 Bxe3+ 32. Kh2 Rxf6 33.
Qc3 Kg7 34. h4 { 34.Be5  loses:  34...Bf4+  35.Bxf4  Qf2 } 34... Kf7 35. b4 Bf4
{ White's exposed king is in desperate trouble, so he is now begging for exchanges, but the endgame is hopeless. }
36. Qc5 Bxg3+ 37. Kxg3 Rf3+ 38. Kg4 Qxc5 39. bxc5 Rc3 40. Rd6 Bf3+ 41. Kf4 e5+
42. Kxe5 Rxc5+ 43. Kf4 Rxc2 44. Kxf3 Rc3+ 45. Ke4 Rxa3
{ Three extra pawns for Black. } 46. Rb6 Ra4+ 47. Ke5 Rxh4 48. Rb7+ Kg8 49. Kf6
Rf4+ 50. Kg5 Rf5+ 51. Kg4 Rf7 { Four extra pawns. } 52. Rb6 Ra7 53. Kg5 Kg7 54.
Rb8 h6+ 55. Kf4 a5 56. Rxb5 a4 *

