[Black "Boghossian, Pierre vs. Grollemund, Bertrand, France 2004"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4
{ This is the crudest way for White to play the Grand Prix Attack. } 5... e6
{ Now that White's bishop has committed, we block it out. } 6. f5
{ The f5-pawn sacrifice has given life to the Grand Prix Attack over decades, but we know how dangerous it can be to capture, so let's develop instead. }
6... Nge7 7. fxe6 dxe6
{ By recapturing with the d-pawn, Black keeps four pawns on the kingside and that makes it difficult for White to launch a successful attack. }
8. O-O
{ In the repertoire, I give a slightly different move order for White @@StartBracket@@  8.d3  @@EndBracket@@ but the game quickly transposes. }
8... h6 9. d3 O-O 10. Qe1 g5
{ I give this as my main move in the repertoire. Black takes control on the kingside, carving out territory and giving the knight a square on g6. }
11. a3 Ng6 { Black dominates the centre and on the kingside. } 12. Nd1
{ A miserable retreat, and an indication that White has run out of ideas.   12.Be3  would have been met by the customary  12...Nd4  Perhaps the most important move in the Anti-Sicilians! }
12... g4 13. Nd2 Nce5 14. Ne3 h5 15. Rb1 Bd7
{ 15...Nxc4  16.Ndxc4  f5  was the best option, steaming forward on the kingside. The knights are very poorly placed and it is hard to see how White defends. }
16. Ba2 b5 17. b4 cxb4 18. axb4 a5 19. bxa5 Qxa5 20. Bb3
{ I feel that Black has played on the wrong side of the board: White's kingside could have been attacked. Nevertheless, Black is still comfortable. }
20... Qa7
{ 20...Nc6  Planting the knight in d4 to menace the bishop was a good option. The advantage swings back and forth over the next few moves, but Black comes out on top. }
21. Bb2 Bh6 22. d4 Nc6 23. c3
{ 23.Ra1!  Qb6  24.Rxa8  Rxa8  25.Qf2  Be8  26.Kh1⇆ } 23... Nce5 24. Ra1 Nd3
{ 24...Qb6!  25.Bc2  Rxa1  26.Bxa1  b4  would have given Black a clear advantage. }
25. Qe2
{ 25.Qb1  Bxe3+  26.Kh1  Nf2+  27.Rxf2  Qb7  28.Rxa8  Bxf2  would have left the game in balance. }
25... Ngf4 26. Rxf4 Nxf4 27. Qf1 Qb7
{ Black has a winning material advantage. } 28. Ba3 Nh3+ 29. gxh3 Bxe3+ 30. Kg2
Bxd2 31. Qe2 Bg5 32. hxg4 h4 33. Ra2 Rfc8 34. Bc5 Rxa2 35. Bxa2 Bc6 36. Kf3 Ra8
37. Bb3 Ra1 38. Qd3 Bxe4+ 39. Qxe4 Rf1+
{ Black gets there in the end, but it's a pity he didn't go for the direct kingside assault around move 15 - that feels appropriate after the kingside expansion with the g- and h-pawns. }
