1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5
{ This is the slightly more sophisticated way of playing the Grand Prix Attack. White wants to exchange on c6 and then push forward on the kingside. }
5... Nd4
{ The key move! The knight is a big presence, and if White exchanges off, Black gains a tempo as the knight on c3 is hit. }
6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 Nh6
{ Speedy development is crucial for both sides and I really like the knight on this square. Sometimes it lands on g4 to begin an attack, sometimes it lands on f5 once the e4-pawn moves. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Ng3
{ 9.d3  d5  This is the main line in the repertoire. Black threatens to play ...Qa5, winning a piece! }
9... d5
{ The pawn strikes out at White's centre. By removing the e4 pawn, Black gains a square for the knight on f5 and also rules out any chances of a kingside attack. }
10. exd5
{ 10.e5  The pawn blocks out the bishop on g7, so, quite logically, Black needs to break it down.  10...Qb6  First of all, let's push the bishop to a poor square.  11.Bd3  The bishop blocks the d-pawn making it difficult for the c1-bishop to enter the game.  11...f6  12.exf6  Rxf6  13.b3  Qd6  With pressure on the f4-pawn. }
10... Qxd5 11. Be2 Nf5
{ Centralising the knight looks very powerful, but my computer prefers  11...Qd6  12.d3  Be6  13.Bf3  Bd5  Neutralising the bishop on f3, and then attacking the c2-pawn. }
12. Bf3 Qc5 13. Ne4 Qb6 { The queen has found its way to an excellent square. }
14. Kh1 Bd7 15. g3 Rac8
{ Using the space advantage conferred by the pawn on d4, Black attacks down the c-file. }
16. c3
{ Instead, the more normal  16.d3  runs into  16...Rc7  17.Rb1  Rfc8  18.Rf2  a5  The squeeze is on. White suffers through lack of space. }
16... Rfd8
{ Compare Black's harmonious pieces with White's. There is no rush, just keep control. }
17. Qb3 Qa6 18. Re1 Be6 19. Qb4 Bd5 20. a4 Qd3
{ White's position is completely cut in two. He has no defence. } 21. Bg2 Rc4
22. Nf2 Nxg3+ 23. Kg1 { 23.hxg3  Qxg3  24.Bxd5  Rxd5  leads to mate. } 23...
Ne2+ 24. Rxe2 Qxe2 25. Bf1 Rxb4 26. Bxe2 Rb6 27. c4 d3 28. Bxd3 Be6 29. Rb1
Rxd3
{ If  30.Nxd3  Bf5  and Black will have an extra piece. How fitting that at the end White's f-pawn is left isolated and abandoned, a hopeless crumbling monument, dedicated to White's dreams of a kingside attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Varkentin, Wilgelm Wilgelmovic vs. Krassilnikov, Evgeni, Orsk 2001"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ This is the old and discredited way of entering the Grand Prix Attack. There is a reason that White normally plays  2.Nc3  and only then 3.f4 @@StartBracket@@for better or for worse@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ With this pawn thrust Black breaks up the pawn duo. White has a problem. } 3.
exd5 Nf6
{ Instead of recapturing with the queen which would waste time @@StartBracket@@  3...Qxd5  4.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@ Black is prepared to sac a pawn to speed up development. This is the reason that it is rare to see the move order 1.e4 c5 2.f4. From a positional viewpoint, the pawn on f4 is ugly on its own without the pawn on e4. }
4. Bb5+
{ 4.c4  e6  5.dxe6  Bxe6  gives Black excellent compensation for the pawn - as detailed in the repertoire. }
4... Nbd7
{ 4...Bd7  5.Bxd7+  Qxd7  6.c4  e6  is also promising, but I think by blockading with the knight, the position is more complex and there is more chance for White to go wrong. }
5. c4
{ White hangs on the pawn, but this creates serious weaknesses on the d-file. This line is addressed in detail in the repertoire. }
5... a6 6. Ba4 b5
{ It makes sense for Black to bust open the position, undermining the pawn on d5 and speeding up development. }
7. cxb5 Nb6 8. bxa6+ Nxa4 9. Qxa4+ Bd7 10. Qc4
{ White is attempting to hang on to as many pawns as possible, but this is dangerous considering his lack of development and dreadful pawn structure. }
10... e6
{ Black is better developed and has the two bishops - therefore opening the position is desirable. }
11. Nc3 exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Rxa6
{ Black is two pawns down but has a raging attack. Even the rook enters into the fun. }
14. Nf3 Re6+ 15. Kf2 Re2+
{ What a great idea. If  16.Kxe2  Bb5+  wins the queen. } 16. Kf1 Bb5
{ Even in the endgame the initiative persists. } 17. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ In practice this is incredibly difficult for White to defend. Even the computer believes that Black is better. }
18. d3 { Returning one of the pawns in order to free the bishop on c1. } 18...
Bxd3 19. Kg1 c4 { The second bishop enters the fray. } 20. h3 Bc5+ 21. Kh2 Be4
22. Rf1 Re8
{ 22...Kc8  23.Kg3  f5  is even stronger, keeping White in the box. } 23. Bd2
f5
{ 23...Bxf3  24.Ba5+  Kd7  25.Rxf3  Rxb2  is stronger. The passed c-pawn is huge. }
24. Bc3 Be3 25. Kg3 Re6 26. Rad1+ Kc8 27. Nh4 Rxg2+ 28. Nxg2 Rg6+ 29. Kh4 Bxg2
{ The king is stranded! Black just needs to give a check with the dark-squared bishop and it's all over. }
30. Be5 Bc5 31. Kh5 Be7 32. Bxg7 Bxh3 33. Rg1 Bg4+ 34. Rxg4 Rxg4 35. Rh1 Rxg7
{ With an extra piece, Black wins. } 36. Rc1 Rg4 37. Rxc4+ Kd7 38. Kh6 Ke6 39.
Kxh7 Rh4+ 40. Kg6 Rg4+ 41. Kh6 Kf7
{ A beautiful sustained initiative. This game is a warning: in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.f4  d5  , White should not be too greedy... }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Rendle, Thomas vs. Gormally, Daniel, Hastings 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This hybrid of the Rossolimo and the Grand Prix Attack has intermittent bursts of popularity. I have played it a few times, without any great conviction. }
3... Nd4
{ Black must not allow the exchange on c6, and with White's knight on c3, playing the knight to d4 is not only safe but strong. }
4. Bc4 { White can also play  4.Nf3  . } 4... Nf6
{ 5.e5  can be met by  5...d5  ,  which is more than fine for Black - an important idea that occurs a few times in the variation as a whole. }
5. Nge2 a6 { Looking to chase away the bishop and expand on the kingside. } 6.
d3
{ 6.a4  is give as the main line in the repertoire, with Black playing ...e6 and ...d5 to shut out the bishop. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 Nxb3 8. axb3 Bb7
{ Although Black is a little behind in development @@StartBracket@@on the kingside at least@@EndBracket@@ he has already bagged knight for bishop, and the light-squared bishop lines up on the long diagonal. If the diagonal opens, that bishop will have no opponent. That's why Black does not fear the pawn advance e4-e5. }
9. Bg5 { 9.O-O  is examined in the repertoire. } 9... e6 10. f4 Be7 11. O-O h6
12. Bh4 g5
{ One could also wait with  12...d6  ,  but it would be hard to resist this pawn stab, chasing down the second bishop and potentially setting up a kingside attack. }
13. Bg3 { 13.fxg5  Ng4  would have given Black a wonderful kingside attack. }
13... Nh5 14. f5 Nxg3 15. Nxg3 Bf6 16. Kh1 Qe7 17. fxe6 dxe6 18. Qh5 Be5
{ A wonderful bishop, although White can maintain some balance if he doubles rooks on the f-file. }
19. Nd1 Rf8 20. Ne3 O-O-O 21. Rab1 Bf4 22. Rf3 f5
{ With the entry of the second bishop into the attack, Black's pressure is too much and White has to give up material. }
23. exf5 Bxf3 24. Qxf3 Qb7 25. Qxb7+ Kxb7 26. fxe6 Rfe8 27. Nef5 Rxe6 28. Ne4
Kb6 29. g3 Be5 30. Kg2 g4 31. Ne3 h5 32. Ng5 Ree8 33. Nf5 c4 34. bxc4 bxc4 35.
dxc4 Rd2+ 36. Kh1 Bf6 37. h4 Re5 38. Rf1 Ree2 39. Ne3 Rh2+ 40. Kg1 Bd4
{ It took a little time to achieve, but Black gets through to White's king in the end. This is a typical fate when the f-pawn advances. }
