[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Snigurov, Maxim vs. Bakhmatsky, Vladislav, Lichess 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Be2
{ In this chapter I am examining a strange kind of Grand Prix Attack where White plays the bishop to e2. Compared to the standard GPA where the bishop is placed on either c4 or b5, this appears somewhat passive. But as we have seen, if Black is alert in those lines, in fact that bishop ends up getting pushed around or frequently redundant as Black's knight leaps into d4. So that is the rationale behind Be2: the bishop avoids trouble, and can also help secure the c2-d3-e4 pawn chain while getting on with the kingside attack  @@StartBracket@@Qe1-h4 and the traditional pawn break f4-f5@@EndBracket@@.Naturally there is a down side to it. Over the first few moves, there is next to no pressure on Black's position, so it is possible to stake a strong claim in the centre making it difficult for White to pursue the kingside attack.   I should mention that move order in this system is flexible, so one sometimes sees, for example,  2.d3  Nc6  3.f4  g6  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  which transposes to the main line of this chapter. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O
{ White is playing a typical Grand Prix Attack but without developing the queen's knight, which gives less central control. }
5... Nf6
{ Provocative. Black is not concerned about the e5 push as that break up the pawn duo, making it harder for White to push through with f5. }
6. d3 O-O 7. Qe1 d5
{ The game has transposed into a kind of Dutch Defence with colours reversed. }
8. e5 Ng4
{ We have seen this manoeuvre in the Rossolimo! The knight will spin round via h6 and then to f5. The pawn on e5 can be attacked with ...f6 to get the g7-bishop working. }
9. h3 Nh6 10. c3 f6
{ White's centre is under pressure. It is particularly difficult to defend as the pieces on the queenside have yet to enter the game. }
11. Bd1
{ A typical manoeuvre in this variation. The bishop sometimes pops out at b3. Nevertheless, it makes it more difficult to bring the queen's rook into play.   11.d4  is given in the repertoire as the main line. Not that it is a huge improvement. }
11... fxe5 12. Nxe5
{ 12.fxe5  can be met by  12...Qb6  ,  12...Bf5  ,  12...Nf7  and even  12...a5  . Your choice! }
12... Qc7
{ 12...Nxe5  is also good:  13.fxe5  Rxf1+  14.Qxf1  Qc7  with uncomfortable pressure. The pieces on the back rank don't make good viewing @@StartBracket@@for White@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Nxc6
{ This exchange makes the position even more difficult. Giving up a pawn was a better chance:   13.Nd2  Nxe5  14.fxe5  Nf7  15.d4  cxd4  16.cxd4  Qb6  17.Rf2  Qxd4  18.Nf3  Qb6  19.Be3  Qd8  20.Bd4  e6  21.Be2  For the pawn White at least has some central control. }
13... bxc6 14. Nd2 Ba6
{ Black's lead in development gives excellent chances to attack. } 15. Qe6+ Kh8
16. Bc2 Rf6 17. Qe1 Rxf4 18. Rxf4 Qxf4 19. Qxe7
{ Very risky. Which side has more pieces in play? } 19... Nf5 20. Qxc5
{ 20.Qe1  and Black has decent options but nothing absolutely clear. } 20...
Nd4
{ 20...Bd4+  21.cxd4  Qe3+  22.Kh1  Qe1+  23.Kh2  Qg3+  24.Kg1  Ne3  also wins. }
21. Nb3 { 21.cxd4  Bxd4+  wins the queen. } 21... Ne2+ 22. Kh1 Qf1+ 23. Kh2
Be5+ 24. Bf4 Bxf4+ 25. g3 Bxg3#
{ Justice was done. When White plays f4, accuracy is required, or the whole attack rebounds. In this line, it always feels that Black is ahead in development, and that is a great platform for attack. }
