[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Salcedo Tornero, Pablo vs. Rojo Huerta, Gabriel, Madrid 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. f4
{ The crudest way to play the position.  6.Be3  and  6.Nge2  are more subtle, but none of these moves should give Black sleepness nights. }
6... e6 { The first step in ensuring that White's f-pawn does not advance. } 7.
Nf3 Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. g4 { White is intent on attacking, but this rebounds. }
9... f5
{ This is the classic response. Blockading the pawn on f4 ensures that the scope of the bishop on c1 is limited. It also forces White to make a decision with the pawn on g4. }
10. gxf5 exf5
{ In this situation, the best way to recapture: keeping the pawn on g6 ensures the g-file remains blocked. }
11. Be3 b6
{ Supporting the c5-pawn in case White thinks about breaking with e5, introducing the possibility of ...d5 at a later date, and allowing the bishop to move to the long diagonal. White has a problem in the centre: if the e4-pawn ever moves, he will be left with a dreadful pawn structure. }
12. Qe1 Bb7 13. Qh4 Qd7
{ Black's pieces are harmoniously set up. It is very hard for White to generate a kingside attack. }
14. Rae1 Rae8 15. Ng5 h6 16. Nf3
{ With this little shuffle, White is obviously hoping that the g6 pawn will be weakened. Or perhaps he just ran out of ideas. }
16... Nd4
{ As usual in these Closed Sicilian positions, the knight on d4 causes problems for White. Should it be tolerated or exchanged off? }
17. Bxd4
{ Giving up the dark squared-bishop is a big concession.   17.Qf2  would protect the c2-pawn and attack the d4-knight. However, there is a good reply.  17...Ne6!  The pressure on the e4 and f4 pawns increases.  18.Qh4  b5  19.Bd2  b4  20.Nd1  Qa4  Black wins a pawn. }
17... cxd4 18. Nb1 Qc7
{ The c-file opens.   18...Qa4!  would have caused an immediate problem. } 19.
Na3 { A dreadful square for the knight, but options were limited. } 19... Qc5
20. Nd2 b5 { Dominating the knight on a3. } 21. Nb3 Qb6 22. Qf2 Kh7
{ 22...fxe4  23.dxe4  Ba6  threatening ...b4 would have been even more problematic for White. }
23. Qd2 { 23.c4  was the best chance. } 23... fxe4 24. Bxe4 Bxe4 25. Rxe4
{ Alternatively,   25.dxe4  d5!  26.e5  b4  27.Nb1  Nf5  brings the knight to e3. It is often the case that once the e- and f-pawns have been disturbed, Black finds a way in by using the f5-square. }
25... d5 26. Re2 Nf5
{ Black has a winning position. White will be unable to defend the kingside with the knights offside. }
27. Rxe8 Rxe8 28. Qa5 Qe6 29. Qd2 Ne3 30. Rf2 Qg4+ 31. Kh1 Nd1 32. Rg2 Qf3 33.
Kg1 Ne3 34. Rf2 Qg4+ 35. Kh1 b4 36. Nb5 Nxc2
{ In my experience, when White plays g4, this kind of mating attack between moves 30-40, is very common. White's king, without pawn cover, is at the mercy of Black's pieces. Compare with Black's snug king. }
