[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Biti, Ozren vs. Petkov, Vladimir, Zagreb 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. d3 Bg7 5. f4
{ White is playing a Closed Sicilian but without playing the knight to c3. He wants to be able to control the d4-square by playing c3, which also blocks the bishop on g7. }
5... d6 6. Nf3 e5 7. O-O Nge7
{ In the course I recommend  7...exf4  @@StartBracket@@see here@@EndBracket@@, but of course simple development is also sensible. }
8. c3
{ Preventing the knight from entering d4, so often a thorn in the middle for White. The disadvantage of this @@StartBracket@@from White's viewpoint@@EndBracket@@ is that there is less influence over the d5-square and the queen's knight does not have a natural square to move to. }
8... h6
{ This looks slow, but Black wants to play the bishop to e6 without allowing the knight to g5. }
9. Na3 Be6 { A great square, covering two important diagonals. } 10. Be3 exf4
11. gxf4 { If I were White, I would have preferred  11.Bxf4  . } 11... f5
{ Does this pawn structure in the middle look familiar? Have a look at the previous Closed Sicilian model game. White has a problem: if the pawn on e4 advances or captures, the pawn structure will be very shaky. }
12. Nc2 O-O 13. Qd2 Kh7 14. a3 Qd7
{ Black is able to develop solidly, there is no need to exchange on e4 yet. }
15. Qf2 Bb3
{ 15...c4  is a tempting alternative, undermining the e4-pawn, but the game continuation is nicely teasing. }
16. Rac1 b6 { By protecting the c5-pawn, Black prepares the ...d5 pawn break. }
17. Na1 Be6 18. Nc2 Rae8
{ I like Black's patience: there is no need to break in the centre until all the pieces are in play. White can do nothing constructive. }
19. Rfd1 Na5
{ The knight might hop into b3, or after an exchange of pawns on e4, perhaps c4 - all depending on how White plays. }
20. Nd2 fxe4 21. dxe4 Bg4
{ Black has taken the plunge and exchanged and now pushes the rook away from the d-file. }
22. Rf1 Bh3 23. Rfd1
{ The rook returns, but Black has gained a little time to exchange off the light-squared bishop and the pawn on e4, as well as White's king, look weaker. }
23... Bxg2 24. Qxg2 Qe6 25. Rf1 Nc4 26. Nxc4 Qxc4 27. Rce1
{ White's pawns control important squares. Black's task is to break them up. }
27... d5
{ Finally, Black achieves this pawn break. Once the e4- and f4-pawns are split, Black finds excellent outposts. }
28. e5
{ The best of the options, but still leaving Black with an excellent position. The f5-square is a strong outpost for the knight and the f4-pawn is weak.   28.exd5  Nxd5  would leave White with an isolated and doomed pawn on f4. }
28... Nf5 29. Qe2 Qa4 30. Bc1 d4 31. cxd4 cxd4 32. Qd3 Rc8 33. Re2 Rfd8
{ Black's kingside is secure and he can concentrate on pushing through the middle. }
34. b3 Qc6 35. Bb2 Bf8 36. Rc1 Qd5 37. Ne1 Rxc1 38. Bxc1 a5 39. Bb2 Bc5
{ At some point, Black is angling to sink the knight on e3. } 40. Nc2 b5
{ Black would like to play ...a4 and, if circumstances allow, sink the queen into b3 to press on the blockading queen on d3. }
41. b4 axb4 42. axb4 Bb6
{ Black is ready to play ...Qc4, so White decides to distract. } 43. e6 Qc4 44.
Ne1 Ne3
{ This is the high-point of Black's strategy - total domination in the centre. The pawn on e6 won't last long. }
45. f5 Nxf5 46. Rc2 Qxe6 47. Nf3 Ne3 48. Rf2 Qg4+ 49. Kh1 Rf8
{ Two extra pawns and the attack. It's game over. } 50. Ne5 Rxf2 51. Nxg4 Rf1+
52. Qxf1 Nxf1 53. Ne5 Ne3 54. Nd3 g5 55. Kg1 Kg6 56. Bc1 Kf5 57. Kf2 Ng4+
{ I liked Black's manoeuvring in the early middlegame, patiently building before looking to break up White's centre pawns with the pawn break ...d5. It was worth comparing this game with Salcedo-Rojo. In essence, Black's strategy is similar. }
