[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Mohammad Fahad, Rahman vs. Giri, Anish, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ Black has to be a little careful with this move order as White still has the option to play into an Open Sicilian, for example  3...g6  4.d4  , and a Dragon might not be your thing. }
3... e5 { This prevents White from going into an Open Sicilian. } 4. Bc4 Be7
{ It's important to play this before  4...Nf6  - which would allow  5.Ng5  . }
5. d3 d6 6. Nd2
{ White would like to bring the knight round to cement control over the d5 square.   6.O-O  is the other main move. }
6... Nf6 { Sensible development. } 7. Nf1
{ The knight continues on its journey. } 7... Bg4
{ This is a nice disruptive move which once again has echos of the Kalashnikov where it is a relatively common theme - in my course I describe it as 'The Poke'. The queen doesn't want to move to the awkward square d2, but advancing the f-pawn also isn't ideal as it slightly weakens the kingside. }
8. f3 Be6
{ This is the natural square for the bishop, challenging its counterpart on c4, and covering the d5-square. Anyone that plays the Kalashnikov, or indeed other variations of the Sicilian which feature a backward d-pawn such as the Sveshnikov or the Najdorf, will recognise that this is the correct spot. If White exchanges, the pawn on e6 will cover the important d5 and f5-squares. }
9. Ne3
{ The knight has finally reached its destination, taking control over the d5-square. }
9... O-O 10. Ncd5
{ White has consistently followed his plan of occupying the d5-square. In the repertoire, I give  10.O-O  Rb8  as the main line. }
10... a6 11. c3
{ If White plays  11.a4  Black can respond with the tactical  11...b5  or  11...Nb4  ,  fighting for control over the d5-square - your choice. }
11... b5 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bd5 Qd7
{ White has control over the d5-square, but Black has gained space on the queenside and has good coordination. The position reminds me of some of the Spanish Anti-Marshall systems - but a favourable one for Black. the pawn on f3 doesn't do White any favours as it prevents the queen moving there and slightly exposes Whte's king along the a7-g1 diagonal. }
14. O-O Rab8 15. Bd2 Bg5
{ Another typical Kalashnikov manoeuvre - The Breakout Bishop! Black is fighting back and will soon conquer the d5-square. }
16. Nf5 Bxd5 17. Bxg5 Be6 18. Ne3 f6 19. Bh4 d5
{ Black enjoys a huge space advantage. } 20. exd5 Bxd5 21. Bf2 Rfd8
{ Black has a stable pawn structure and pressure on the d-file. Finding counterplay is hard for White. }
22. Qe2 { 22.Nxd5  Qxd5 } 22... Bf7 23. Nc2 Bg6
{ Nice switch of diagonal. That's what you can do when you have space. } 24.
Ne1 Qd5
{ Instead,  24...Bxd3  25.Nxd3  Qxd3  26.Qxd3  Rxd3  27.Bxc5  would ease White's defensive task. Black can do so much better by holding the tension. }
25. Be3 Rb7 26. f4
{ White does not want to wait passively, but lashing out does not help. Black is well coordinated and can easily manoeuvre to take advantage of the open files. }
26... exf4 27. Rxf4 Re7 28. Qf2 Rde8
{ Coordinated rooks against split rooks. White does not stand a chance. } 29.
c4 bxc4 30. dxc4 Qe6 31. Bd2 Nd4 { Every picture tells a story. } 32. Rxd4 cxd4
33. Qxd4 Rd7 34. Qc3 Red8 35. Nf3 Rd3 36. Re1 Qd7
{ A very smooth victory. White's knight manoeuvre might look good in theory, but without a pawn break, controlling d5 in itself does not achieve too much. Giri gives an excellent demonstration of how to tackle White's control over the d5-square. }
