[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Mollema, Thomas vs. Salem, Saleh, Titled Tuesday 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2
{ White's strategy is too obvious. Once the bishop is committed to the long diagonal, Black can take immediate steps to block it out. }
3... e5 { The bishop needs to be redeployed and that takes time. } 4. Bc4
{ This is the disadvantage of advancing the pawn to e5: the king's bishop finds a good diagonal. But Black's position is solid. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. d3 g6
{ Considering that White's development is slow, Black can afford the time to play the bishop to a better square than e7. }
7. Nge2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd5
{ In practice, more people have gone for  9.f4  @@StartBracket@@who can resist a Freddie Attack?@@EndBracket@@ but as is so often the case, advancing the f-pawn rebounds: Black gets play on the central dark squares and White's king is weak - see the repertoire. }
9... Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Ne7
{ At this point White should withdraw the bishop. In that case, Black can combine two ideas: chasing down the bishop with ...Rb8 and ...b5; and playing for ...f5 @@StartBracket@@after ...Kh8@@EndBracket@@ - see the repertoire. }
11. c4 Nxd5 12. exd5
{ At this point, a couple of games have continued  12.cxd5  f5  @@StartBracket@@threatening to play ...f4 with a King's Indian style pawn storm@@EndBracket@@  13.f4  fxe4   13...Qe7  14.Qc2  Bd7  15.fxe5  Bxe5  16.Bxe5  Qxe5  17.Qc3  Rae8  with advantage to Black @@StartBracket@@Dickson-Horton, England 2011@@EndBracket@@  14.dxe4  Qe7  15.fxe5  Rxf1+  16.Qxf1  Bxe5  17.Bxe5  Qxe5  Also with advantage to Black  @@StartBracket@@Just-Engelmann, Bayern 2019@@EndBracket@@. }
12... g5
{ This was only a blitz game, but Salem understands the position perfectly: White's only active plan is to break with f4, and if that is stopped, Black can play on both sides of the board without hindrance. }
13. Ng3 f5 14. Re1 g4 15. f3
{ White decides to break up the pawns before they roll over the king, but now Black can operate on the g-file. }
15... gxf3 16. Qxf3 Qg5 17. Re2 Qg6 18. h3 Bd7 19. Rf1 Rae8
{ Notice how White cannot threaten Black's centre pawns in any way; and that means Black can build up at his leisure. }
20. Kh2 Rf7 21. Qh5 b5 22. Qxg6 hxg6
{ The endgame has not changed the assessment of the position: Black is the only one that can make the breaks. }
23. Kg1 a5
{ If White does nothing, then Black is able to switch to the queenside and play ...a4, ...Rb8 and break in to attack the d3-pawn. }
24. h4 { A slight weakness which Black pounces on. } 24... Bh6 25. h5 gxh5 26.
Nxh5 f4 { The knight is in trouble: Black threatens ...Bg4. } 27. g3 f3 28. Rh2
Be3+ 29. Kh1 bxc4 30. dxc4 Bg4 31. Rh4 Bxh5 32. Rxh5 Bd4 33. Bc1 e4
{ Simple chess. The kingside pawn storm comes good. } 34. Bf4 Rh7 35. Rxh7 Kxh7
36. Kh2 e3
{ For a blitz game, this was a very smooth operation, but a reminder that Black can often switch to a kingside pawn storm if White is careless. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Simensen, Atle vs. Stigar, Petter, Namses 1995"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. b4
{ The Wing Gambit. I'm sad to say that I have never faced this in my chess career. }
2... cxb4 3. a3 d5
{ Classical chess: strike out in the middle, particularly as White's development is actually hindered by the pawn on b4. }
4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3
{ Prudent. A game in the US Championship once continued:  5.axb4  Qe5+  and White resigned. }
5... e6
{ There are many ways to play this position, but this looks solid and sound and also protects the extra pawn. }
6. axb4 Bxb4 7. c3 Be7 8. Na3 Nc6
{ Bringing out the queen's knight protects the a7 pawn and therefore guards against White's next move. }
9. Nb5 Qd8
{ Black spotted the threat. Notice how the knight on c6 protects the a7-pawn. }
10. d4 Nf6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O
{ We have arrived at a typical 'hanging pawns' position @@StartBracket@@pawns on c3 and d4@@EndBracket@@ except White is lacking an a-pawn. Usually White attempts to start a kingside attack, but there's not much chance of that, particularly with the knight on b5 in such an odd position. }
12... b6 13. Ne5 Bb7
{ The most active square for the bishop, raking down the diagonal towards White's king. }
14. c4
{ White feels the need to claim some ground in tthe centre, but it only weakens the pawns. }
14... a6 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Nc3 b5
{ An excellent move breaking up the central pawns and giving Black a foothold on d5. }
17. Be3
{ 17.cxb5  axb5  18.Rxa8  Qxa8  retains the extra pawn with a huge advantage for Black. }
17... bxc4 18. Bxc4 a5
{ Black has a sound extra pawn and good control in the middle as the d5-square can be occupied. }
19. f4
{ White lashes out - it's funny how common the Freddie Attack is! - but it usually only serves to weaken White's king. }
19... Bb4 20. Ne2 Bd5 21. Bd3 Be4
{ Black is taking no chances and seeks exchanges. } 22. Bxe4 Nxe4 23. f5 exf5
24. Rxf5 Qd7 25. Rf4 Rae8 26. Rc1 Nf6 27. Rxf6
{ 27.Rf3  Nd5  would be gorgeous. } 27... Rxe3 28. Rf1 Rfe8 29. Ng3 g6
{ Black still has everything under control: he is well coordinated and the extra pawn is waiting in the wings. White flaps around, but it is basically game over. }
30. d5 R3e5 31. d6 Qxd6 32. Qg4 Qb6+ 33. Kh1 Qe6 34. Qf3 Qd5 35. Qf6 Be7 36.
Qa6 Bh4 37. Rcd1 Qe6 38. Rd6 Qe7 39. Qb6 Bxg3 40. hxg3 Rh5+ 41. Kg1 Re5 42.
Rdf6 Rf8 43. Qb3 Qc5+ 44. R6f2 Re3 45. Qb7 Rxg3 46. Kh2 Rg5 47. Rxf7 Rh5+
{ Told you White would regret moving the f-pawn. And probably the b-pawn too. The Wing Gambit does not have a huge amount to recommend it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Lau, Ralf vs. Gurevich, Mikhail, Bundesliga 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ Hey! I thought we were studying the Sicilian! As I discuss in the repertoire,  when Black plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  e6  , transposition into the French is possible. The position that arises later in this game could have been reached via a Sicilian move order, specifically: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.c3  e6  3.d4  d5  4.exd5  exd5  5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@a modest place for the bishop, but a move I have encountered on quite a few occasions@@EndBracket@@  6...Nf6  The best place for the knight, looking forward to the outpost on e4!  7.O-O  Bd6  8.dxc5  Bxc5  We have arrived at the Isolated Queen's Pawn position. I really enjoy playing with this structure as Black has more space than White.  9.Nbd2  The knight is heading to d4 via b3.  9...O-O  10.Nb3  Bb6  This bishop plays an important role in the game attacking on these diagonals.  11.Nbd4  Re8  The rook is beautifully placed on the open file, keeping an eye on the bishop.  12.Be3  Bg4  And this is the position that we reach in the game - via a French move order. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nf6 6. Be2 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Nb3 Bb6
9. O-O O-O 10. c3 Bg4 11. Nbd4 Nc6 12. Be3 Re8
{ The moment of transposition. I can't emphasise enough the move order is flexible for both sides @@StartBracket@@even within the Sicilian move order@@EndBracket@@, and that understanding the strategy in Isolated Queen's Pawn positions @@StartBracket@@rather than precise lines@@EndBracket@@ is fundamental for success!  Look at that rook pointing at the bishops - I would feel distinctly uncomfortable with White. }
13. h3
{ Playing these positions is difficult for White, but I would question weakening the diagonal in this way. }
13... Bh5 14. Re1 Ne4
{ Playing the knight to the outpost feels very natural, but there was already the possibility to sacrifice the exchange to weaken White's kingside:  14...Rxe3!?  15.fxe3  The h3 pushed has weakened White's kingside.  15...Qe7  It is not easy for White to defend when the dark squares are so weak. }
15. Qa4 Qf6
{ This is such an attractive spot for the queen, pressing on the d4 square and f2, as well as connecting the rooks. }
16. Qb5
{ With this queen manoeuvre, White has succeeded in putting some pressure on the d5 pawn and the b7 pawn, restricting the movement of the bishop, but Black is still very comfortably placed. }
16... Rad8
{ This maintains tension. Black could have equalised immediately by exchanging pieces:   16...Bxf3  17.Bxf3  Nxd4  18.Bxd4  Bxd4  19.cxd4  Qxd4  20.Bxe4  dxe4  21.Rad1  The game will soon burn out to a draw. }
17. Rad1 Bxf3
{ It is unusual to voluntarily give up bishop for knight, but Gurevich does so in order to bring the queen's knight into the game. }
18. Bxf3
{ Instead,  18.Nxf3  Bxe3  19.fxe3  Qe6  isn't the best pawn structure for White. Whose king is safer? }
18... Ne5
{ There is an immediate threat to take on d4 and then f3. The bishop must move. }
19. Be2
{ Instead,  19.Bxe4  dxe4  looks menacing, although White can still hold the balance with  20.Nc2  . }
19... Ng6
{ The knight swings round to the kingside. Will it land on f4 or h4? Notice that if White attempts to drive away the knight from e4 with f3, it would destabilise the bishop on e3 and weaken the g3 square. }
20. Bf1 Nf4
{ The computer disapproves of this, suggesting instead,  20...Nh4  21.a4  Qg6  threatening to take on d4 and then check on f3. }
21. Qa4 { 21.a4!  is better, threatening to push again. } 21... Re5 22. Qc2
Rde8
{ Black's line up of pieces is impressive, although for the moment, White is holding firm. }
23. Qc1 Ng6
{ 23...g5  was also possible, maintaining the knight on its active square. }
24. g3 R5e7 25. Bg2 h6 26. Rf1 Ne5
{ Playing g3 and Bg2 seemed to have strengthened White's king position, but there is a potential weakness on f3. }
27. Qc2 Nc4 { Don't those knights look beautiful! } 28. Bc1
{ The knights are great, but what can be done with them? White remains solid - so Black must remain patient. }
28... a6 29. Kh2 Qg6 { Tactics are brewing... } 30. Qd3 Ne5
{ This is a critical moment. In time pressure, White cracks. } 31. Qb1
{ Falling for a tactic. Instead,  31.Qe2  h5  looking to prise open the king, gives Black a tasty attack.   31.Qe3  would keep White in the game, but it's very uncomfortable after  31...f5  32.Kg1  Qf7  followed by ...g5 - it is a huge kingside attack. }
31... Nxg3
{ Game over. After  31...Nxg3  32.Qxg6  Nxf1+  33.Rxf1  Nxg6  Black is the exchange up with a winning position. }
